<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PresidentialSalmon     05-02 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Salmon,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maine Sea-Run Salmon May be White House Bound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His catch gave him quite a battle, but a
fisherman known as ``Salmon Bill'' landed the season's first salmon
on Maine's Penobscot River, earning him the right to offer his
prize to the president.
   Bill Ellison, 41, who lives in a tent near the river during the
May-mid-October season, caught the 25{-inch, 6-pound fish early
Monday.
   ``This fish took me out in the middle of the river three or four
times. She didn't want to come ashore no how, and it was nip and
tuck right up to the end. But she finally came in,'' said Ellison,
who was among about 100 anglers in the Penobscot near Bangor for
the opening of season.
   Within hours, the fish had been certified as a sea-run salmon
and up to standards for delivery to the White House, in keeping
with tradition.
   Maine Inland Fisheries and Wildlife Department officials were
making arrangements for a presentation later this month to
President Bush, who is a fishing enthusiast, said department
spokesman Paul Fournier.
   Ellison's offer continues a tradition that started in 1912 when
a sea-run salmon was presented to President William Howard Taft.
   Pollution of the Penobscot forced a halt to the practice during
the 1960s, but with cleanup efforts, extensive restocking, removal
of some dams and construction of fish ladders, the tradition was
revived after President Reagan was elected.
</TEXT>
