<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Letterman     05-02 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Letterman,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letterman Back In Heartland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman is taking his ``Late Night'' show
to his native Midwest for a week of ``deep-dish'' humor,
Chicago-style.
   The New York City-based show today was opening a four-day stint
at the Chicago Theater. The set will be modeled after the city's
downtown Loop district and feature a moving replica of an elevated
train in the background.
   ``The Midwest seemed a natural place for Dave,'' executive
producer Jack Rollins said Monday. ``It's almost like coming home.
... It's the center of the country _ what do they call it? The
heartland?''
   Rollins noted that Letterman is a native of neighboring Indiana.
   Producer Robert Morton acknowledged that the show has a strong
``New York feel,'' but said the host would adapt easily to the new
surroundings.
   Letterman ``very much represents the sensibility of the
Midwest,'' he said.
   Segments this week will feature a Midwestern or Chicago flavor,
such as wacky props that are ``deep-dish anything,'' Midwestern
pets performing stupid tricks and a visit to Wrigley Field that
``has something to do with the lights,'' Morton said.
   Guests include talk show host Oprah Winfrey and Chicago Bulls
star Michael Jordan. Some of the city's blues artists will perform
each night on the NBC-TV show.
</TEXT>
