<FIRST>r a PM-People-CityWolf     05-02 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-City Wolf,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ownership of Captured Wolf Tracked to `Flash Gordon' Actor Sam Jones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wolf that ran wild in a residential area
and ate a pet rabbit belongs to actor Sam J. Jones, but the ``Flash
Gordon'' star won't be getting his pet back, authorities said.
   ``We believe he purchased it as a pup from a breeder so it was
raised in a sort of domestic environment. But still, you can't have
them,'' Lt. Marshall Vernon of the city's Department of Animal
Regulation said Monday.
   The 100-pound wolf, a full-grown female named Hurricane, was
captured April 14 near the Encino Reservoir in the San Fernando
Valley.
   Residents of the hillside neighborhood had complained that a
huge white dog had been roaming the area for about two months and
gobbled down a rabbit.
   Vernon said the predator is probably an endangered gray wolf.
Its nearest wild relatives are in Alaska or Minnesota.
   In addition to starring in the 1980 movie ``Flash Gordon,''
Jones appeared in ``10'' and in the television series ``Hardcastle
and McCormick,'' ``Hunter'' and ``Highwaymen.''
   His personal manager, Stan Kamens, said he had no knowledge of
the matter and would not comment.
   Keeping wolves within city limits without a permit is a
misdemeanor punishable by up to six months in jail and a fine of up
to $500, said Lt. Fred Michael of the animal regulation department.
But he said there were no immediate plans to prosecute Jones.
   Hurricane apparently lived by hunting wild rabbits, ground
squirrels, opossums and quail in the uninhabited brush around the
reservoir, officials said.
   ``We want to give the wolf to some type of a sanctuary that can
handle that type of animal. We just don't want to send it
anywhere,'' Vernon said. ``She's not going back to the owner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
