<FIRST>u a AM-AirForceCrash     05-02 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force Crash,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>F-15 Crashes in Gulf of Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYNDALL AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force F-15 on a
training mission crashed over a target range Monday in the Gulf of
Mexico, and a search was mounted for the pilot.
   The twin-engine fighter jet went down around 12:45 p.m. EDT
about 65 miles southeast of this base on the Florida Panhandle,
said Staff Sgt. Gail Floyd of the U.S. Air Defense Weapons Center.
   Officials planned to search the area with ships overnight. If
the pilot is not found by daylight Tuesday, search aircraft will be
dispatched, Floyd said.
   The pilot, who was alone and on a student training mission, was
not identified, but it was believed he was Sean Murphy, 24.
   His father, Bob Murphy of Warsaw, Ind., said the family was
notified Monday night that his son's plane had gone down.
   ``Maybe he's just sitting in his little rubber boat, just
waiting,'' Murphy told the Fort Wayne (Ind.) Journal-Gazette. ``It
could be two or three days because the gulf's a pretty big place to
be looking.''
</TEXT>
