<FIRST>r a AM-FBI-CampusPolice     05-02 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Campus Police,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Investigating ASU Police Treatment Of Blacks After Brawl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Arizona (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is investigating allegations that
Arizona State University campus police bullied black students while
breaking up a brawl last month, officials said.
   University Police Chief Doug Bartosh said Friday that agent Dave
Small of the FBI's Phoenix bureau called him that week to tell him
his department would be investigated.
   Small said the FBI has begun an investigation into possible
civil rights violations, but would not say what the focus of the
probe was.
   ``We welcome the investigation,'' said Bartosh. ``I feel our
officers acted appropriately based on the information I have.''
   ASU police came under fire for their handling of the April 16
brawl on Fraternity Row in which an unruly group of white students
began yelling racial slurs at four black students who drove into
the conflict.
   While trying to break up the fight, police handcuffed Robert
Rucker and James Liddell, both 20-year-old members of the
university track team. Rucker and Liddell were put in patrol cars
and taken to campus police headquarters.
   Rucker said that when he and Liddell complained the handcuffs
were too tight, one officer said, ``Next time, I'll put them on so
tight they'll make you cry.''
   The allegations of rough treatment resulted in three days of
protests by minority students and a promise by ASU administrators
to take steps to reduce racism on campus.
   Small said the FBI investigation could take several months to
complete.
</TEXT>
