<DOCNO> AP890502-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay 4thLd-Writethru a0741 05-02 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0741,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Candidate Routs Opponents in Paraguay Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with Rodriguez claiming victory,
updated vote tallies. Picks up 15th pvs, `Election observers ...' ^LaserPhoto
ASU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who ousted
Alfredo Stroessner and his 34-year dictatorship three months ago,
routed seven other candidates in presidential elections Monday,
unofficial returns showed.
   Opposition candidates denounced ``numerous and serious''
irregularities in the balloting, but by late Monday evening had not
withdrawn from the election or challenged the early results. One
opponent conceded.
   ``We promise our people we will carry Paraguay on a bright path
to its destiny of greatness and happiness,'' Rodriguez told
cheering party members at his home Monday night as he lifted a
glass of champagne in a toast.
   Official returns had not been disclosed nearly eight hours after
polls closed but unofficial tallies by Rodriguez' ruling Colorado
Party as well as by the Christian Democrats and the political
science group CEPES showed the general won by an overwhelming
majority.
   Domingo Laino of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party and the
presidents of three other opposition parties denounced ``serious
deficiencies'' in the balloting. They refused to concede, but did
not withdraw.
   According to the Colorados, Rodriguez received 576,312 votes of
772,785 cast for president, or 74.5 percent. The closest
challenger, Laino, garnered 158,851 votes or 19.94 percent.
   The votes represented nearly more than a third of the 2.2
million people on official voter registration lists. Non-Colorado
candidates have complained that the list was out of date and
bloated, and even the Central Electoral Board said the list might
contain 600,000 duplicate or non-existent names.
   The Colorado Party, one of eight parties that submitted slates
of candidates for Congress, said it garnered 552,542 votes for
Congress out of 743,150 votes cast, or 74.4 percent. It said
Laino's party received 148,202, or 19.9 percent.
   The Colorados would thus, by law, receive 24 of the 36 Senate
seats and 48 spots in the 72-seat Chamber of Deputies.
   Rodriguez, 65, an army general and longtime aide to Stroessner,
dissolved Congress after leading the Feb. 3 coup that ended nearly
35 years of Stroessner rule. He served as provisional president
since then. Stroessner also belonged to the party, which has been
in power since 1947.
   Turnout appeared high across this landlocked South American
nation of 4 million, despite cloudy skies, light rain and cool fall
weather.
   Diplomats and foreign observers said the balloting and vote
count were reasonably fair and Rodriguez clearly won.
   ``I think it was a very good attempt at something they have
never done before,'' said British Ambassador John Grant McDonald.
   Presidential candidate Carlos Ferreira Ibarra of the Liberal
Party acknowledged that Rodriguez won.
   Laino, a former exile, said earlier Monday that the voting
irregularities were ``numerous and serious. We do not have all the
information, but the irregularities exceeded our expectations.''
   Election observers and party officials said not every citizen
was able to vote in private; ballots of opposition parties were
stolen and so not available at election tables; indelible ink was
not always used to prevent multiple voting, and the government
added voters to the official list after the registration period
ended three weeks ago.
   Euclides Acevedo, president of the Revolutionary Febrerista
Party, said ballots for his party were stolen at several voting
stations by Colorado supporters ``who simply put them in their
pockets.''
   But Fernando Vera, the party's presidential nominee, said the
four opposition parties were not about to withdraw from the
election.
   ``Why the obsession about withdrawing?'' Vera asked a reporter.
``No one has to withdraw from the process. ... What must be done is
determine on the basis of results if the fraud ... was significant
in its entirety or not.''
   Government and Colorado Party officials denied irregularities
were widespread, organized by them or influenced the outcome.
   Paraguayans seemed to accept as unavoidable one more general in
the National Palace and the Colorados once more in control of
congress, given the suddenness of elections following a long
dictatorship.
   ``My party was founded in 1965. This is the first time we're
participating in elections,'' said Martin Caceres, 28, a Christian
Democrat.
   ``People are hopeful,'' he said, standing in a school courtyard.
``The period of Stroessner hasn't ended ... but this is a
beneficial transition _ peaceful, with people getting used to
democracy.''
   In Coronel Oviedo, a large rural town 80 miles east of the
capital city of Asuncion, peasants traveled along muddy roads to
voting stations by flatbed truck, horse, bicycle and tractor.
   ``The last time I voted was in Stroessner's second
re-election,'' in the late 1960s, said Dario Benitez, 60. ``Then I
quit because I didn't like him anymore.''
   Since becoming provisional president, Rodriguez has criticized
the former regime, permitted banned newspapers and political
parties to operate and mended fences with foreign governments and
the Roman Catholic Church. Prominent Stroessner aides and ministers
have been arrested.
   Stroessner, 76, lives in exile in Brazil.
</TEXT>
