<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bob Hope helped open
Disney-MGM Studios' new $400 million theme park, capping a
star-studded weekend of parties and previews.
   ``It's the largest theme park run by actors, or cartoon
characters, unless you want to count Washington, D.C.,'' joked Hope.
   Hope joined Disney Chairman Michael Eisner in opening day
ceremonies Monday on an outdoor stage in front of a re-creation of
Grauman's Chinese Theater on Hollywood Boulevard. The 135-acre
complex combines filmmaking with backstage studio tours and
attractions like the Indiana Jones Epic Stunt Spectacular theater
show.
   ``The world you have entered was created by the Walt Disney
Company and is dedicated to Hollywood ... a world that never was
and always will be,'' Eisner told the crowd.
   The grand opening followed a weekend of festivities, including a
Saturday night gala in which 40 movie and television stars paraded
down the park's Hollywood Boulevard in vintage automobiles. Among
them were Bette Midler, Lauren Bacall, George Burns, Audrey
Hepburn, Betty White and Kevin Costner.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American rockers Bon Jovi and
Motley Crue will join West German and Russian bands in Moscow this
summer in a benefit concert for drug abuse programs on both sides
of the Iron Curtain.
   West Germany's Scorpions and the Russian ensemble Gorky Park
will share the stge with the two U.S. hard-rock groups at Lenin
Stadium on Aug. 12-13 for the ``Moscow Music and Peace Summit,'' it
was announced Monday. Proceeds will go to drug- and alcohol-abuse
programs in the United States and in the Soviet Union.
   ``There is really a very big problem in the Soviet Union with
drugs and alcohol,'' Gorky Park's Sasha Minkov said at a news
conference. ``Maybe not so much with drugs, as in the United
States, but alcohol for sure.''
   ``This is something we really think is going to make a
difference. The youth is tomorrow's leader,'' said Jon Bon Jovi, an
admitted former drug user.
   The groups and other rock artists including Ozzy Osbourne and
Skid Row also will issue a related studio album in August. The
album will feature new renditions of songs by groups who have lost
a member to substance abuse, such as the Sex Pistols and The Who.
   Portions of the concert will be shown in the United States on
Showtime Event Television on a pay-per-view basis. The Westwood One
radio network will carry the Aug. 13 show live.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian-born gymnastics guru Bela Karolyi can
pack a U.S. passport on his next international coaching tour. He's
now a citizen.
   ``It's a great moment and I'll never forget it,'' said Karolyi,
46, who guided Mary Lou Retton and other young Americans to Olympic
fame after defecting eight years ago. ``Now, I am an American.''
   Karolyi, his 46-year-old wife and fellow coach, Marta, and
daughter, Andrea, 15, were among 1,201 people who became citizens
in a ceremony Monday.
   ``My students are the ones who are representing the whole
American young generation and, along with them, I would like to
step on that floor not just as a professional coach but as an
American citizen,'' he said.
   Karolyi, who coached Olympic gold medalist Nadia Comaneci of
Romania, defected in March 1981 while on a tour of 15 American
cities with the Romanian team. But the usual five-year citizenship
process stretched to eight after immigration officials twice lost
the Karolyis' paperwork.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' star Robin Williams
has married his girlfriend, the former live-in nanny of his son.
   Williams, 36, married Marsha Garces in a private ceremony in
Lake Tahoe attended by a few close friends, his publicist, Mark
Rutenberg, said Monday. Miss Garces is believed to be in her late
20s or early 30s.
   Williams, whose credits including television's ``Mork and
Mindy'' and the movie ``The World According to Garp,'' met Miss
Garces five years ago when he and his former wife, Valerie Velardi
Williams, hired her as a nanny for their son, Zachary.
   Williams and his former wife, who filed for divorce last year,
share custody of the boy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court has upheld most of a
divorce judgment against comedian Joe Piscopo, frustrating his
effort to gain custody of his 10-year-old son.
   A three-judge panel Monday rejected Piscopo's argument that his
ex-wife should not have been allowed to move from New Jersey to
Florida with their only child.
   The judges also upheld the awarding of $500,000 in joint assets
to Nancy Piscopo Hayes and an additional award of $50,000, which
was half the value placed on Piscopo's celebrity status.
   The court also said it wasn't unreasonable to require the actor
and former ``Saturday Night Live'' regular to pay $40,000 a year in
child support to his ex-wife.
   Mrs. Hayes has remarried since the 1988 divorce decree.
   Attorney Francis Donahue said he would discuss with Piscopo
whether to appeal the case to the state Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Lionel Richie and his wife,
Brenda, have pledged $500,000 to Tuskegee University to endow a
chair in at their alma mater's business school.
   Richie, who won an Academy Award for ``Say You, Say Me,'' plus
numerous Grammy and American Music awards, is a graduate of
Tuskegee's business school. Brenda Richie has a social work degree
from the Alabama school's arts and sciences college.
   The endowment represents ``the Richies' genuine commitment to
intellectual development in general and the special mission of
historically black institutions and the people they serve,''
Tuskegee President Benjamin F. Payton said in a statement released
Friday.
   The Lionel and Brenda Richie Chair is the first of its kind at
the university, Payton said.
