<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-02 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans sipped champagne and led cheers in
Greek as St. John's College won its only official intercollegiate
athletic event, defeating the U.S. Naval Academy at a day-long
croquet tournament.
   The 6{-hour match, played Sunday after rain postponed it for a
day, ended with the home team capturing the ``Annapolis Cup.''
   The music of Vivaldi and Beethoven filled the air and some
spectators alternated between watching the game and reading George
Orwell's ``Down and Out in Paris and London.''
   The croquet tournament is not so much an athletic event as a
chance for neighboring schools that normally have little contact to
have a little fun together.
   While the academy turns out naval officers drilled in tactics
and terminology, St. John's produces a small crop of literary
scholars versed in Shakespeare and Socrates.
   Members of the two teams planned to meet later this week at a
restaurant where the tournament trophy is kept. ``I see that as a
step forward in the Midshipmen-Johnnie relationship,'' said George
Turner of the St. John's team.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lost little kittens may owe their lives
to a shop owner who stopped by his store to check on something, and
heard tiny meows inside the wall.
   Kevin Squitieri, 41, grabbed a sledge hammer Sunday and whacked
a couple of holes in the wall at Bay Windows, a window and
construction material store.
   Out came two blue-eyed kittens, one black, the other black and
white.
   Squitieri said the mother cat probably crawled into the attic of
his store to give birth, and the kittens apparently fell down
inside the wall.
   Saving the kittens was worth the $100 damage to his shop, he
said.
   ``They're cute as a button,'' he said. ``When I pulled them out
my heart felt good.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Green Bay Packers Coach Lindy Infante is
better known in that city than Police Chief Howard Erickson,
according to a telephone name recognition survey by the Green Bay
Press-Gazette.
   While all 35 respondents knew Infante's occupation, only eight
recognized Erickson. Residents were asked by telephone to identify
Infante, Erickson and eight other personalities.
   ``Obviously those were law-abiding citizens,'' said Erickson.
``I'm not concerned as long as the paymaster, my wife and my
children weren't among those who said they don't know me.''
   Having a football team with a 4-12 record last season is enough
to make any coach recognizable, Infante said.
   ``They're going to know who you are. They want to know who the
fool is who did this to their football team,'' Infante said.
</TEXT>
