<FIRST>r i PM-MonkeyBusiness     05-02 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Monkey Business,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monkeys Spark Panic During a Break From Confinement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten monkeys enjoyed a bit of freedom when a
zookeeper at a park near Tel Aviv tried to please a group of
squealing children by opening the animals' cage.
   One monkey hitched a ride by jumping on the head of a boy riding
a bike then bit a zoo attendant in the hand before being recaptured
at the Rishon Letzion Zoo, animal keeper Charlie Zeitun said on
Israel radio.
   Two hours passed Sunday before all the creatures were back in
the cage, Zeitun said.
   ``Open it, open it, we want to see the monkeys,'' a group of
children yelled at him, Zeitun said. ``So I opened the inner door
to the cage. I didn't notice that the outer door wasn't locked.''
   But the monkeys did, and made a quick dash for freedom.
   The last monkey captured was the largest. Sandak, Hebrew for
``godfather,'' spent two hours scampering through the park and
chasing after children, Israel radio said.
   A police official in Rishon Letzion confirmed the monkey escape
and said the animals were about 20 inches in length, but could not
identify the species.
</TEXT>
