<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Taxes Bjt   05-02 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Taxes, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Next Year Could be Saying `Don't Read my Lips'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush vowed ``read my lips: no new
taxes'' all through his presidential campaign but never indicated
for how long the message would be displayed there.
   Administration officials now are reluctantly conceding that Bush
may only stick to the pledge for a year, and that higher taxes may
be part of a fiscal 1991 budget agreement.
   One possibility actively being considered is a swap trading
White House support for some new taxes, most likely on gasoline,
for concessions from Congress in other areas, like a cut in the
capital gains tax rate, said the sources, speaking on the condition
of anonymity.
   Bush has long made chopping the capital gains tax rate a key
item, claiming it will eventually raise revenue for the Treasury.
But it has found scant support in the Democratic controlled
Congress, which questions the logic of trying to raise revenue by
cutting taxes.
   Despite Bush's rhetoric against new taxes, reiterated as
recently as Monday in a speech to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
many economists say higher taxes seem all but inevitable to get the
federal deficit _ estimated at $163 billion this year _ under
control.
   In fact, to many analysts, it was only a matter of time before
the administration conceded that some forms of tax hikes were
needed.
   Administration officials still haven't done this publicly. But
privately they admit contingency planning is under way on new taxes
_ and on what tradeoffs the administration might be able to wrest
from Congress in exchange for White House support for them.
   Even the no-new-taxes budget compromise Bush recently reached
with Congress for fiscal year 1990 calls for $5.3 billion in
unspecified new revenues.
   Bush has claimed that slashing the capital gains tax from the
present 28 percent to 15 percent will produce the bulk of this,
$4.8 billion. But since Congress seems unlikely to go along with
this tax cut, some way must still be found this year to come up
with the $5.3 billion.
   And, a weakening economy could make the projected 1990 deficit
even larger than the $98.6 billion Bush projected in his budget
submission to Congress _ meaning even more ``new revenues'' will be
needed to meet deficit targets of the Gramm-Rudman law.
   That budget-balancing act requires a deficit of no more than
$100 billion in fiscal 1990 _ or automatic across-the-board cuts
are triggered.
   Budget Director Richard Darman will issue revised economic
assumptions on the economy on July 15.
   Some administration sources suggested that a
gas-tax-for-capital-gains-cut deal might even be considered as
early as then, if the new economic numbers prove to be gloomy.
   But generally, administration officials said the president's
clear intention was to honor his campaign vow through this year.
   After that, all bets are off.
   Bush on Monday showed no indication he was ready to make a deal,
however. In his speech to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, he said:
``I mean to live by what I've said: No new taxes.''
   Bush told the Chamber of Commerce, ``We don't have to raise
taxes. We have to release the energies of free enterprise.'' He
said his ``favorite source of new revenue'' was the capital gains
tax cut.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Monday, ``We
are talking to the tax-writing committees about it (the capital
gains tax cut). But we wouldn't want to speculate on how it might
come out at this time.''
   The notion of a deal trading support for higher gasoline taxes
for a cut in the capital gains tax was first raised the weekend
before last in a session between Bush and a group of economists at
the presidential retreat in Camp David, Md.
   Although Bush was generally noncommittal, he did not object to
discussing possible higher taxes, and the proposed swap was
endorsed by some of the economists present, according to the
sources.
   The federal gasoline tax is now 9.1 cents per gallon.
   There have been a variety of congressional proposals for raising
the gasoline tax for amounts ranging from a few cents up to 50
cents a gallon. However, a major obstacle to any such rise is the
opposition of Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
