<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Gaal     05-02 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Gaal,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Photographer Found Dead In Thai Resort Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Gaal, a Canadian photographer who
covered the war in Afghanistan as a stringer for The Associated
Press, was found dead at a Thai resort hotel, officials said today.
He was 29.
   Gaal's body was found about 1 p.m. Sunday at the bottom of the
swimming pool at the Ocean View Hotel in the Pattaya resort, 70
miles south of Bangkok, said the hotel's assistant manager, Viroj
Phunpiriyat.
   Viroj said Gaal had gone swimming in the pool alone at about 1
a.m. Sunday after having had some drinks. A large amount of
marijuana and other drugs were found in his room, Viroj said.
   Foul play was not suspected, Viroj said.
   The body was taken to a police forensic institute in Bangkok
where an autopsy was to be peformed, said Nipha Kietniyom,
assistant consular officer at the Canadian Embassy.
   Gaal, from Kelowna, British Columbia, was vacationing in
Thailand.
   Gaal was born in Fernie, British Columbia. Starting in 1978, he
was a staff photographer for the Kelowna Daily Courier. From 1983
to 1985 he was chief photographer for the Lethbridge Daily Herald
in Alberta.
   Gaal made his first trip to Afghanistan in 1984 and did a photo
series on the war. In 1985 and 1986, he worked for the
Toronto-based Fotopress News Service covering the Middle East and
Asia.
   He returned to Pakistan in 1986 and since made several trips
into Afghanistan with the Moslem guerrillas fighting the pro-Soviet
government.
   Since September 1987 he had worked as a news and photo stringer
for the AP based in Peshawar, Pakistan.
   ``He took some of the AP's most startling and dramatic photos of
the war in Afghanistan,'' said Bryan Wilder, the AP's chief of
bureau in Pakistan. ``He was a mellow, quiet fellow who seemed to
be fearless when in combat situations.''
</TEXT>
