<FIRST>r w PM-EmployeeBenefits     05-02 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Employee Benefits,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Delays Enforcing Health Insurance Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is delaying the
deadline for employers to begin using complex tests to prove that
their health insurance plans do not discriminate against lower-paid
workers.
   The testing requirement, enacted at the request of the Reagan
administration as part of the 1986 tax overhaul, imposes an
unreasonable compliance burden on business, Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady said.
   He chose a meeting of business executives at the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce on Monday to announce, ``We have ordered a delay until
Oct. 1 in the beginning date for ... testing plans for compliance
with (Internal Revenue Code) Section 89 regulations.''
   The audience, which has made repeal or modification of the law a
major goal, applauded loudly.
   Brady said the goal of the legislation _ to ensure that
tax-deductible fringe benefits are distributed equitably among
workers _ was a good one. ``A system that differentiates between
people in the matter of health benefits subsidized by the taxpayers
cannot be sustained,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, the cost of compliance is excessive, Brady said.
``The law needs to be changed and we stand ready to encourage,
support and work with Congress to revise and improve it.''
   More than half the members of the House and a large number of
senators are sponsoring bills to repeal the provision or change it
significantly. The House Ways and Means Committee, whose chairman
and most of its members are sponsoring one modification bill, was
holding hearings on the subject today.
   The law requires employers to conduct a lengthy series of
complex tests to demonstrate that employee benefits, especially
health insurance, are not weighted against workers making less than
$50,000 a year.
   Paperwork required by the law is so voluminous that some
employers are threatening to withdraw health insurance coverage for
all employees.
   The Section 89 rules went into effect on Jan. 1, but the IRS
freed employers from any significant compliance requirements until
July 1 and agreed that no employer would be penalized if a
good-faith effort to follow the rules was made the remainder of
1989.
   The federal government forgoes more than $30 billion a year in
taxes on the value of employer-financed health insurance. The
employer deducts the cost as a business expense and the employee
excludes the value from taxable income.
   Under the Section 89 law, highly compensated employees may be
subject to taxation on the excess coverage if their health plan is
more valuable than is offered to rank-and-file workers.
   Under the House substitute plan, employers that provide a health
plan would have to offer coverage costing workers $10 a week or
less ($25 or less for a family plan) to 90 percent of employees.
Higher-paid workers would be taxed on the value of coverage that
was better than that provided other employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
