<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     05-02 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Focuses on Use of US-Banned Pesticides on Imported Fruit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee this week will be
examining whether Americans are getting imported produce sprayed
with U.S.-made pesticides that are outlawed for use here.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., who chairs the subcommittee on
environment, energy and natural resources, said he is concerned the
Environmental Protection Agency isn't adequately informing other
countries about the chemicals they're buying from American
companies to enhance crop production.
   ``Many of these countries do not have the resources or
information needed to ensure that pesticides are used safely,''
said Synar.
   He said they need help developing regulations and they need
information.
   ``They're not getting enough of either,'' he said.
   Synar noted that pesticide exports have increased and so have
foreign food imports.
   He said his subcommittee, which will hold a hearing on the issue
Wednesday, will review EPA's efforts to protect American consumers
from imported food contaminated by pesticides which are prohibited
from use domestically.
   Jay Vroom, spokesman for the National Agricultural Chemicals
Association, said some of the pesticides that are exported are
unregistered here because they are designed to combat insects that
exist only in the climate of the foreign country.
   But he said it is in the best interests of the industry to have
as much information available to buyers as possible.
   ``We support access to information, delivery of information and
delivery of educational packages that do some good, not just arrive
on a dock somewhere,'' said Vroom.
   He said his organization has conducted educational programs on
pesticide use for foreign buyers.
   Through the United Nations, efforts are under way to develop an
international system of pesticide information exchange and export
notification, said Synar.
   ``Adoption of a system of prior informed consent is an important
first step toward improving the information base for many
countries,'' he said. ``However, our current notification system
must be improved.''
   EPA attorney Bob Perlis said federal law requires that companies
planning to export unregistered pesticides obtain a signed
statement from the foreign buyer saying the buyer understands that
the pesticide is not allowed to be sold in the United States.
   ``A copy of that statement is then sent to a representative of
the foreign country's government,'' said Perlis.
   He said the registration of pesticides is canceled from time to
time by the EPA and, when that happens, countries that have
purchased the product are notified the reason for the cancellation.
   ``There is not a pesticide product produced in this country
which could not be exported (under the law),'' said Perlis.
   Over the past decade, global pesticide use has doubled, said
Synar.
   The United States is a major pesticide producer, supplying about
one-quarter of the world market, he said, adding that about 25
percent of the U.S. pesticide exports are unregistered.
   Garry Hamlin, spokesman for Dow Chemical Co., said his company
follows the law explicitly.
   He also said, ``We do not ship banned products or products that
are severely restricted to other countries _ which is not to say we
do not ship products that are not registered in the United States.''
   He said Dow is seeking registration on a number of products that
are not registered here.
</TEXT>
