<FIRST>r w PM-TransitionSpending     05-02 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transition Spending,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Spends Just Two-Thirds of Money Earmarked For Transition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, who received $3.5 million to
make the transition from candidate to president between his
election and inauguration days, has returned more than a third of
the money to the Treasury.
   Bush spent $2.21 million to facilitate his entry into the
nation's highest office and returned $1.29 million to the
taxpayers, according to the final balance sheet released Monday.
   Under a new federal law, Bush had been allocated $1.5 million
more than former President Ronald Reagan to make the transition
into office, according to Raymond A. Fontaine, comptroller of the
General Services Administration, which administers transition
accounts. But the increase also tightened regulations for reporting
private sector donations.
   Bush raised no private money, said Fontaine, who has headed the
financial aspects of the transition process since Lyndon B. Johnson
left the White House in 1969.
   ``This was squeaky clean. No outside money, no outside gifts,''
Fontaine said. ``The Bush people refused to take free IBM
typewriters or free General Motors rental cars. The Reagan people
took lots of freebies.''
   The president spent his transition funds primarily on salaries
of the people who assisted in his smooth passage to a new
administration, said Fontaine.
   Bush employed 225 people, compared with the 400 government
employees Reagan used for the same purpose in 1981. Reagan spent
more than $1.7 million for transition, according to Fontaine.
   ``This was a much slimmer transition than Reagan had,'' said
Fontaine. ``Smaller people, smaller money. They seem to be a little
obsessed with this whole ethics thing.''
   The transition allocation for outgoing presidents to spend over
the six months after leaving office was increased from $1 to $1.5
million under the new law, Fontaine said. Reagan's activities have
included setting up the Reagan presidential library.
</TEXT>
