<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Cafes     05-02 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Cafes,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cafes Replace Parades In May Day Celebrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-May Day-Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man peering through the window of the
cafe Nowy Swiat thought only specially invited people were allowed
to share their thoughts with the government ministers inside.
   No, no, he was assured by another onlooker, anyone could go in.
   ``Well then, I'd like to give them a piece of my mind,' he said,
pulling open the cafe door.
   In May Day celebrations Monday meant to stress the new wave of
reform in Poland, the communist government replaced the traditional
parade with a rally.
   And it organized ``kawiarnias,'' meetings at Warsaw cafes at
which ordinary citizens could exchange views with ranking officials.
   The sessions were held in several of the coffee-and-cake shops
along New World Street, a restored stretch lined by historic
buildings.
   The street was closed to cars and dotted with ice cream vendors
and concert stands for the day.
   The government ministers, who stood in front of bars and cabaret
stages in the smoke-filled cafes, talked about politics, economics
and other issues with standing-room-only crowds that sat at tables
and packed every corner of the columned rooms.
   Among them was Deputy Prime Minister Ireniusz Sekula, former
government spokesman Jerzy Urban, sports minister Aleksander
Kwasniewski and Alfred Miodowicz, leader of the official union
alliance OPZZ.
   But as Politburo member Stanislaw Ciosek took questions and even
fended off hecklers at the cafe Nowy Swiat, the new spirit of
democracy was being tested on the street as riot police clashed
with young protesters.
   Ciosek's give and take _ ``We are entering a completely new
state of things,'' he told one questioner _ was interrupted by
shouts from outside.
   The crowd rushed out to see a row of shield-carrying, helmeted
riot police who had closed the street after a clash with
demonstrators during which rocks and smoke bombs were thrown.
   The protesters, young militants who had wandered over from the
day's huge Solidarity march, fled after being charged by police.
</TEXT>
