<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-02 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Rise, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange increased
steadily to another record high Tuesday, while the dollar fell
slightly against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 33,954.99, up
161.82 points, or 0.48 percent. It was the third straight day of
trading the stock market's main barometer set historic high levels.
   The dollar, after opening Tuesday at 133.75 yen, rose 0.10 yen
to 133.85 by the day's close, down 0.05 yen from Monday's close of
133.90 yen. It moved Tuesday between 133.65-134.05 yen.
   A dealer at Sumitomo Bank said the currency market was ``holding
steady,'' and dealers were holding back in reaction to Monday's
high dollar and in anticipation of Bank of Japan intervention next
week.
   ``Today's calm in the market primarily reflects dealers stepping
back after yesterday's heavy trading,'' he said.
   On the stock market, dealers cited light trading without any
particular market-affecting news other than the approach of three
consecutive holidays, beginning Wednesday. Tokyo markets will close
Wednesday and reopen Monday.
   Dealers indicated there was significant buyer interest in steel
issues, however.
</TEXT>
