<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IceClassic     05-02 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ice Classic,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spring Arrives In Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NENANA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's annual rite of spring _ waiting
for the ice to melt in the Tanana River _ is over, and four of
150,000 bettors predicted the time to the minute.
   The 73rd annual Nenana Ice Classic, held 50 miles southwest of
Fairbanks in one of the state's coldest areas, is watched statewide
as a harbinger of warmer weather.
   A tripod on the ice is connected by a cable to a clock on shore.
When the ice thaw moves the tripod a certain distance, the cable
stops the clock.
   The tripod toppled over early Monday and moved 30 feet when a
downstream ice jam dislodged, but it wasn't until 8:14 p.m. Monday
that the tripod finally tripped the clock.
   Manager Wayne Taylor said four tickets had 8:14 p.m. on May 1 as
the time the ice would go out. They were bought by Doris Craig,
Michelle Phillips and Dennis Starr of Anchorage and a pool of
bettors in Fairbanks.
   The winners will divide $135,000 in prize money, Taylor said.
   About 150,000 tickets were sold at $2 apiece. The rest of the
money is spent on the contest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     05-02 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ultra-Nationalist Extremists Attack Country's Largest Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese militants early today
attacked the country's largest army garrison with grenades and
automatic rifles but were beaten back before they could reach the
armory, a military official said.
   At least three militants were killed and five soldiers wounded
in the raid, which was launched during a heavy downpour at 1:30
a.m., said the official, who cannot be identified under briefing
rules.
   He said at least 100 militants attacked the Panagoda army
garrison, 12 miles southeast of Colombo, which usually holds
between 10,000 and 15,000 soldiers.
   The attack was the biggest raid on an army post by the militants
since they launched an anti-government campaign in 1987 to protest
peace overtures to ethnic Tamil rebels.
   The Sinhalese extremists contend the Sinhalese-dominated
government of this Indian Ocean island nation is making too many
concessions to the Tamil minority.
   The militants have attacked army camps and police stations in
the past to get weapons. The military official said the attackers
penetrated the Panagoda garrison's perimeter and came within yards
of its armory before being repulsed.
   Army helicopters and foot patrols searched rice paddies and
jungles around the camp for the militants, many of whom are
believed to be injured, he said.
   He said authorities thought the attackers belonged to the
People's Liberation Front, an ultra-nationalist Sinhalese group.
   The government has blamed the front for the killings of at least
3,000 people, mostly government officials and supporters, since Sri
Lanka signed a peace accord in July 1987 aimed at ending a Tamil
insurrection that started four years earlier.
   The largest Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, also rejected the 1987 peace accord but opened talks with
the government last week.
   The talks were held after President Ranasinghe Premadasa offered
amnesty and seats in Parliament to the rebels and the Sinhalese
militants. The Sinhalese radicals rejected the government's offer.
   Sinhalese form 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 18 million people, and
Tamils make up 18 percent.
</TEXT>
