<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay-Peasants     05-02 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay-Peasants,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peasants Believe Voting Could Mark Start Of New Era</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Paraguay-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORONEL OVIEDO, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer proudly displayed his
calloused right index finger, stained with the purple ink designed
to ensure that no voter cast more than one vote.
   In his 60 years, Pablo Caballero has known little but
dictatorship and seen few elections that were not fixed. He said
his ink-stained finger represented the hope of change.
   ``Now we can vote freely for our own candidate with no rushing
or pressures,'' said Caballero, a feeling expressed Monday
throughout this rural farming town 80 miles east of Asuncion, the
capital.
   ``I am over the obligatory voting age, but I came to cast my
vote anyway because I have hopes that things will change,'' said
Ramon Ramirez, 64.
   The vote Monday to select a president and two-chamber congress
to replace the regime of former President Alfredo Stroessner,
ousted in a Feb. 3 coup, was mandatory for all Paraguayans between
18 and 60.
   Stroessner, 76, who took power in a 1954 coup, had eight
straight times arranged his own election. Rural peasants often were
trucked to voting sites, handed ballots for the ruling Colorado
Party and told to place them in the box while party officials
looked on.
   Caballero said he did not cast his ballot for the Colorados this
time.
   ``I voted for Domingo Laino of the Authentic Radical Liberal
Party because he always fought for freedom,'' added Caballero.
   Despite the support of voters such as Caballero, the election
was won by the general who deposed Stroessner: Colorado Party
candidate Andres Rodriguez.
   ``I'm going to vote for Gen. Rodriguez because he promised many
things to the peasants and he brought us democracy,'' said Eulalia
Dominguez, 33, in the town of Caacupe, 32 miles east of Asuncion.
   Clusters of farmers stood beside the highway in a light drizzle,
waiting for flatbed trucks of Rodriguez's and Laino's parties, the
two largest, to take them to voting sites. Others traveled by
bicycle, horse and tractor.
   Officials at voting sites in several small towns strictly
followed regulations, supplying private rooms for citizens to
choose in secrecy between the ballots supplied by the eight parties
participating in the elections.
   They also supplied indelible purple ink, furnished by the United
States, to mark voters' right index fingers.
   In the February 1988 election, only Colorado Party ballots could
be found at many voting places and private voting rooms were
scarce. But all sides called the election Monday more open.
   ``Some people are saying these are the cleanest elections in
Paraguayan history,'' said Omar Jara, 29, who quit his job as a
teacher because of low pay and now does odd jobs.
   ``But I say it is the cleanest fraud,'' he added. ``I would have
voted for Rodriguez, but you can see that the people around him are
just continuing the farce.''
   Opposition spokesmen reported some irregularities in voting,
such as indelible ink that washed off, registration of new voters
by Colorado officials on the day of balloting and some mix-ups with
voter registration lists.
   ``Things are somewhat better (than in 1988) but we still have a
long way to go,'' said Fernando Guillen, an observer for the
Revolutionary Febrerista Party in Arroyo San Jose, 60 miles east of
the capital.
   Lidia Ramirez, 64, of Caacupe, seemed to take the irregularities
in stride.
   ``It may not be perfect, but at least now we have freedom to
choose,'' she said, waiting in line to vote.
</TEXT>
