<FIRST>r a PM-JoggerRaped     05-02 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jogger Raped,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>`High Five,' Other Encouraging Signs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was severely beaten and raped in
Central Park by a gang of youths has shown signs of emerging from a
coma, and gave a ``high five'' sign for a hospital worker, doctors
said.
   The 28-year-old woman remained in a coma Monday and physicians
were not optimistic about her chances for a full recovery, but she
has squeezed hands, raised her eyebrows, smiled at jokes and nodded
vigorously, said Dr. Robert S. Kurtz.
   ``Over the last day our patient has shown an increased level of
alertness,'' Kurtz told reporters at Metropolitan Hospital.
   ``She certainly isn't fully awake and we're still in some
concern about ultimate outcome,'' he added. ``But obviously these
changes are for the better.''
   The victim, an investment banker, was jumped by the gang April
19 as she jogged through an isolated section of Central Park on her
nightly run. Six teen-agers have been indicted on charges of
attempted murder, rape, sodomy and assault.
   Kurtz said an electroencephalogram, a measure of brain waves
known as an EEG, showed ``a better pattern than last week.'' The
woman's eyes are now open some of the time, he said.
   Neurologists use a scale of 3 to 15 to measure brain function.
The woman came into the hospital at 4 or 5, improved to 7 for most
of last week, and now is roughly an 11, just below consciousness,
Kurtz said.
   ``She's not completely, totally comatose,'' he said.
   On Sunday, a hospital staff member asked her to give a ``high
five'' and the woman, who was in semi-upright, raised her hand,
Kurtz said.
   Kurtz said she sometimes raises her eyebrows when her name is
called, squeezes hands when asked, and once nodded vigorously when
asked if she wanted to see one of her Wall Street co-workers.
   ``There's just too many of these experiences to ignore them or
totally downplay them,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, he said doctors were ``pretty concerned about
whether she'll make a full recovery. It's not out of the question.
... The woods are full of stories of amazing recoveries when no one
ever expected it.''
   The odds, however, are that she will have a ``significant
neurological deficit,'' the extent of which won't be known for some
time, he said.
</TEXT>
