<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchSlayings     05-02 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Slayings,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rural Congregation Shattered By Slayings of Minister, 3 Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKEVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a rural church shaken by the
slayings of their minister, his wife and two daughters have settled
into the rituals of mourning, accepting condolences from neighbors
and the minister's teen-age son.
   The peace inside the Olive Branch Church of the United Brethren
in Christ, perched near the top of a small rise amid greening trees
and freshly tilled fields, was shattered Sunday by the slayings.
   The bodies of the Rev. Robert L. Pelley, 38, his 32-year-old
wife, Dawn, and daughters Janel, 8, and Jolene, 6, were found in
the parsonage Sunday morning after the family failed to appear for
services.
   Investigators say the slayings may have occurred Saturday
afternoon.
   Police have ruled out burglary or theft, as well as
murder-suicide. They have refused to discuss possible motives.
   The four victims all apparently were shot at close range with
the same weapon, said St. Joseph County sheriff's Sgt. Charles
Feirrell. Autopsy results were not expected before today, he said.
   In an act of condolence Monday, members of neighboring churches
brought cold cuts, salads and soft drinks for the congregation that
gathered informally at the church.
   ``Even people who don't go to any church were bringing things,''
said Alfred Price, superintendent of the United Brethren's Northern
Ohio Conference, which includes part of northern Indiana.
   Joining the mourners was Jeff Pelley, 17, the minister's only
son. He returned to the parsonage Monday after being gone Saturday
and Sunday for his high school prom and a visit with friends at an
amusement park north of Chicago.
   Pelley entered the one-story frame house where his father,
stepmother and stepsisters died. He emerged moments later with a
garbage bag filled with belongings and crossed the gravel parking
lot to console grieving members of the congregations.
   Some members embraced and wept.
   ``You have a bond here that a lot of times you don't find in a
bigger church,'' said Richard Thorpe, a former pastor at the church.
   The church's communion Bible was opened to a verse of the Old
Testament book of Isaiah that said ``the righteous perisheth.'' A
financial statement posted on the bulletin board showed Pelley
earned $1,250 a month, and the church bank balance totaled $254.94.
   The Pelleys had married after their first spouses died,
congregation members said. Jeff and Jackie, 14, were Pelley's
children from his first marriage, and Jessica, 10, Janel and Jolene
came from Ms. Pelley's first marriage.
   Jackie was attending a church camp when the killings occurred,
and Jessica had spent the night with friends, police said.
   The Rev. Don Merrilatt, a United Brethren pastor from a nearby
town, said Pelley had just written a paper on merging broken
families for a counseling course they were attending at Huntington
College.
   Merrilatt said Pelley had talked about friction among the
children in the new family, but declined to elaborate.
   However, church member Beatrice Roush, 66, said she babysat
frequently for the Pelley's younger children and noticed no signs
of strain. ``They all got along fine,'' she said.
</TEXT>
