<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-KillerBees     05-02 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Killer Bees,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Destroys Swarm of `Killer Bees'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A swarm of about 500 Africanized honeybees,
popularly known as ``killer bees,'' has been destroyed at Miami's
port, state officials said.
   The bees, hitchhiking on the outside of a container brought in
from Suriname aboard the freighter Werner, were discovered April 21
by workers at the Omni Terminal in downtown Miami, Agriculture
Commissioner Doyle Conner said Monday.
   The bees were destroyed that day by a state inspector, but as a
precaution additional bait hives have been placed in the port and
surrounding area.
   It is the fifth swarm of the highly aggressive bees that has
been discovered and destroyed in Florida in the last four years.
   Last May, a swarm of about 10,000 was found at Fort Lauderdale
aboard a freighter carrying fruit and vegetables from Guatemala.
   Conner said his department has had about two dozen bait hives at
Miami's port, Miami International Airport and the Miami River for
some time. The additional bait hives put in place since the swarm
was discovered will bring the number to more than 50.
   ``The first bait hive we ever placed was in Miami because it's
an area we've always been concerned about,'' Conner said. ``There
is just a tremendous interchange between Miami and Central and
South American countries, virtually all of which are now infested
with Africanized bees.''
   State and federal inspectors monitor up to 300 bait hives in 13
port areas in Florida.
   The bees have been migrating north from Brazil since the 1950s
and now are in the central part of Mexico. They are expected to
reach the Texas border sometime next year.
   Officials in Florida are not expecting them to arrive through
the normal migration process for another four or five years.
Meantime, they are concentrating their efforts on eradicating any
accidental introductions.
   The Africanized bees' venom is not more potent than that of
European honeybees that are common throughout the United States,
but they are more dangerous because they are likely to sting in
greater numbers due to their aggressive nature.
   They are hard to distinguish from domestic bees, although
slightly smaller.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
