<DOCNO> AP890502-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay-Rodriguez     05-02 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay-Rodriguez,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Rodriguez Is Career Officer With A Populist Touch</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Paraguay-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, the apparent
winner of his country's presidential election, is a career officer
with a populist touch.
   Rodriguez, 65, ran Monday as the candidate for the Colorados,
the powerful and well-organized party that has ruled this
semitropical, landlocked nation since 1947.
   Party affiliation aside, Rodriguez won wide popular support for
leading the Feb. 3 coup that toppled Gen. Alfredo Stroessner,
ending his 34 years of autocratic rule.
   The stocky, black-haired general named himself acting president
and, to the surprise of many Paraguayans, called for general
elections, accepted the Colorado candidacy and campaigned for
democracy and human rights.
   ``The man seems to have become the latter-day saint of
democracy,'' said Fernando Vera, presidential candidate of the
opposition Revolutionary Febrerista Party.
   Rodriguez further surprised his countrymen by legalizing eight
political parties banned under Stroessner, approving an extra
five-week voter registration period to allow opposition parties
time to sign up members and attending 21 political rallies.
   His chief rival, former exile Domingo Laino, reminded
Paraguayans, however, that the general served from 1961 to 1989 as
head of the Asuncion-based 1st Army Corps and was Stroessner's
close aide.
   Rodriguez said he collaborated with the regime out of
``discipline and obedience'' as a military officer.
   The Rev. Ismael Rolon, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Asuncion
and a frequent critic of Stroessner, said it was too early to
assess Rodriguez's ability to govern. But, he added, ``In the few
contacts we have had he seems to be a man of good intentions.''
   Born into a rural farm family, Rodriguez entered the army as a
cadet at age 18 and quickly earned the nickname ``Tiger'' for his
perseverance and willingness to fight to achieve goals.
   Reports published abroad have suggested Rodriguez may have been
involved in narcotics trafficking. He emphatically denies the
charge.
   Other reports have suggested the general's luxurious home in
Asuncion and his wealth are due to involvement in contraband and
questionable business associations.
   ``He is a wealthy man, a very wealthy man, one of the richest
men in the country, maybe the richest,'' said a foreign diplomat
who spoke on condition of anonymity. The diplomat noted that
Rodriguez owns the country's largest foreign exchange house, an
aircraft importing firm and has huge cattle and land holdings as
well as part ownership of a flour mill and brewery.
   ``They say he has an exchange house, but that is because the
owners are his friends,'' said Blas N. Riquelme, a businessman who
says he has known Rodriguez for nearly 26 years.
   ``He always has helped businessmen out and so people say he is a
partner in this or that,'' Riquelme said. ``But there is no proof
nor will there ever be any because he is a simple working man who
has earned his wealth honestly.''
   During the campaign, Rodriguez often cited his humble origins
and delighted supporters with spontaneous talks in Guarani, the
native Indian language spoken by most Paraguayans.
   ``He knows the psychology of the Paraguayan people much better
than Stroessner, who always was formal,'' said Roman Catholic
Bishop Mario Melanio Medina, a human rights leader.
   Rodriguez, unlike Stroessner, included his family in the
political campaign and reportedly consulted closely with his wife
Nelly and three daughters after speeches. He relaxed by playing
with his 10 nieces and nephews.
   Rodriguez plays tennis, sometimes with U.S. Ambassador Timothy
Towell, and likes to ride horses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
