<FIRST>r a PM-SalvadoranAsylum     05-02 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvadoran Asylum,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Halts Deportation of Salvadorans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered immigration
officials to stop deporting hundreds of Salvadorans from a Texas
detention center.
   U.S. District Judge David V. Kenyon said the aliens were denied
a chance to seek political asylum.
   Kenyon ruled that the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service violated his previous order to provide help to Salvadorans
at the Port Isabel Service Processing Center.
   ``Out of a group of 67 Salvadorans deported from Port Isabel on
April 20, none was represented by counsel at their deportation
hearings,'' he said in his preliminary injunction issued Friday and
made public Monday. ``The court finds it difficult to believe that
each of these individuals learned of and knowingly and effectively
waived his or her right to counsel.''
   Kenyon also ordered the INS to hold group presentations advising
the detention center inmates of their rights.
   Last month, an attorney for the Los Angeles-based Central
American Refugee Center sought an order requiring that legal
counsel be provided the immigrants.
   Activists had argued that a stepped-up enforcement program had
led to the detention of thousands of people at Port Isabel, and
that many faced deportation hearings without legally-required
access to a lawyer.
   Kenyon's order remains in effect pending a May 30 hearing.
</TEXT>
