<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Quayle     05-02 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Meets With Singapore Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle arrived here today
for a one-day visit intended to reinforce the ties between the
United States and this island nation.
   Quayle paid a courtesy call on President Wee Kim Wee, whose job
is primarily ceremonial, before trying to squeeze in a round of
golf.
   Later in the day, the vice president was to see Prime Minister
Lee Kuan Yew, political leader of the tiny nation since it achieved
independence in 1965.
   High on the agenda were issues of trade and defense as well as
the future of neighboring Cambodia after the Vietnamese occupation
troops leave this fall.
   Singapore is a close U.S. ally although tensions developed in
the relationship last year after the expulsion of an American
diplomat who was accused by the Singapore government of meddling in
internal politics. In the past, Washington has raised questions
about the government's detention of its political opponents.
   Earlier, before leaving Jakarta, Indonesia, Quayle told
reporters he ``re-established a strong friendship'' with Indonesian
President Suharto.
   Quayle praised Indonesia's economic growth. He also brought up
the subject of human rights _ which he said he talks about
``wherever I go, unrequested'' _ although he did not directly
criticize the Suharto government on the issue.
   Some members of Congress had asked Quayle to find out the status
of up to 400 political prisoners believed to be held in Indonesia.
   On Monday, Quayle said he met with three human rights activists
in Indonesia and discussed legislation pending in Congress that
would tie U.S. aid levels to a country's human rights stance.
Quayle said he ``rejected that categorically'' on grounds the
legislation was a ``dumb idea.''
   Also while in Indonesia, Quayle repeated his support for
Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk, but added that
a meeting between the two brought no changes in U.S. policy toward
that country.
   Sihanouk was visiting Indonesia along with the leaders of two
other factions hopeful of running Cambodia after the promised
Vietnamese withdrawal.
   The fourth group vying for control in Cambodia is the Khmer
Rouge, a Chinese-backed organization that was responsible for
killing as many as 1.5 million Cambodians from 1975 to 1979. Quayle
and other U.S. officials have said they will not tolerate a
Cambodian government dominated by the Khmer Rouge.
   Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed government has changed the
country's name and flag, and invited Sihanouk to return home and
help rule. Sihanouk welcomed the concessions, saying, ``We are
going to make progress on the way toward a settlement.''
   Quayle has said the United States is considering giving military
aid to Sihanouk and possibly the other non-communist Cambodian
faction, headed by Son Sann. But he said such aid did not come up
in his discussions with Sihanouk.
   On Wednesday, Quayle flies to Thailand for two days and will
visit a refugee camp where Cambodians live along the Thai border.
He returns to the United States on Friday and will stop in Alaska
to monitor the cleanup efforts following the March 24 Exxon Valdez
oil spill in Prince William Sound.
</TEXT>
