<FIRST>r a PM-Cocaine-ChildAbuse     05-02 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine-Child Abuse,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Who Used Cocaine Before Giving Birth Is Guilty Of Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who used cocaine hours before
giving birth was convicted of prenatal child abuse and neglect by a
judge who compared the drug use to giving a baby razor blades to
play with in the crib.
   ``This is the first case of this kind to come before this
court,'' Juvenile Court Judge Frederick J. Kapala said Monday in
finding the mother guilty.
   The child was put in the care of social workers pending a May 25
hearing.
   A key element in the case involved the question of whether
Illinois law covers fetal rights, including the possibility of
future health damage to so-called cocaine babies.
   The mother's attorney, Alberto F. Altamore, said the Illinois
juvenile court act defines abuse and neglect of minors, but ``does
not address the issue of fetus abuse.''
   Kapala said Altamore raised a ``legitimate argument'' because
state child abuse laws only speak of ``minors under the age of 21.''
   But he said: ``I have to take a stand one way or the other on
the issue'' of fetus rights.
   ``We can expect to see a growing body of law on this subject,''
he said.
   Altamore said the case could open the door to child abuse and
neglect charges being filed against pregnant women who drink
alcohol or smoke.
   But Kapala said there's a difference with cocaine, since it's
illegal.
   The baby, born three months ago, has shown no signs of addiction
or serious health problems associated with cocaine babies,
according to testimony.
   Assistant State's Attorney Gary Golian said medical studies
suggest cocaine babies may be subject to serious health problems
far into the future.
   The judge said effects of the cocaine on the baby ``may not
appear for years.''
   But ``it's the same as if a mother gave a child a pack of razor
blades to play with in the crib,'' he said. ``The child might drop
the blades out of the crib and not get hurt, but the exposure to
danger is the same.''
   Kapala delayed a decision on whether the child eventually can be
returned to the mother. She has been participating in a drug
treatment program.
   Because it is a juvenile case, neither the woman's name was not
released.
</TEXT>
