<FIRST>r a PM-UnderseaSchool     05-02 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Undersea School,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kids Nationwide Tune In To $7 Million Science Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular robot was relegated to the sidelines,
but thousands of excited schoolchildren still watched in awe as a
$7 million science project lit up screens nationwide, whisking
viewers to the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea.
   The satellite-relayed view from a camera-equipped submersible
robot Monday was the first of two weeks of live broadcasts to an
expected 250,000 students at 13 museums from British Columbia to
Florida.
   The project suffered a temporary setback last week when Jason,
the 7-foot long robot whose older brother first explored the sunken
Titanic, sank among the ruins of an ancient Roman trading ship off
the coast of Italy.
   The cable used to lower the million-dollar submersible and its
mobile garage, Argo, snapped and the pair plunged 2,100 feet to the
soft, silty ocean floor.
   The robot was recovered apparently undamaged Saturday, but sat
out the first 40-minute broadcast Monday.
   The biggest laugh of the morning came when Kenneth, a grade
school student from Memphis, Tenn., had a chance to question Dr.
Robert Ballard, the head of the expedition.
   ``Is Jason all right?'' he asked, his voice crackling over a
3,000-mile connection to the support ship, Star Hercules.
   ``Jason is fine,'' Ballard told his student audience via the
two-way hookup. ``His pride's a little hurt, but luckily none of
his instrumentation is.''
   Ballard sought to reassure the students, who have through weeks
of lessons and classroom discussion developed an affection for the
little propeller-driven robot explorer.
   Jason can be remotely driven in and around underwater objects.
Its replacement Monday, Medea, is merely a sophisticated camera
platform that is towed to the ocean floor.
   Broadcasting from his control center on the bridge, Ballard took
questions from students at three of the 13 participating museums,
narrated live footage of underwater volcanoes and set the stage for
pre-prepared films on satellite technology and the ancient Greek
voyager Jason, for whom the 20th century robot was named.
   For some of the kids, the show wasn't quite the same without its
star.
   ``The teachers said it was going to be so real that it would
seem like the water could come right off the screen,'' said
10-year-old Almas Rathod of the Walter J. Paton School in
Shrewsbury, Mass. ``It wasn't like that.''
   But classmate Barry Lyall said the field trip had lived up to
his expectations.
   ``It's much more interesting than hearing about it in a
classroom,'' the 9-year-old native of Scotland said. ``It was the
next best thing to being there.''
   The project, whose sponsors include Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution, Turner Broadcasting System, Inc., the National
Geographic Society and Electronic Data Systems, was scheduled to
move 120 miles southwest next week, where it will broadcast from
the site of a 2,000-year-old Roman trading ship.
   The participating museums are The Boston Museum of Science; the
Museum of Natural History in Denver; the Detroit Science Center;
Discovery Place in Charlotte, N.C.; the Museum of Science and
Industry in Chicago; The Science Place in Dallas; Memphis (Tenn.)
Pink Palace Museum; The Franklin Institute in Philadelphia; the
Rochester (N.Y.) Museum and Science Center; Mote Marine Laboratory
in Sarasota, Fla.; National Geographic Society Grosvenor Auditorium
in Washington and Dallas; and the Royal British Columbia Museum in
Victoria, British Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
