<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Clamscam     05-02 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clamscam,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening Arguments in Giant Clam Caper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven people poached nearly $2 million worth of
giant clams by underreporting harvests and evading state fisheries
agents, a prosecutor claimed.
   In opening statements Monday, Assistant prosecutor Marilyn
Brenneman said the ``defendants routinely took thousands of pounds
of state resources'' from Puget Sound without paying for them.
   But an attorney for one of the defendants said the trial was the
result of a bitter feud between those who dominated the geoduck
clam industry and resentful divers recruited by the state to build
its case.
   ``You're going to hear two very different stories on this
industry,'' Richard Hansen said.
   Opening arguments were expected to resume today.
   The so-called Clamscam trial, one of the biggest white-collar
crime cases in the state's history, centers on the evolution of the
geoduck industry, which did not exist until 1970.
   The geoduck, pronounced ``gooey-duck'' after an Indian word for
``dig deep,'' has a long, sinuous neck, an oblong shell up to six
inches long and weighs as much as 10 pounds.
   The mollusk is harvested in Washington and British Columbia,
much of it for export to Japan where its flesh can bring $12 a
pound.
   The defendants were officers, suppliers and associates of the
now-defunct Washington King Clam Inc. and related companies. They
are accused of stealing at least $1.8 million worth of clams from
state-managed clam beds.
   Ms. Brenneman said testimony would show that Brian D. Hodgson,
52, the company's co-owner, in the early 1970s conspired to
underreport the amount of clams harvested to state Department of
Fisheries and Department of Natural Resources officials.
   Also charged was Carol K. Kondo, 58, who came to the United
States from Japan in the 1950s and was a pioneer in the harvesting
of geoducks along with Hodgson. The two were the first to discover
a market in Japan after a trip there in 1975.
   Besides falsifying harvest figures, Brenneman said, Hodgson
directed divers to go outside legal clamming areas for the
desirable white-necked clams and to share information on how to
evade authorities.
   Hansen, an attorney for Hodgson, told jurors the 1.2 million
pounds of clams allegedly stolen over a span of 10 years actually
was just 5.1 percent of the entitled harvest within that time.
   He also said the divers the state will call to testify for the
most part were angry with the pay given them by Hodgson, and that
the divers had done the poaching.
   Also charged were Kondo's daugher, Cindy Rommel, 28; Mark E.
Pearce, 37, a former employee of King Clam; fisherman Richard
Myers; bookkeeper Ralph Williams; and Roger Hondle, who was aboard
Myers' boat when it was seized in 1986.
   All seven defendants were charged with first-degree theft and
conspiracy to commit trafficking of stolen property.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
