<FIRST>r a PM-NorthropEngineer     05-02 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northrop Engineer,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Northrop Engineer Pleads Guilty to Falsifying Tests For Jet
Part</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Northrop Corp. engineer pleaded
guilty to falsifying tests for parts installed in Marine Corps
Harrier jets.
   Howard Hyde, chief engineer for Northrop's Western services
department in El Monte, changed his plea Monday from innocent to
guilty in a hearing before U.S. District Judge Pamela Rymer.
   ``The government has overwhelming evidence against Mr. Hyde and
the rest of the individuals named in the indictment,'' Hyde's
attorney, Marshall Schulman, said after the hearing. ``He is very
contrite and he feels bad about the whole situation, and he is
accepting his responsibility.''
   Northrop and five current or former employees were named April
11 in a 167-count indictment accusing them of falsifying tests for
stabilizers for the jets and guidance components for nuclear-tipped
cruise missiles.
   Hyde, named only in counts involving the jet, is expected to
testify against other indicted officials, Schulman said.
   Hyde, 48, of Yorba Linda, faces as much as 15 years in prison
and a $750,000 fine at his sentencing Aug. 21. He is free on bail.
   The Harrier jet, built by McDonnell Douglas Corp., is an unusual
fighter-bomber that can take off and land vertically. It is
designed to carry nuclear and conventional payloads.
   The Navy is conducting studies to determine whether the planes
should be fitted with new stabilizers.
