<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0819EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Holocaust 1stLd-Writethru a0425 05-02 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Holocaust, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>6 Million Remembered By Countrywide Name Readings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with readings; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nazi Holocaust survivor Leah Zonershein choked
back tears today as she read aloud the names of her parents, Chaim
and Hannah, who perished in a World War II concentration camp.
   She was one of hundreds of people who took part in memorials
throughout the country at which names of the 6 million Jewish
victims were being read on Israel's national day of mourning for
the Holocaust.
   Sirens sounded at 10 a.m. throughout the country. Thousands of
Israelis paid tribute by halting traffic or stopping in their
tracks and bowing their heads for the two-minute wail of the sirens.
   Polish-born Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who lost family in
the Holocaust, was expected to read names later today at Parliament
in keeping with this year's theme of personal remembrance.
   Names also were read aloud at army bases, schools and following
prayers at Judaism's holiest shrine, the Western Wall, the remnant
of the ancient Jewish temple in Jerusalem's walled Old City.
   The Dutch-born Mrs. Zonershein, 62, said the ceremony at
Parliament helped ease memories of her ordeal. ``I have found that
talking about it helps,'' she said.
   Her sister, Judith Ilan, stood at her side at the microphone but
could not speak. ``I still am unable to let it all out,'' Mrs. Ilan
said afterward.
   The sisters spent 15 months in the Bergen-Belsen concentration
camp in occupied Poland, where their parents died. The women were
freed by Soviet troops in April 1945 after a forced ``death march''
by Nazi soldiers who fled the Allied invasion.
   ``I don't know how we went on to live normal lives after what
happened. Somehow life wins out over everything,'' said Mrs.
Zonershein, a retired teacher.
   Several elderly survivors wept as they pronounced names of
brothers, sisters and cousins who died.
   Difficult as it was, most survivors agreed the readings were an
effective way to keep the memories alive for young Israelis, now
two generations removed from the Holocaust.
   ``Holocaust day became a routine thing here. The number, 6
million, says nothing to most people, but name after name after
name, that gets the message across,'' Mrs. Zonershein said.
   In Jerusalem's outdoor Ben Yehuda shopping mall, hundreds of
vendors and shoppers paused to bow their heads in tribute when the
siren rang out for Holocaust Martyrs and Heroes Rememberance Day.
   They included Orthodox Jews who read from the Torah and a
Palestinian in an Arab keffiyeh headdress who bowed his head in
silence.
   To many Israelis, the Holocaust has become a symbol of Jewish
suffering that also reflects their security fears amid continued
Arab enmity.
   ``This is a very important show of respect and an act of
remembering because it could happen again,'' Devora Feinstein, 17,
said after the collective silence.
   Another name-reader at Parliament was Lithuanian-born Parliament
speaker Dov Shilansky, a survivor of Dachau concentration camp in
Germany, who lost aunts, uncles and grandparents to the Nazis.
   ``Now we have our own Jewish state, with our own parliament and
I am speaker as a remnant of your flesh,'' Shilansky said in a
brief speech after laying a wreath of flowers by a stand of
memorial torches.
   Shilansky criticized the construction of a Roman Catholic
convent just outside the former Auschwitz death camp.
   ``In Auschwitz in Poland they have built a kind of monument to
your graves, a Carmelite convent with a big cross.''
   The church agreed to move the convent in 1987, but the agreement
has not been implemented.
   Holocaust day is timed by law in Israel to fall half way between
the start of a 1943 Jewish uprising against German troops in
Warsaw, Poland and Israeli Independence Day, which this year is on
May 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
