<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Carriers 1stLd-Writethru a0437 05-02 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Carriers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shippers, Unions Work out Plan to Combat Smuggling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with von Raab comment today after 5th graf,
The agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a longshoremen's union says his
members might stop unloading ships from drug-producing countries,
as members of the cargo industry work out a plan to fight
trafficking in illegal drugs.
   ``We'd rather lose wages than lose our children,'' John Bowers,
president of the International Longshoreman's Association, said
Monday.
   Bowers' statement came Monday as U.S. Customs Commissioner
William von Raab announced a proposed agreement by Customs, air
lines and sea carriers and unions to combat drug trafficking. None
of the carriers had signed the agreement Monday.
   ``This is the first time that industry, labor and government
have joined together to put together a plan to combat drug
smuggling,'' von Raab said before a meeting with representatives of
about 100 air and sea carriers where the plan was outlined.
   The agreement _ still in draft form _ calls for carriers to
impose strict security standards at foreign and domestic docks,
terminals and facilities and aboard their planes and ships.
   Von Raab said on ``CBS This Morning'' today that ``one thing
we've started to do very effectively is to deal with the pilots
that use small airplanes and the guys that use small speedboats (to
smuggle drugs).''
   ``They're really losing that war, as it were, so the theater of
war is shifting to commercial cargo,'' he added. ``That will be the
last theater of this war. It'll be a tough one, but with the help
of the shipping companies, the airline companies and labor, all
together, we're going to win it. It's just going to take time.''
   The ILA's Bowers swore that his membership _ 110,000 from
``Maine to Texas, Puerto Rico and Canada'' _ would help out. ``I
told the commissioner we'll have 110,000 pairs of eyes out there
looking to help him,'' he said.
   He noted that the longshoremen had refused for 25 years to
unload cargo from the Soviet Union and recently paid $9 million in
fines because the union lost a Supreme Court decision over the
boycott.
   Bowers declined to say whether any country's cargo or ships
already had been targeted for a possible boycott or what criteria
the union would use to refuse to unload ships.
   Bowers assured the sea carriers' representatives that he would
make sure there would be swift and sure, if rough, justice for any
union member found helping drug traffickers.
   ``If we take him down there, you won't need a court for him,''
Bowers said. ``Anything with my people, I'll make sure they never
work on the waterfront again.''
   Some of the carriers' representatives wanted a tariff imposed
that would cover their costs for the new security measures the
agreement would demand so they would remain competitive with
carriers that don't participate.
   Lou Razzino, the Customs program manager for narcotics
interdiction in commercial cargo, said such a decision would have
to be made by Congress.
   As part of the agreement, Customs will provide security
training, surveys of foreign and domestic sites and help in
identifying potential smuggling opportunities. If a carrier is
found to be carrying illegal drugs, Customs will weigh the
company's degree of general compliance before deciding on a penalty.
   Under the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, penalties for carrying
illegal drugs went up to $1,000 per ounce of heroin and cocaine and
$500 per ounce of marijuana. The act also authorized the seizure of
the carrier.
   ``If you help us prevent drugs from getting aboard your
conveyance, you'll have no problems with penalties and seizures,''
Razzino said.
   Von Raab estimated that 30 percent of the cocaine now entering
the country is coming in by shipping container, and said he
expected that to increase to 50 percent in the next two years and
up to 80 percent to 90 percent by 1992 because of a crackdown on
other forms of trafficking.
</TEXT>
