<FIRST>r a PM-Living-In-Sin 1stLd-Writethru a0481 05-02 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Living-In-Sin, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Abolishes Living-In-Sin Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th pvs, `Zoning, I believe...' to include
quotes from those who wanted to keep the ordinance. Picks up 6th graf,
`The living-in-sin ....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It still may be living in sin, but unrelated
people can live together throughout Denver after City Council
revoked a law that had caused years of controversy and forced some
to carry marriage certificates.
   The council late Monday voted 7-6 to abolish the law that had
covered more than half the city.
   ``There are no longer any zoning districts where two people
cannot live together,'' said Councilwoman Cathy Reynolds, who
worked to change the ordinance since she was first elected in 1975.
``I'm delighted.''
   Councilwoman Mary DeGroot also voted to abolish the law.
   ``Zoning, I believe, should be used to determine land use and
density but not relationships,'' she said.
   Supporters of the law argued that revoking it could hurt family
values.
   ``The family is the fundamental structure that preserves our
society,'' said Councilman Bill Roberts.
   The vote is a ``step toward destroying our city,'' said
Councilman Ted Hackworth. Councilman Bob Crider called the passage
``a sad day in the city of Denver.''
   The living-in-sin law had covered about 60 percent of the area
of Denver, which has a population of more than 500,000.
   Under the law, neither boarders nor unrelated people were
allowed to live in the same house in areas zoned R-0. In areas
zoned R-1, a homeowner was required to obtain a $20 boarder's
permit to cover a non-relative.
   ``After reviewing the sales prices and the square footage of the
homes, there did not appear to be a significant difference between
an R-1 and an R-0 in my district, '' DeGroot said.
   Cathy Donohue, another supporter of change on the council, said
the law forced people to carry their marriage certificates with
them, and zoning inspectors complained about having to count
toothbrushes in homes.
   Donohue said some neighborhood arguments turned nasty and people
were forced to move after being turned in to authorities.
   The penalty for violating the ordinance was $999 a day. People
had six months to appeal but when told they faced a fine for every
day of violation, most sold their houses, often at a considerable
loss because of Denver's soft housing market, Donohue said.
   Several churches turned out previously to oppose any change to
the law, but most opposition this time came from families and a
real estate agent, who sold houses based on the zoning restrictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Soviet     05-02 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Soviet,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Radio Suggests Expanding Trade Ties With Soviet Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should develop
trade relations with the Soviet bloc as a counter to punitive
economic sanctions imposed by Western countries, state radio said
today.
   The South African Broadcasting Corp. commentary also diverged
from previous government statements by depicting the Soviet Union's
presence in Southern Africa as legitimate and permanent.
   It was one of the most explicit expressions of a major new
development in South African foreign policy, triggered by the
diplomatic initiatives of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev's tactics have forced Pretoria to revise its
decades-old view of Moscow as an arch enemy orchestrating black
nationalist guerrillas in a ``total onslaught'' to overthrow South
Africa's white-dominated government.
   In recent months, the two countries have found a common interest
in seeking to keep an independence plan for Namibia on track. South
African officials also have been pleased by Soviet statements that
Moscow seeks peaceful change in South Africa.
   ``The Soviet Union appears to have accepted that South Africa is
the regional power in Southern Africa,'' the radio said. ``South
Africa, for her part, must accept that although Southern Africa is
not a traditional sphere of influence for the Soviet Union, she has
been allowed by other governments in the region to establish a
presence that is a permanent presence.''
   Because of this, the commentary said, ``a certain degree of
interaction is consequently inevitable and, in certain areas, could
be fruitful.''
   ``Trade relations with Eastern Bloc nations can be expanded
without South Africa diluting her firm and longstanding resistance
to the inhumanity of communism,'' it said. ``Diversified trading
relations are all the more important given the hostile action of
Western nations such as the United States in instituting economic
sanctions.''
   Last week, there was an official Soviet visit to South Africa
for the first time since the countries broke diplomatic ties in
1956. Soviet diplomat Viacheslav Ustinov came to Cape Town with
U.S., Angolan and Cuban officials to assess accords calling for
South Africa to end its rule of Namibia and Cuba to withdraw troops
from Angola.
   Ustinov emphasized that Moscow will not consider restoring
relations with Pretoria until it dismantles its policy of legal
race discrimination and grants political rights to the black
majority.
   The radio said: ``As a Christian nation, South Africa, in turn,
must condemn the oppression of religious and ethnic minorities
under the communist system ...
   ``This having been said,'' it added, ``there are certain
realities that have to be taken into account.''
</TEXT>
