<FIRST>r a PM-Genovese-Killer     05-02 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Genovese-Killer,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Bid For Retrial for Man Convicted of Killing Kitty
Genovese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge refused a new trial for the man
convicted of stabbing Kitty Genovese to death 25 years ago as her
neighbors reportedly ignored her screams for help.
   Winston Moseley, 54, is serving a 20-years-to-life sentence for
the 1964 murder. He sought a new trial on the ground that his trial
lawyer, Sidney Sparrow, had once represented Genovese.
   State Supreme Court Justice Charles Thomas rejected the appeal
Monday, saying a ``significant possibility of conflict of
interest'' had not been shown.
   Thomas noted that the fact that Sparrow represented both
Genovese and Moseley ``doesn't automatically result in a conflict
of interest.''
   In his appeal, which Queens District Attorney John Santucci
opposed, Moseley claimed he never knew that Sparrow had represented
Genovese on a bookmaking charge.
   But according to Thomas, Sparrow declared in his summation
before the jury: ``I knew Kitty Genovese and represented her for
years.''
   ``Neither the defendant nor the trial court thought it necessary
to pursue the issue at that time,'' Thomas said in his six-page
decision.
   Genovese, 28, was killed March 13, 1964 on a street in Queens,
in a case that became a nationwide symbol of urban fear and
indifference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
