<DOCNO> AP890502-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Thailand     05-02 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Thailand,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Refugee Camp Shelled In Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shells crashed into the largest
Cambodian refugee camp in Thailand today, the latest in a recent
surge in border assaults, Western relief officials said.
   Three rounds flew over camp known as Site 2, striking a road,
and two shells landed in the camp 30 minutes later, said Patrick
Van de Velde, deputy director of the U.N. Border Relief Operation.
No casualties were reported.
   Van De Velde said that in the past 10 days, 15 shells or rockets
have landed in or around Site 2. Three seriously wounded refugees
were sent to the hospital of the International Committee of the Red
Cross, a Red Cross official said.
   ``We are concerned by the repeated instances of shelling of
civilian encampments and appeal to concerned parties to refrain
from harming innocent civilians,'' Van de Velde said.
   Site 2 houses about 180,000 refugees. It is in Prachinburi
province, near the border with Cambodia, and about 50 miles north
of the Thai border town of Aranyaprathet.
   The camp is controlled by the Khmer People's National Liberation
Front, one of three guerrilla groups fighting the forces of Vietnam
and of the government it installed in Cambodia after invading in
late 1978.
   It is not clear who is responsible for the recent shellings,
which have forced the temporary evacuation of all but the most
essential relief personnel.
   ``Whoever is doing the shelling, the aim is clear. They want to
disrupt the relief services, they want to disrupt normal life in
the camp,'' said the Red Cross official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Some officials theorized the pro-Vietnamese Cambodian forces
were shelling the camp to pressure the refugees to abandon the
resistance and return to Cambodia. Others theorized that the
guerrillas were doing it to convince the world they needed more
weapons to defend the camp.
   In the past, shellings of the border camps also have escalated
as the two sides maneuvered diplomatically. Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, leader of the resistance coalition, has been holding
talks in Indonesia this week with Hun Sen, premier of Cambodia.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw its forces by the end of
September. Sihanouk's three-party resistance coalition includes the
Khmer Rouge, which was blamed for killing hundreds of thousands of
people when it ruled Cambodia from 1975 until Vietnam's invasion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
