<FIRST>r a PM-LucyMemorial     05-02 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucy Memorial,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucille Ball Laid to Rest, Public Memorial Masses in 3 Cities Next
Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Masses for Lucille Ball will be said
in New York, Chicago and Los Angeles on Monday night, ``when most
of the nation was used to being with Lucy,'' the family said.
   Miss Ball's family gathered over the weekend for a brief,
private memorial and the actress' remains were interred at Forest
Lawn Memorial Park in Hollywood Hills, a source who requested
anonymity told The Associated Press.
   The weekend gathering took place at an undisclosed location and
included Miss Ball's husband, Gary Morton, and Lucie Arnaz and Desi
Arnaz Jr., her children by former husband Desi Arnaz.
   ``They just said a few prayers together and that was it,'' said
Eddy Jo Bernal, a spokeswoman for the family. ``It was just the
immediate family and some long, longtime associates. It was very
informal.''
   The family announced Monday that Roman Catholic Masses will be
said for the comedian in New York, Chicago and Los Angeles. The
services will each begin at 8 p.m. local time on Monday, May 8.
   ``Monday night was the time when most of the nation was used to
being with Lucy,'' a statement from the family said.
   Two of the three long-running comedy shows in which Miss Ball
starred, ``The Lucy Show'' and ``Here's Lucy,'' aired Monday nights
on CBS, while ``I Love Lucy'' had starting times on Monday and
other days as well.
   Miss Ball died Wednesday of a ruptured aorta, eight days after
having heart surgery at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center. She was 77.
   Informal tributes to Miss Ball included a blocklong sympathy
scroll signed over the weekend by people visiting her
flower-bedecked star on Hollywood's Walk of Fame. Peggy Robinson,
who thought of the giant sympathy card, said the scroll would be
presented to the family.
   A makeshift shrine was erected at the marble and bronze star, as
fans dropped by with red roses, candy, lipsticks and photos of the
film and television star.
   In New York, the memorial Mass will be celebrated by the Rev.
Jim Fox at St. Ignatius Loyola; in Chicago by the Rev. John Cusack
at Old St. Patrick's Church; and in the Los Angeles suburb of Santa
Monica by the Rev. Lloyd Torgerson at St. Monica's Church.
</TEXT>
