<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0959EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-Cabinet     05-02 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Cabinet,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenyan Leader Replaces Vice President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi has replaced his
vice president in a shake-up that leaves Kenya's major tribe out of
the government's top two jobs for the first time since independence.
   Moi named George Saitoti, the finance minister and a former
professor of mathematics at the University of Nairobi, as the
country's sixth vice president since this former British colony won
black rule 25 years ago.
   He replaces Josephat Karanja, who resigned as vice president and
vice chairman of the ruling party after receiving a unanimous vote
of no confidence from Parliament. Saitoti retains the finance
portfolio.
   The change leaves both the presidency and vice presidency
occupied for the first time by men who are not members of the
dominant Kikuyu tribe.
   Karanja is a Kikuyu, but his successor calls himself a Masai, a
tribe of largely nomadic cattle herders. Moi, the country's second
president since independence, is a member of the small Kalenjin
tribe.
   Moi, who had been expected to dismiss Karanja if he did not
voluntarily step down after the parliamentary vote, announced the
changes Monday evening. They included reshuffling the portfolios of
nine ministers, abolishing one Cabinet post and creating a new one.
   Thursday's vote of no confidence came after nearly two months of
attacks on the vice president.
   They began with a relatively low-level politician telling a
village gathering that ``an unnamed politician'' had been ursurping
the authority of the president.
   From then on, accounts of verbal attacks on ``an unnamed
politician'' appeared almost daily in Nairobi's three
English-language newspapers.
   Speculation quickly centered on Karanja who, it was said,
arrogantly forced others to kneel before him and was appealing to
tribal animosities.
   But it was not until two weeks ago that Karanja finally was
identified by his detractors.
   Through it all, Moi kept silent, leading to widespread
speculation that he sanctioned or even orchestrated the attacks.
   Kenya, by law, is a one-party state and opposition is firmly
suppressed.
   In announcing his resignation, Karanja again denied the
allegations against him, which included charges of corrupt business
practices and receiving money from neighboring Uganda to
destabilize the government.
   Most other Cabinet changes were minor. But Moi scrapped the
Ministry of National Guidance and Political Affairs and created a
new Ministry of Reclamation and Development of Arid, Semi-Arid and
Waste Land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
