<FIRST>u w PM-HelicopterFlaws 1stLd-Writethru a0445 05-02 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helicopter Flaws, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Flaws Were Exaggerated to Cut Helicopter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, The SH-60F, to CORRECT that the SH-3H was built
by Sikorsky sted Kaman Aerospace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney exaggerated
problems with the Sikorsky Aircraft SH-60F when he scrapped plans
to order 18 of the anti-submarine helicopters in the 1990 budget,
says a congressman from the state where Sikorsky is headquartered.
   ``They were blown out of proportion,'' Rep. John G. Rowland,
R-Conn., said Monday. ``There were really no big problems at all.''
   Cheney last week cited operational problems in the two SH-60Fs
already delivered by Sikorsky, the Stratford, Conn.-based division
of United Technologies Corp. Cheney did include funds to keep the
program going until future purchases can be made.
   But according to briefing papers the Navy provided to Rowland, a
member of the House Armed Services Committee, most of the problems
either have been fixed or are being resolved. The Navy said none of
the failures pose a serious enough problem to prevent safe use.
   The problems included improper installation of a warning light
and damaged sonar cables, according to the documents. The Navy said
the helicopter has ``no substantial design flaws.''
   Sikorsky officials also were fixing problems discovered during
the previous year's testing, including an overly sensitive
automatic altitude control designed to keep the craft at 50 feet
above the water. The system apparently forced the helicopter up and
down with the motion of the waves below, according to Rowland aide
David Boomer.
   The SH-60F is a modified version of Sikorsky's SH-60B Seahawk.
The SH-60F, expected to replace the Sikorsky-built SH-3H, is made
to be based on aircraft carriers for anti-submarine missions. The
SH-60F lowers sonar equipment into the water and pulls it in search
of enemy subs.
   Capt. Barton Strong, the Navy's program manager, told Rowland in
the private briefing Monday that the SH-60F was performing well and
would be a significant improvement over the older SH-3H, according
to the congressman.
   Strong assured Rowland that the Pentagon still supported the
SH-60F program.
   Navy officials told the congressman that the administration
plans to buy a total of 175 SH-60F helicopters over 13 years. Seven
were ordered in 1987 and 18 each in fiscal 1988 and 1989. The Navy
plans to return to a request of 18 in 1991, then 12 a year through
1995, 17 in 1996, 24 in 1997 and 25 in 1998.
   The helicopters cost about $15.8 million each.
   The 1990 budget, which originally called for $313.6 million in
SH-60F spending, was reduced by Cheney to $94 million to cover
spare parts and advanced procurement to keep the program alive. No
SH-60Fs would be purchased in 1990 under Cheney's budget, but
Congress still has to approve that plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-HomeSales     05-02 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Sales,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>New-Home Sales Down 5.5 Percent in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes fell 5.5 percent in March
and registered their first back-to-back declines in more than a
year, the government said today.
   The Commerce Department said sales of new single-family homes
dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 587,000 in March,
following a 10.5 percent decrease during February.
   It was the first time sales had declined for two consecutive
months since they fell for five months in a row from September 1987
through January 1988, the months surrounding the October stock
market crash.
   The declines left sales in March at the slowest annual rate
since the 576,000 level of January 1988.
   The report was another indication of the impact with which
rising interest rates have hit the housing industry. Earlier
reports on housing activity in March showed sales of existing homes
declining for the third straight month and construction of new
homes and apartments dropping for the second month in a row.
   The Federal Reserve Board for a year has been pushing up
interest rates in an effort to restrain economic growth and thus
reduce inflationary pressures.
   Fixed-rate home mortgages last week were averaging 11.03
percent, and lenders were asking an average initial rate of 9.38
percent on one-year adjustable rate mortgages, according to a
national survey by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   The biggest drop in new home sales in March was in the West,
where sales dropped 20.5 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 155,000.
   Sales in March were down 12.7 percent in the South to an annual
rate of 199,000 and declined 2.8 percent in the Midwest to 105,000.
   Sales surged 43.3 percent in the Northeast to a rate of 129,000
after plunging 26.9 percent during the previous month.
   The drop in sales was accompanied by a 4.7 percent increase in
the median price of the homes sold, as lower-income buyers
apparently were the first ones to leave the housing market.
   The March median price for a new home was $126,000, meaning half
the homes sold for more and half for less.
   The average price, which is pulled up by sales of expensive
homes, was up 4 percent to $152,200.
   For the first three months of the year, new home sales were 1.8
percent lower than in the same period a year earlier.

</TEXT>
