<FIRST>u i PM-France-Arafat 2ndLd-Writethru   05-02 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Arafat, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0530,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Arrives, Jews Protest Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th, `During the...' to UPDATE with
political leader saying Arafat called PLO charter outdated; picks up 6th
pvs: Arafat, after...; minor editing throughout to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand today urged PLO
leader Yasser Arafat to rewrite the group's original charter so
that it no longer calls for the destruction of Israel, a spokesman
for the French president said.
   Jewish merchants in Paris' garment district turned on their
burglar alarms in unison today to protest Arafat's visit, which has
caused outrage in France's Jewish community.
   A point frequently made by Israel is that despite the decision
by the Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament in exile,
to recognize Israel and renounce terrorism, the organization's
charter still calls for the Jewish state's destruction.
   Mitterrand told the Palestine Liberation Organization chief to
alter the charter.
   ``During the meeting, Mr. Francois Mitterrand noted that the
continuation in force of the charter of the PLO, adopted in 1964,
was contrary to important points of the political program adopted
by the Palestine National council in Algiers on Nov. 15, 1988, and
that in his eyes things should be made clear,'' said a statement
read by Mitterrand's spokesman, Hubert Vedrine.
   Arafat later met with several other French political figures,
including Pierre Mauroy, leader of the Socialist Party. Mauroy told
reporters he also raised the article in the PLO charter on the
destruction of Israel.
   According to Mauroy, Arafat replied that ``this text has existed
for many years and is now outdated.''Mauroy said Arafat reaffirmed
the PLO's recognition of Israel and abandonment of terrorism.
   Arafat, after the 90-minute meeting with Mitterrand, smiled and
posed for photographers on the steps of the presidential palace.
Urged to comment, he said only: ``It was a very successful and
useful meeting.''
   He added that all would be explained at a news conference
Wednesday.
   Arafat met with Mitterrand on the day his personal
representative and the PLO's senior official in Lebanon, Issam
Salem, was shot and seriously wounded in an ambush in the Lebanese
port of Sidon, police there said.
   PLO officials with Arafat in Paris said Salem died. The source
of their information was not known, and there was no claim of
responsibility for the attack.
   About 2,000 police, including sharpshooters and helicopter
patrols, were mobilized for Arafat's visit, during which he also
was to meet with Premier Michel Rocard and Foreign Minister Roland
Dumas.
   Vedrine read the French statement about the meeting and said he
would take no questions from reporters.
   The statement said Mitterrand questioned Arafat on his position
concerning elections proposed by the Israeli government in the
occupied West Bank and occupied Gaza Strip and expressed French
concern ``about the serious present situation of the inhabitants of
these territories.
   ``He indicated to Mr. Yasser Arafat that France would continue
to act with all interested parties so that an international
conference on the Middle East can be held under the terms which he
himself (Mitterrand) has already suggested,'' the statement
concluded.
   Israeli leaders were critical of the visit. Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir said: ``This man says a lot of things to the Jewish
people. ... He's following the same tradition of the Nazis.''
   Today is Israel's national day of mourning for the 6 million
Jewish victims of the Nazis during World War II.
   In the Jewish-dominated garment district in Paris, Jewish
manufacturers and shopkeepers set off their burglar alarms and
private car alarms for five minutes to protest Arafat's visit.
   ``It is ridiculous to officialize Arafat before getting any
guarantees,'' said protester Victor Gotajner, a clothing
manufacturer.
   France's Jewish community is largely opposed to Arafat's visit
and planned a demonstration today at the Copernic synagogue where a
bomb in October 1980 killed four people.
   The United States began talks with the PLO in December for the
first time since in 13 years after Arafat said he recognized
Israel's right to exist and renounced terrorism.
</TEXT>
