<HEAD>Engine Explodes On Saudia Jetliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to identify aircraft as Boeing 747. Picks up 3rd
pvs, ``They said ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the engines of a Saudi Arabian
jumbo jet exploded today while it was flying with 293 people from
Manila to Riyadh, airport officials said.
   No one was injured in the accident aboard the Boeing 747, said
airline and airport officials who were reluctant to give details.
   They said the blast apparently resulted from a mechanical
failure rather than sabotage.
   The state-owned Saudi Arabian Airlines jet was 20 minutes into
the flight when the engine blew up. It safely returned to Manila.
   Manila control tower technician Andy Abuan said flight
controllers monitored the explosion and advised the pilot of Saudia
Flight 389 to turn back.
   One employee at Saudia's airport office, who refused to give his
name, said the explosion was caused by a mechanical failure. He
said there were 276 passengers and 17 crewmen aboard.
   A flight attendant who asked not to be identified told reporters
she heard a hissing sound from engine No. 4 _ the outer engine on
the plane's right side _ before the explosion.
   She said the plane dumped fuel in the South China sea before
turning back.
