<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0507 05-02 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Says He Will Consider Lifting Blockade Of Illegal Ports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Aoun saying he considers lifting
blockade, envoy postponing visit; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun
said today he would consider lifting a blockade of illegal ports
run by Syrian-backed Moslem militias to end an eight-week conflict
that has killed 278 people.
   Aoun made the offer in a 90-minute news conference a few hours
after fierce shelling duels today between Christian and Syrian
gunners in and around Beirut killed two people and wounded eight.
   ``The ports are no longer the basic issue,'' Aoun said at the
presidential palace in suburban Baabda, east of Beirut. ``Syrian
military presence in Lebanon is the issue.''
   Aoun said he might lift the blockade after talks with Arab
League representative Lakhdar Ibrahimi of Algeria, who was due in
Lebanon Wednesday to try to salvage a shaky 4-day-old cease-fire
mediated by the league. Ibrahimi had been scheduled to arrive today
but postponed his arrival, according to sources in Syria.
   Today's casualties raised the overall toll to 278 people killed
and 1,010 wounded since March 8, when fighting broke out between
Aoun's Christian army units and an alliance of Syrian and Druse
forces.
   A police spokesman said Syrian gunners targeted the coastal
strip north of Beirut and prevented the French tanker Penhors from
approaching the power station in the suburb of Zouk to unload fuel
oil.
   The barrage damaged the main power cable connecting the Zouk
plant with Beirut and stripped the capital of its daily two-hour
ration of electricity, said the police spokesman, who cannot be
named under standing rules.
   The Christian voice of Lebanon radio blamed the cease-fire
violation on Syrian gunners and said Aoun's troops ``responded in
self-defense.''
   Voice of the People, radio of the pro-Syrian Lebanese Communist
Party, blamed Aoun for the renewed fighting.
   ``Aoun's gunners started the barrage,'' the radio said without
elaboration.
   The thuds of exploding shells echoed across Beirut and the
flashes of artillery explosions lighted up the dark skies. Most
civilians deserted their apartments and sought refuge in
underground shelters.
   The police spokesman said there was almost no traffic in Beirut
as the warring factions traded sniper fire and rocket-propelled
grenades across the Green Line that divides the Christian and
Moslem sectors.
   ``It seems most civilians have decided to remain in basements
and bomb shelters pending the outcome of Ibrahimi's mission,'' the
spokesman said.
   Ibrahimi was to meet Wednesday with acting Premier Salim Hoss,
head of the Moslem Cabinet in Lebanon's dual government and
complete arrangements for the deployment of Arab military observers
to oversee a new truce.
   An aide to Hoss said Ibrahimi and the Sunni Moslem leader will
discuss a compromise to the sticking point of the truce _ Aoun's
blockade of ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut.
   The compromise calls for the deployment of Arab observers at the
ports to ``guarantee that they are not used for illegal
activities,'' said the aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The aide said it was Ibrahimi's responsibility to convince Druse
warlord Walid Jumblatt and Shiite Moslem leader Nabih Berri to
accept the proposed solution.
   Berri's Shiite Amal militia operates a single-dock harbor in
Beirut's fishermen's suburb of Ouzai and Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party runs two facilities at Khaldeh and Jiyeh south of
the capital.
   Aoun on March 6 blockaded the three facilities that deny the
state treasury of about $100 million in lost customs dues annually.
Aoun also said the ports were used to ``smuggle drugs and
terrorism.''
   Jumblatt's forces responded to Aoun's blockade by shelling the
310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the capital. Syrian
gunners later joined in the fighting, but Amal did not take part.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing
to achieve a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League by
siding with the Moslems in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
