<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Grain     05-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Grain,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Decide on Soviet Grain Subsidies, Dole Said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush was deciding today whether to
approve a U.S. subsidized sale of 3 million tons of grain to the
Soviet Union, top congressional Republicans said.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas said Bush did not
indicate which way he was leaning during a breakfast meeting with
GOP leaders, but that the lawmakers strongly advised him to go
ahead with the deal.
   It would be Bush's first approval of a major agricultural
subsidy. The sale has been the subject of intense disagreement both
within the administration and in Congress.
   Dole told reporters after the meeting that several lawmakers
made ``strong pitches'' to the president on behalf of the sale,
``the point being, if we're going to trade with Soviet Union, which
we are, then we have to be competitive, we have to meet world
prices.''
   ``We made our case to the president,'' said Dole, whose state is
a leading grain producer. ``I think there was general agreement
among those this morning that if we're going to be in this trade
game, we've got to be competitive. The subsidy's not very great in
this case, probably not as much as the storage costs.''
   The Bush administration, following the lead of the Reagan
administration, has called for eventual elimination of all export
subsidies. It has said, however, that it would not unilaterally do
away with such government farm support so long as other trading
nations subsidized their exports.
   Dole and other participants said Bush indicated he would make up
his mind on the subsidies later today, amid reports that the
president might decide on partial subsidies for the grain sales.
   The administration is divided on the proposed grain sale, with
the Agriculture Department supporting it and the Office of
Management and Budget and the National Security Council reportedly
opposing it.
   The sale would be made under a 1985 law, the Export Enhancement
Program, under which nations that buy U.S. agricultural goods
receive bonus quantities of commodities from government stockpiles.
</TEXT>
