<HEAD>Confederate Flags at Center of Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Controversy over the flying of confederate
flags in Alabama has flared with the arrests of three black men,
including a minister, after a confrontation at a drive-in
restaurant.
   Black leaders expressed anger about the arrests and met Monday
night at Tabernacle Baptist Church to discuss the Sunday incident.
   Mayor Joe Smitherman said police reports indicate the rear
window of a car containing two young black men was broken out or
shot out by two white men in a pickup truck flying two Confederate
flags. The arrests occurred after men with an ax handle cornered a
white youngster who was not involved, the mayor said.
   Three black men, including the Rev. George Bennett, were charged
with disorderly conduct. Bennett said he responded to a call from
his nephew, who had been arrested at the drive-in, ``and I wound up
being arrested, too.''
   Smitherman promised Monday to try to prevent a recurrence.
   ``I don't object to the Confederate flag flying over the Capitol
or behind City Hall in Selma, but when somebody tries to use it to
stir up trouble, it's coming down,'' Smitherman said.
   The Confederate battle flag flies atop the Capitol dome in
Montgomery. Fourteen black legislators are appealing their
conviction on misdemeanor trespass charges resulting from a march
to the Capitol grounds in protest of the flying of the Rebel flag.
