<FIRST>u i PM-Brazil-Bombing     05-02 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Bombing,0271</SECOND>
<UNK>New Monument To Striking Workers Wrecked By Bomb</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb today wrecked a new
monument in Volta Redona honoring three striking steelworkers who
were killed by army troops, officials said.
   No injuries were reported in the predawn blast. TV Globo, the
nation's largest commercial television network, said a previously
unknown group, Patriotic Front, claimed responsibility for the
blast.
   The monument was unveiled Monday during Labor Day commemorations
in Volta Redonda, a town 80 miles west of Rio. It depicted the
three victims, with a concrete spear stabbing a worker.
   The monument was designed by architect Oscar Niemeyer, a
communist who designed most of the public buildings in Brasilia,
the nation's capital.
   Police in Volta Redonda said the monument was ``seriously
damaged, although not completely destroyed.''
   The officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, added, ``The
explosion was very powerful. The only reason there were no injuries
was because of the time _ 3 a.m.''
   Niemeyer said in a radio interview he was ``deeply shocked'' and
offered to design another monument.
   TV Globo said the blast broke windows 500 yards away and
scattered fragments across a downtown plaza.
   Brazil regained civilian rule, under President Jose Sarney, in
1985, following a 21-year right-wing military regime. Sarney's
administration has been marked by financial chaos, runaway
inflation and almost daily strikes.
   Last Nov. 9, army troops, with Sarney's authorization, invaded
the government-run National Steel Company in Volta Redonda, which
had been occupied by strikers seeking higher pay and shorter
working hours. Three workers were killed.
</TEXT>
