<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vermont has been courting movie makers,
but the state almost blew it when it sent Don Johnson a fat tax
bill for his work here.
   The ``Miami Vice'' star got a bill in February for more than
$50,000 of the money he earned in 1987 while filming the movie
``Sweetheart's Dance'' in Hyde Park.
   ``He was upset because he felt he was being singled out,'' said
Don Lyons, a spokesman for the state film bureau, which promotes
Vermont as a movie location.
   On Monday, the state Senate Finance Committee considered a tax
exemption for out-of-state actors and film crews who are in Vermont
for under four months.
   The proposal would be retroactive to Jan. 1, 1986, which would
let Johnson off the hook.
   The state administration believes the money the film industry
brings to Vermont far exceeds what could be raised by taxing actors
and crew members.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Bush introduced comedian Garry
Shandling at a correspondents dinner as just an average citizen he
pulled out of the White House tour line, it wasn't that far from
the truth.
   Shandling was invited to the dinner last weekend by a Washington
Post reporter who also arranged a tour of the White House for
Shandling and his girlfriend. Bush walked by on his way to the Oval
Office and recognized the star of ``It's Garry Shandling's Show,''
which airs on Fox and on Showtime cable.
   ``He said what are you doing in town? and I said, well, I'm
going to the correspondents dinner tonight. He said, well, we
should do something together on stage. I said, no, no, no, no, no,
I just can't, I said I'm on vacation, and I thought he was
completely joking,'' Shandling said.
   ``In fact, I said on stage I thought the president was joking
because I'd never taken him seriously before.''
   Shandling said he spent an hour with Bush and his staff, helping
prepare the president's comedy routine for the dinner.
   ``He said, `I'll say I pulled you out of the line,' and I said,
`Well, I'll say I was in the liberal line, which is the line that
has to pay to get into the White House.' And he just laughed very
hard at that joke,'' Shandling said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singing cowboy Gene Autry, actor James
Garner and golfer Sam Snead will take part in the Indianapolis 500
Festival Parade.
   Autry will be grand marshal of the May 27 parade, which will
have an American West theme.
   Garner, an auto racing fan, drove the pace car at the
Indianapolis 500 in 1975, 1977 and 1985. In the late 1960s, he
owned a racing team.
   Others participating in the parade include former ``Real
People'' host Sarah Purcell and actor Pat Buttram of ``Green
