<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DeafJurors     05-02 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaf Jurors,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles County Pays for Sign Interpreters for Deaf Jurors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county has broken the sound barrier in
court by paying for a sign-language interpreter for a partly deaf
person called to jury duty.
   ``At least deaf people now have the option of serving on a jury
just like everybody else,'' said Nathan Shapiro, an engineer who
was assigned the interpreter Monday because of a settlement reached
in October of a lawsuit.
   The Council for the Deaf sued Los Angeles County in 1981 for
refusing to pay the $4,000 Shapiro spent to hire an interpreter to
help him serve as a juror in 1980. Hearing impairment had been a
valid excuse for being excused from jury duty.
   Shapiro was summoned again in 1987 for jury duty and the county
still refused to pay for an interpreter, said Marcella Meyer,
council executive director.
   The new interpreter service will cost the county $30,000 for a
full-time coordinator plus $171 a day for each interpreter.
   ``It's about time that deaf people had the right to serve as
jurors if they want to,'' Meyer said. ``This is one step forward.''
   ``We hope this will encourage other deaf and hearing-impaired
people to become jurors,'' said Ed Johnson, director of the
county's interpreter services. ``We now have seven others in our
jury pool waiting to be assigned to a court.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
