<DOCNO> AP890502-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Concorde     05-02 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Concorde,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Goes Supersonic to Zambia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE CONCORDE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II, who has flown the
equivalent of the distance between the Earth and the moon and more
than halfway back, broke another barrier Tuesday by becoming the
first supersonic pontiff.
   Like the seasoned traveler that he is, the pope took it in
stride, quietly reading a book about animal behavior as the Air
France jetliner flashed across the Indian Ocean toward Africa at
1,350 mph _ twice the speed of sound.
   ``He's showing mild curiousity,'' said Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro as the needle-nosed Concorde carried the pope from the
French island of Reunion to Lusaka, Zambia, on the third leg of his
four-nation nine-day pilgrimage.
   The chief cabin steward said John Paul read during his two hours
and 34 minutes aboard, but he also took time out to learn some
details of the 1,920-mile flight.
   ``He was very interested, he asked us about the speed and the
altitude,'' said the steward, who declined to give his name.
   The crew served 1983 vintage Perrier-Jouet champagne, but the
pope opted for mineral water and orange juice.
   ``He said he had a long day ahead of him, and he wanted to keep
a clear head,'' the steward said, adding that the pontiff only
picked at lunch of goose liver pate with truffles, lobster in
Sauterne sauce, potatoes, rice creole, cheeses and lemon meringue
dessert.
   The Concorde left Reunion and rocketed out over the ocean at a
speed of 225 mph in 30 seconds. About 10 minutes later, the digital
speedometer in the cabin showed the Concorde had reached Mach 1, or
675 mph.
   After another 10 minutes, the speed doubled to Mach 2 as the
Concorde reached 50,000 feet.
   Since the Concorde does not fly at supersonic speed over land,
it detoured around Madagascar and gradually slowed to subsonic
before reaching the African continent over Mozambique. The plane
touched down at 170 mph.
   Prior to the flight, Vatican officials said the pope would fly
only at subsonic speed to Africa, but the crew evidently wanted to
show their distinguished passenger what the Concorde was capable of.
   John Paul returns to a less-exotic form of air travel Wednesday,
taking an Air Zambia ART42 passenger plane to the northern city of
Kitwe.
   Easily the most traveled pope in history, John Paul has flown
more than 370,000 miles in the 10{ years of his papacy.
   He has far surpassed Pope Paul VI, who became known as the
``apostle on the move'' in nine overseas journeys between 1964-70.
John Paul is on his 41st trip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Kurds     05-02 0111</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Kurds,0116</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Killed by Kurdish Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERUH, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas killed four soldiers and a
villager in this southeastern township, it was reported Tuesday.
   The gunmen, believed to be Kurds, stopped a van Monday evening,
forced the five out and shot them, the Anatolia news agency said.
The gunmen escaped, the dispatch said.
   It did not say what the motive for the killings might have been.
   Kurdish guerrillas are fighting for an independent communist
state in southeastern Turkey. About 800 civilians and military
personnel and an equal number of Kurdish rebels have been killed
since 1984.
   Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's population of
52 million.
</TEXT>
