<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Fence     05-02 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Fence,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Begins Dismantling Border Fence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEGYESHALOM, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers today began tearing town a
barbed wire fence and electronic alarm system that separates
Hungary from Austria.
   The event marked the ``closing of an era'' in Hungary's
relations with the West, said Andras Koevari of the Interior
Ministry.
   ``Hungarian glasnost has many faces, and one of them is the
world passport which moved Hungary closer to Western Europe,'' he
said, referring to laws instituted last year that allow Hungarians
to go to the West as often as they can afford to do so.
   Because Hungarians do not require visas to visit Austria,
millions have taken advantange of the new regulations to travel
regularly.
   The work begun today to dismantle the fence on Hungary's
220-mile border with Austria is to be completed by Dec. 1, 1990.
   The fence, an electronic alarm system which is about a mile from
the actual border, once was used to help prevent Hungarians from
escaping to the West.
   A border official, Tibor Vidus, said about 97 percent of those
who recently have tried to flee across the Hungarian border to
Austria are not Hungarians. When work is completed, he said, there
will be no fence on the border with Austria.
   Balazs Novoki, another border official, said the border was
tightly secured until 1955 and was resecured with minefields after
a failed 1956 anti-Soviet revolt.The mines were removed because
Austria complained floods sometimes washed the explosives across
the border, killing farm laborers.
   The electronic signal fence was installed by 1972.
   The Communist Party leadership decided in February that
considering Hungary's improved relations with the West, the
electronic fence should be removed.
</TEXT>
