<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Egypt-Libya     05-02 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Egypt-Libya,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Grants Asylum to Libyan Pilot, Temporarily Opens Borders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt will grant political asylum to a
Libyan pilot who flew his helicopter to southern Egypt last week, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   A government source also said Egypt has opened its border with
Libya to allow thousands of Egyptian workers to return home for a
religious holiday.
   The daily Al-Messa newspaper quoted unidentified sources as
saying the pilot, Maj. Fath'i Miloud al-Saghir, would not be
returned to Libya, where he would face a death sentence. The
26-year-old pilot peeled off from a five helicopter squadron flying
from Libya to Sudan on April 27 and landed in southern Egypt, where
he requested asylum.
   According to a government source, Egypt has opened its border
with Libya to allow tens of thousands of Egyptian workers there to
come home this weekend for Eid, the end of the Islamic month of
Ramadan.
   Libya and Egypt have no diplomatic relations. Relations soured
in 1972 after Cairo spurned a bid by Libyan leader Col. Moammar
Gadhafi to merge the countries.
</TEXT>
