<FIRST>r w AM-DataBook     05-02 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Data Book,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>How Many Cows? How Many Cars? How Many Credit Cards?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How many cars are there in the United States?
What percentage of state prison inmates never finished high school?
Where do you find such facts? Has the government got a book for you!
   To the delight of statisticians and trivia fans alike, the
government is publishing the 109th annual edition of the
Statistical Abstract of the United States.
   The book's 984 pages contain 1,450 charts and tables giving
details about business, society, economics and other aspects of
American life.
   For example:
   _There were 135.4 million cars in the United States as of 1986,
one for every 1.8 persons. Japan had one car per 4.2 people, while
in China there were 1,374 people per car.
   _There were 841.4 million credit cards in use in 1987, more than
three cards for every man, woman and child in the country.
   _There were 1,441 heart transplants in 1987, up from just 62 in
1981.
   _The United States was home to 10.3 million milk cows, 10.7
million sheep and lambs and 53 million hogs and pigs in 1988.
   _Sales of personal computers increased 651 percent from 1981 to
1987.
   _There were 38.7 million cable television subscribers in 1986,
at an average monthly fee of $11.09.
   _A profile of state prison inmates shows that 96 percent are
male; 54 percent have never been married; 62 percent failed to
finish high school and 31 percent were unemployed at the time of
their arrest.
   _Women make 5.1 visits to their doctor annually, compared with
4.8 for men. Women also go to the dentist more, 1.7 visits compared
with 1.4 for men.
   _New single-family homes averaged 1,755 square feet of space in
1987, up from 1,595 in 1980. Many added a garage and extra
bathrooms.
   _Nuclear energy provided 18 percent of the nation's electricity
in 1987, but accounted for more than half of that used in Vermont,
South Carolina and New Jersey.
   For the record, the volume costs $26 in paperback, $32
hardbound, and will be on sale at government bookstores and from
the Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C., 20402.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
