<FIRST>r a AM-SaltFlats     05-02 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salt Flats,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>BLM Proposes Joint Study On Bonneville Salt Flats' Woes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WENDOVER, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The famous Bonneville Salt Flats, the dry,
hard-packed lakebed where thrill seekers for decades have gone to
set world land speed records, are losing salt, and the government
wants to know why.
   The 100-square-mile area of smooth, uninterrupted surface, where
even jet-powered cars can run flat out for miles, has been
shrinking 1 percent a year for 28 years, said U.S. Bureau of Land
Management District Manager Deane Zeller.
   ``Given this long-term trend, it's apparent that the Salt Flats,
as we know them today, are in trouble. Clearly, some hard questions
need to be addressed,'' he said in a statement Monday.
   The BLM is asking state agencies, the U.S. Geological Survey,
racing interests and a potash company to join in a three-year,
$330,000 study of what can be done.
   Zeller said that while other salt flats exist in Australia and
Africa, none are of the quality and accessibility of the Bonneville
Salt Flats.
   The BLM has the backing of the Southern California Timing
Association for the study. The group, organizer of the largest of
the annual speed trials held on the salt, has complained for years
about deterioration of the racing surface.
   Many suspect a Wendover company's practice of draining brine
from land adjacent to the flats to recover potash.
   But Reilly Chemical Co. denies responsibility for any
deterioration and maintains there is no hard evidence of an overall
salt loss.
</TEXT>
