<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-02 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Female alligators that have no qualms
about going for a romantic tumble in the wilds are having trouble
breeding behind bars.
   Sometimes captive girl gators just need a good tranquilizer
before being artificially inseminated, said Paul Cardeilhac, a
wildlife reproduction specialist at the University of Florida
College of Veterinary Medicine.
   ``We were literally rodeoing the female gators before, and they
would rebel by not laying eggs for us,'' said Cardeilhac, who
conducts his research at Gatorland Zoo in Kissimmee, the world's
largest alligator farm.
   ``But we've found that a tranquilizing drug like Valium will
restrain them without interfering with the reproductive process or
affecting the hatchlings.''
   Reproduction in farm alligators is only 10 percent to 20 percent
as effective as in the wild, where females produce about 22
hatchlings each, he said.
   Cardeilhac, who has studied reproductive problems in captive
alligators for nearly a decade, made alligator-breeding history in
1981 when 11 healthy baby gators hatched as the result of
fertilization by his artificial insemination technique.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLOVIS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young inventors here have their priorities:
get your bed made, keep your big brother from hogging the
television and help grandma when you can.
   Students from kindergarten through eighth grade displayed the
fruit of their ideas as part of a program aimed at fostering
inventiveness.
   One popular invention at Saturday's award ceremoney was the
Bishop Bedmaker, created by Jeremy Bishop of Sandia Elementary
School.
   His device uses a bed-width roller at the head of the bed. Lines
fastened to the roller have clips at their free ends that are
clamped to the bedcovers. Cranking the roller winds the lines on
the roller and pulls the covers tightly to the head of the bed.
   ``I invented it because I hate to make my bed,'' Jeremy said.
``I want to make an electric one with a button.''
   Lockwood Elementary School fifth-grader Ricky Thompson designed
a key-lock for the on-off switch on the family TV set. He said he
invented it because his 15-year-old brother ``watches too much TV
and doesn't do his homework.''
   Kristen Dickinson of Cameo Elementary re-invented something that
once was a laundry fixture _ a wringer, mounted on a sink or
bathtub.
   ``My grandma has arthritis and couldn't wring out rags,''
Kristen said. ``It's good for small kids, too.''
</TEXT>
