<FIRST>r i AM-China-US     05-02 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>New U.S. Ambassador to China Arrives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James R. Lilley, a veteran foreign service
official who was born in China, arrived Tuesday to take up his post
as the new U.S. ambassador.
   Lilley succeeds Winston Lord, who returned to private life after
more than three years as Washington's top envoy to Beijing.
   He arrives at a time when Beijing is facing the most serious
outbreak of pro-democracy student demonstrations in the communist
government's 40-year history.
   One of his first tasks will be to monitor the first Sino-Soviet
summit in 30 years. Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev arrives May
15 for talks with China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping that will
normalize long-strained political relations.
   The United States has welcomed the Sino-Soviet rapprochement,
saying it will not affect the strong political and economic ties
between Washington and Beijing.
   Lilley, born in the Chinese coastal city of Qingdao, was
appointed national intelligence officer for China in 1975, the year
President Bush headed the U.S. liaison office in Beijing.
   He also has served in American missions in the Philippines,
Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, Taiwan and Hong Kong. From 1986 to 1989,
he was U.S. ambassador to South Korea.
   Before that, he was principal deputy assistant secretary for
East Asian and Pacific affairs in the State Department.
   Lilley, 61, studied classical Chinese at Hong Kong and Columbia
universities and has taught courses on Chinese economics at the
Johns Hopkins School for Advanced International Studies.
   He and his wife, Sally Booth Lilley, have three sons.
</TEXT>
