<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Nepal-India     05-02 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nepal-India,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nepal Won't Be Isolated, Envoy Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nepal's Washington ambassador said Tuesday his
landlocked country will continue expanding its relations with China
and might complain to the United Nations about economic pressure
from its other big neighbor, India.
   India's month-long cutoff of necessities to Nepal causes great
human hardship and threatens the stability of Nepal, said
ambassador Mohan Man Sainju.
   Nevertheless, he told an audience at the National Press Club,
his nation is still ``open to any dialogue, any approach suggested
by India'' for solving the crisis.
   Sainju described as ``beyond comprehension'' statements by
Indian External Affairs Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao and India's
Washington ambassador that there is no economic blockade and Nepal
has itself to blame for reduced supplies of necessities such as
oil, baby food, salt and medicine.
   Petroleum shipments have been held up since March 23, a week
before India declared that a treaty with Nepal had lapsed, he said.
   Sainju also said that the Nepalese finance minister, B.B.
Pradhan, plans ``to talk about a long-term arrangement with China''
on economic matters. Pradhan is in Beijing for meetings of the
Asian Development Bank and the Nepal-China joint economic
commission.
   If Nepalese policy openings to China upset India, let India say
so openly, Sainju suggested.
   Rao, in a long report to the Indian Parliament last week about
relations with Nepal, did not mention Nepal's recent arms purchases
or other contacts with China. But Sainju, asked if Nepal's
redefinition of political and military relationships is at the root
of the dispute with India, replied, ``I think so.''
   ``The realities that exist in 1989 have got to be taken into
account,'' he said. ``Nepal was isolated for so long. It never
wants to be isolated again.''
   Asked if Nepal would formally request help from other countries,
the United Nations or other international agencies, Sainju said:
   ``We may. The U.N. is a very important organization for small
countries, and Nepal is one of the countries really committed to
U.N. values.
   ``But we still believe good sense will prevail'' on the part of
India. ``We do not want to believe India ... is bullying its
neighbor.''
   The State Department last month urged India and Nepal to
negotiate their differences and declined comment ``on the relative
merits of this bilateral issue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
