<FIRST>r w AM-FBI-Libraries     05-02 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Libraries,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Says It May Release Details of Library Counterintelligence Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI said Tuesday it may release some
details of agents' visits to the nation's libraries to monitor
Soviet and East Bloc intelligence agents. The program has been
questioned by those who say it violates the confidentiality of
library users.
   The bureau has been conducting what it calls an ``awareness
program'' in the New York City area, telling librarians that Soviet
and East Bloc agents use libraries to seek technical data and to
approach potential recruits.
   The FBI also goes into libraries elsewhere in the country in
response to specific counterintelligence investigations of
suspected East Bloc agents who have used those facilities.
   The bureau says the program is a narrowly focused effort which
does not infringe on the public's use of the nation's libraries.
   ``There is not a widespread investigation ... tromping on the
rights of individuals engaged in the use of American libraries,''
said FBI spokesman Milt Ahlerich.
   The FBI's comments are in connection with an agreement reached
with a private group which had sued seeking access to some of the
information the bureau gathered in its investigations. The suit was
filed under the Freedom of Information Act.
   A stipulation reached between the bureau and the National
Security Archives was signed Monday by U.S. District Court Judge
Louis F. Oberdorfer.
   The bureau will begin processing more than 3,000 pages of
documents related to library visits in at least 13 states, said
archives director Scott Armstrong.
   The archives is a non-profit research facility that collects
declassified information on national security issues.
   Civil liberties and library groups have objected to the
surveillance program. They say it has a chilling effect on
constitutional free speech rights and violates state laws and
library rules designed to protect the confidentiality of library
users.
   Quinlan Shea, special counsel for the archives group, said the
stipulation is an important step toward responding to the concerns
of groups which have questioned the FBI's effort.
   ``We sensed in discussions that the bureau would like to sort of
reassure the library community that this isn't some half-crazed
search and destroy mission'' by the FBI in the nation's libraries,
said Shea.
</TEXT>
