<SECOND>AM-National Guard-Drugs,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another 36 Plans Approved for Expanded Use of Guard Units in War
on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has approved
plans submitted by another 36 states or territories to step up use
of their National Guard units in fighting drug trafficking, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   The additional approvals bring to 48 the number of plans now in
place for the expanded use of Guard units. It also expands to $25.2
million the amount committed to the drug-interdiction program for
the National Guard.
   The Pentagon action makes the states eligible for extra federal
funds from a special congressional appropriation of $40 million
approved last year to finance such National Guard operations.
   Cheney announced the first approvals on March 30, concentrating
then on 12 high-priority border states. Those 12 states together
were authorized to use 29.4 percent of the $40 million, or $11.8
million.
   On Tuesday, the Pentagon said Cheney approved commitment of
another $13.43 million to 34 states, Puerto Rico and the Virgin
Islands. Of those on the latest approval list, New York will
receive the most _ $1.8 million _ followed by Puerto Rico with $1.1
million and the Virgin Islands with $873,835.
   ``Remaining plans are in the final review process,'' the
Pentagon said.
   The Pentagon said the plans of each state varied to some extent.
   But in general, the state and territorial governments are
planning to increase National Guard operations by emphasizing more
``aerial photography and other imagery; radar surveillance;
long-range reconnaissance; assistance in searching containers, and
the transportation of law enforcement personnel, equipment and
seized substances.''
   In addition, the Pentagon said some of the state governments
planned to ``expand training of law enforcement personnel and
increase the loans of military equipment.''
   ``This expanded role does not include direct participation by
Guard personnel in police activities such as arrest and seizure,''
the Pentagon stressed, adding its goal is ``supporting civilian
drug law enforcement agencies in the nationwide crusade against
drugs.''
   Besides New York, the other states and the amounts their Guard
units are receiving include:
