<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Holocaust     05-02 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Holocaust,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Remembers Slain Family in Holocaust Observance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir read the names of
his slain parents Tuesday, joining thousands of Israelis who
remembered the 6 million Jewish victims of the Nazi Holocaust by
reciting their names at ceremonies.
   The programs at the parliament, army bases, holy sites and
schools came on an annual remembrance day marking the World War II
tragedy that presaged the founding of the Jewish state.
   About 100,000 Holocaust survivors have settled in Israel, and
the legacy of helpless Jews driven to their deaths in gas chambers
or shot anonymously in forests, has been a driving force behind the
nation's vigilance about security.
   This year's observance was organized around the theme ``Unto
every person there is a name,'' and participants in Israel and 15
other countries were expected to recite the names of some 300,000
Holocaust victims before sundown, Army radio reported.
   The 77-year-old head of the right-wing Likud bloc joined the
program outside Israel's parliament building, where six torches
flickered in the wind. Shamir lost his parents, two sisters, their
husbands and their children.
   ``My father, Shlomo Ysernitzky, who escaped before the train
left for a death camp and while seeking shelter among friends in
the village where he grew up, they, his friends from childhood,
killed him,'' Shamir said, his voice quavering uncharacteristically.
   He paused, then named as other Nazi victims his mother, Pearl;
his sisters, Miriam and Rivka; their husbands, Mordechai and
Yaacov, and their children.
   Shamir has never disclosed how his family perished, but they are
believed to have died in death camps, said his aide, Yossi Ahimeir.
The prime minister also read the names of 30 other victims before
other Cabinet members continued the listing.
   Shamir, born in Ruzinoy, Poland, immigrated to pre-state
Palestine alone in 1935. He helped found a resistance group, known
as the Israel Freedom Fighters, or the Stern Gang, which staged
raids against the British rulers in Palestine.
   He has seldom spoken about his personal loss, although he
frequently refers to the Holocaust and compares Israel's current
adversaries to the Nazis.
   Earlier Tuesday, Shamir condemned French President Francois
Mitterrand's meeting in Paris with PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
Israel considers the Palestine Liberation Organization a terrorist
group and refuses to deal with it.
   ``This man says a lot of things to the Jewish people,'' Shamir
said of Arafat on Israel radio. ``He is following the same
tradition as the Nazis.''
   Holocaust day is one of national mourning in Israel. Flags are
flown at half-staff, melancholy music is played on the radios and
entertainment places are closed.
   The day's events began when sirens sounded at 10 a.m. (3 a.m.
EDT), bringing pedestrias and cars to a standstill for two minutes
of silent tribute.
   At the Ben Yehuda outdoor shopping mall in Jerusalem, merchants
and shoppers paused to bow their heads.
   Name-reading ceremonies at schools and army bases were broadcast
on the radio. Survivors choked back tears as they recited names;
others told horrifying stories.
   Ruth Eliaz, a survivor of the Auschwitz death camp in Poland,
told how she gave her starving, 7-day-old daughter a fatal
injection of morphine at the coaxing of a Polish nurse who feared
both mother and child would be sent to the gas chambers.
   ``I killed my own little girl,'' she said.
   At the observance at the parliament, Dutch-born Leah Zonershein,
a survivor of the Bergen-Belsen death camp in Germany, recited the
names of her deceased parents, Chaim and Hannah, then could not
continue.
   She said later she felt it was necessary to summon bitter
memories to ensure the tragedy is not forgotten.
   ``Holocaust day became a routine thing here,'' said Mrs.
Zonershein, 62. ``The number, 6 million, says nothing to most
people. But name after name after name, that gets the message
across.''
   Holocaust day is observed midway between the anniversary of the
start of a 1943 Jewish uprising against German troops in Warsaw,
Poland, and Israeli Independence Day, which this year is May 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
