<DOCNO> AP890502-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CrackCleanup     05-02 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Cleanup,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Buys Houses To Get Rid of Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McKNIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug pushers aren't dealing across the street
and gunshots no longer interrupt services at a small Baptist church
since the congregation bought a few abandoned buildings used as
crack houses.
   The 293 members of Third Shiloh Baptist voted unanimously in
February to put down $80,000 for five houses with money they
started saving 20 years ago for a new church.
   ``We were afraid to come out,'' said Emma Snowden, a church
board member. ``And they weren't ashamed. The street had more
traffic than Canal Street,'' the city's main business thoroughfare.
   The church, and the houses, are a block from the Desire public
housing project _ the city's largest and one of its most notorious
for drug use and violence.
   Church complaints led to two busts in the last five months and
the sound of gunfire sometimes punctuated services, Snowden said.
   The congregation is now using federal money to renovate the
dwellings so the church can rent them out and stabilize the
neighborhood to keep dealers out.
   A bank was asking $90,000 for the properties but sold them for
much less, officials said. Benjamin Edwards, church board chairman,
said Shiloh is negotiating to buy two other houses from another
owner.
   The maximum federal grant for fixing up a three-bedroom house is
$8,500, and the landlord must rent it for 10 years to a low-income
tenant, said Shelia Danzey, director of the city office of housing
and urban affairs.
   Danzey said 1,000 units have been renovated in the city under
the program, but Third Shiloh's five are the first owned by a
church or community group.
   The tenants will pay about $125 a month for a three-bedroom
apartment and there is already a waiting list, Edwards said. Each
house has two units.
   Some of the rent money will go to a scholarship fund and 15
percent to 25 percent toward building the new church members were
saving for, he said.
</TEXT>
