<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     05-02 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Discussing U.S. Help in Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee appointed by Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir to work out details of his Palestinian elections proposal is
discussing ways to involve the United States in observing the
balloting, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   U.S. involvement, which could answer one Palestinian objection
to Shamir's plan, was among various tactics being studied on how to
conduct the proposed vote in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, said Shamir spokesman Yossi Ahimeir.
   In the occupied territories Tuesday, 12 Arabs were wounded in
clashes with troops, according to Arab reporters and hospital
officials.
   One of the reported victims was a 7-year-old girl shot in the
head in a clash in the Gaza Strip's Shati refugee camp.
   The worst confrontation was in the crowded market in the West
Bank city of Nablus, where soldiers opened fire on dozens of
stone-throwing protesters, the reporters said. Six people suffered
gunshot wounds, hospital officials said.
   About 3,000 police were deployed around Jerusalem's Old City for
Leilat El Kadr, the Moslem night of prayers marking the prophet
Mohammed's receiving the holy Koran.
   Soldiers were reported to be stopping young Palestinians in the
occupied territories from entering Jerusalem to prevent a
repetition of rioting that occurred on the first day of the Moslem
holy month of Ramadan.
   The main prayer takes place at the Al Aqsa mosque compound, one
of Islam's holiest sites and the location of the rioting. Israel
radio said 10,000 worshipers were expected at Al Aqsa, compared
with up to 50,000 in previous years.
   Israelis also marked a national holiday Tuesday to mourn the
Jewish victims of the Nazi Holocaust, and Shamir compared PLO
leader Yasser Arafat to the Nazis as he protested French President
Francois Mitterrand's meeting with Arafat in Paris.
   Shamir said on Israeli radio that Jews everywhere should beware
of Arafat.
   ``This man says a lot of things to the Jewish people. ... He is
following the same tradition as the Nazis,'' he said.
   The Polish-born prime minister later read the names of his own
family members killed by the Nazis. Hundreds of other Israelis
recited the names of other victims in memorial events throughout
the country.
   Arafat's visit sparked several protest demonstrations outside
the French Consulate in Jerusalem.
   The largest group, 50 members of the Temple Mount Faithful,
carried the French tricolor flag marked with a black stain.
   The group's leader, Gershon Salomon, said Mitterrand's meeting
with Arafat ``soiled France's honor'' and urged France to extradict
Arafat as a murderer. The group advocates rebuilding the Jewish
temple on the site now covered by the Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa
mosques.
   Ahimeir said Tuesday the premier has appointed a team to work
out a blueprint for elections in the occupied territories, despite
Palestinian demands that Israel withdraw its troops before any vote.
   Shamir's plan calls for elections to chose Palestinians from the
territories to negotiate with Israel on a five-year period of
autonomy, to be followed by talks on the final status of the lands
occupied since the 1967 Middle East war.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and Palestinians in the
territories have rejected the idea of limited autonomy under
continued Israeli control since it was first suggested more than 10
years ago.
   Shamir made his plan public last month in Washington after
international pressure built on Israel to find a way to end the
16-month Palestinian uprising, which has taken the lives of 458
Palestinians and 18 Israelis.
   Ahimeir said one idea considered for the balloting was some form
of active U.S. participation in overseeing the elections, which
would answer Palestinian and Arab demands for international
supervision of the vote.
   ``I think that U.S. participation and help can be considered,''
Ahimeir said. ``We are always ready to be assisted by the United
States which is genuinely interested in achieving peace ... and
enjoys the trust of both sides.''
   Israeli news reports said the blueprint might be presented to
U.S. officials by Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who is due to
visit Washington in three weeks. A Rabin spokesman declined comment.
   Rabin told representatives of Israel's collective farms in Tel
Aviv that Israel should not rush into elections ``out of the
blue,'' but should agree on an entire process for the vote.
   Facing complaints about stone-throwing attacks on the cars of
Jewish settlers in the occupied territories, Rabin suggested Israel
consider subsidizing protective windows in the vehicles of the more
than 70,000 settlers.
   It would cost $6.7 million to $8.3 million, and ``we will
suggest this to the residents of the territories, and we should
offer to subsidize it if necessary,'' he said.
</TEXT>
