<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     05-02 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Khmer Rouge Must Play Minimal Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Tuesday stepped up its
campaign against the Khmer Rouge rebels by saying that close ties
with a future Cambodian government would not be possible if it is
heavily influenced by that Marxist group.
   The statement by spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler came amid an
intensification of efforts by the Vietnamese-backed government in
Cambodia and non-communist rebel forces to reach an accommodation
on the shape of a future government.
   With Vietnam planning to withdraw the remainder of its forces
from Cambodia by this September, the United States has become
increasingly concerned about the possibility that the Khmer Rouge
could regain power there.
   The Khmer Rouge, the most militarily powerful of the three
resistance forces, are estimated to have killed more than one
million Cambodians during their 3{ years in power in the late 1970s.
   ``The United States is totally opposed to a return to dominance
in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   ``We believe that the best means to achieve this goal would be
acceptance by all parties of a comprehensive settlement agreement
under which the Cambodian people were able to determine their own
future through a process of free choice.''
   She reaffirmed the U.S. view that an interim coalition
government should be formed to organize elections and that Prince
Sihanouk, the former head of state, is a logical leader of such an
arrangement.
   She said that whether the Khmer Rouge, minus discredited leaders
such as Pol Pot, are permitted to participate in such an interim
government is one thing the Cambodian factions themselves will have
to decide.
   But, she said, that American ability to work with any future
Cambodian government ``would be related to the level of Khmer Rouge
participation in that government.''
   Ms. Tutwiler said it is imperative to have a settlement that
includes effective safeguards to keep the Khmer Rouge from
dominating Cambodia once more.
   ``We are convinced that in free and fair elections, the
Cambodian people would reject the Khmer Rouge,'' she said.
   As part of stepped-up U.S. diplomacy in the region, Vice
President Dan Quayle met on Monday with Sihanouk during a visit to
Indonesia.
   Sihanouk said later, after a meeting with Indonesian President
Suharto, said he was optimistic a settlement was within reach.
   The non-communist resistance is eager to reach a political
settlement with the Vietnamese-backed government before the
withdrawal of the Vietnamese forces. Without an agreement, there is
concern that Khmer Rouge will regain power in Phnom Penh because of
their superior military capability.
   The Bush administration has reflected its concern by considering
for the first time the provision of military aid to the two
non-communist factions.
</TEXT>
