<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     05-02 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bionic Duo Win Battle of Sunday Movies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's bionic heroes defeated some other people's
heroes on ABC and CBS to win the first Sunday movie showdown of the
May ratings sweeps.
   ``Bionic Showdown: The Return of the Six Million Dollar Man and
the Bionic Woman II'' ranked 11th for the week, with a Nielsen
rating of 17.6 and a 28 share.
   ABC's ``My Name is Bill W.,'' about the founder of Alcoholics
Anonymous, had a 15.2 and 24 and ranked 24th. Part one of CBS'
two-part ``Guts &amp; Glory: The Rise and Fall of Oliver North'' came
in third Sunday with a 14.0 and a 23 share to rank 31st.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 9.4 million homes
with television. The share is a percentage of sets actually in use.
   A repeat of ABC's ``Roseanne'' was the highest-rated show of the
week, edging a new episode of NBC's ``The Cosby Show.'' ``Cosby''
had a slightly lower rating but a higher share, apparently because
of daylight saving time when there are fewer viewers at 8 p.m. EDT
compared with 9 p.m. when ``Roseanne'' airs.
   The top 10 shows of the week were: ``Roseanne,'' ABC; ``Cosby,''
NBC; ``Cheers,'' NBC; ``A Different World,'' NBC; ``Murder, She
Wrote,'' CBS; ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Dear John,'' NBC; ``L.A.
Law,'' NBC; ``The Wonder Years,'' ABC, and ``Empty Nest,'' ABC.
   NBC won the week ending April 30, its 45th in a row, with an
average rating of 13.7 to CBS' 11.7 and ABC's 11.4. The week
included five days of the May sweep, one of four month-long periods
a year when local stations' ratings are measured.
   The ``CBS Evening News'' pulled into a tie with ``ABC World News
Tonight'' in the news ratings. Each had a 9.8 rating and 21 share.
``NBC Nightly News'' had an 8.7 rating and 19 share.
   The lowest-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ``Dream
Street,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Hard Time on Planet Earth,''
``Moonlighting,'' ``A Man Called Hawk,'' ``Over the Edge,''
``Living Large,'' ``Jim Henson,'' ``Heart and Soul'' and ``Code
One.''
</TEXT>
