<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Church     05-02 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Church,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forced Retirement for Head of State Office for Church Affairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the State Office for Church
Affairs who was associated with strong government control over
church life has been forced to retire, an Austrian Roman Catholic
newsletter said Tuesday.
   The retirement of State Secretary Imre Miklos as president of
the office as of Monday was confirmed by the Hungarian news agency
MTI, which said Miklos' duties were taken over by deputy president
Barna Sarkadi Nagy. No new president was appointed.
   Miklos's retirement came after what MTI described as ``crucial
changes'' in Hungarian church policy.
   It said the essence of the change is that state control is to be
withdrawn from all fields of church a life so as to ``finalize the
separation of the state and churches.''
   MTI said the change in church policy serves the purpose of
expanding the cooperation between the state and churches in the
social, political, cultural and educational spheres.
   The official report made clear the existing church affairs
office would be completely overhauled and given a new name in the
spirit of Hungary's political and social reforms.
   ``There is a need for open political activity in order to create
a forum for coordination of interests that would attract ...
church, state and party officials, as well as independent and
prestigious politicians,'' MTI said.
</TEXT>
