<FIRST>r w AM-MisguidedMissile     05-02 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Misguided Missile,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Delaying Deployment of Trident 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has found the mechanical problem that
caused a Trident 2 missile to explode last March, but corrective
design changes will contribute to a three-month delay in
deployment, a military official said Tuesday.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said a Navy board of
inquiry had blamed the failure on a mechanical linkage in the
first-stage nozzle.
   ``We now expect the first operational missiles to be at sea on
the (submarine) USS Tennessee in March'' of 1990, he said.
   The mechanical linkage is responsible for moving the rocket
nozzles back and forth during the early seconds after a launch. The
Pentagon previously had disclosed preliminary findings, made final
by the Navy board.
   ``They (the Navy) have decided that they have to do some
redesign and modification of the mechanical linkage that transmits
the nozzle position commands to the nozzle exit cone at the base of
the missile,'' Howard said.
   ``Incorporating these changes will allow us to conduct the next
test in July.''
   Howard declined to estimate the cost of the design changes, but
described them as ``fairly simple.'' The Navy said the missile's
builder, the Lockheed Corp., would have to bear the cost.
   The Navy's investigation began March 21, shortly after a Trident
2 missile fired from the Tennessee blew up just four seconds after
launch. The missile popped to the surface as planned and the first
stage ignited properly, but then the missile began spinning like a
burning pinwheel and exploded.
   It was the first submarine launch of the Navy's newest and most
powerful nuclear weapon.
   Howard said Tuesday the delay in deployment was based on two
other factors in addition to the design change.
   ``First, there has been a cessation of all propellant casting,
including the (Trident) second-stage motors, due to the explosion
at the Hercules plant in Magna, Utah, on March 29,'' he explained.
   ``Second, there's an on-going strike at the Kaiser (Aerotech)
plant in San Leandro, Calif., which has resulted in stoppage of
delivery of nozzles for both the second and third stage of the
Trident rocket motors. We anticipate that the delivery of those
will resume by June.''
   On Capitol Hill, Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House
Armed Services Committee, praised the Navy for its willingness to
delay the Trident's deployment, singling out program manager Rear
Adm. Kenneth Malley.
   ``I hope everyone will heap praise on the program manager for
striving to make his missile work rather than damning him for
failing to meet an arbitrary deadline _ the great crime of the B-1
(bomber),'' Aspin said.
   The three-stage Trident 2 is a more lethal version of the weapon
that is the heart of America's naval nuclear deterrent, the Trident
1. The new missile can deliver three to 12 nuclear warheads to
individual targets up to 6,000 miles away.
   The Navy says the new weapon is much more accurate than its
undersea predecessors _ Polaris, Poseidon and Trident 1 _ and can
match the targeting ability of land-based missiles even though it
is launched from a submerged, moving submarine.
   The Tennessee is the first of nine submarines slated to carry 24
of the missiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     05-02 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Offers to End Blockade; Shelling Persists</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun said
Tuesday he may compromise with Moslem militiamen to end the
fighting in Beirut, but will pursue diplomatic channels to oust
Syrian troops from Lebanon.
   The commander of Lebanon's mainly Christian army said he will
consider lifting a blockade of three illegal ports run by
Syrian-backed Moslem militias to end eight weeks of fierce fighting
that has killed 278 people.
   As he made the offer at a news conference, shelling duels
continued between Christian gunners and an alliance of Druse
militiamen and Syrian troops who have ignored Friday's cease-fire
call by the Arab League.
   Police said two people were killed and eight wounded Tuesday,
bringing the toll of wounded to 1,010 since the current fighting
erupted March 8.
   Asked about the blockade, Aoun said it ``could be suspended.''
   ``The ports issue is no longer the basic issue. Syrian military
presence in Lebanon is the issue,'' he said.
   Aoun had declared a ``war of liberation'' against 40,000 Syrian
troops deployed across 70 percent of Lebanon under a 1976 Arab
League peacekeeping mandate.
   But he added: ``The hot phase in the war of liberation is over
... We are prepared to pursue liberation through diplomatic means.''
   He said he was waiting to discuss the ports blockade Wednesday
with Arab League envoys due to arrive from Syria.
   League official Lakhdar Ibrahimi of Algeria and Ahmed Abdel-Aziz
Jassem, Kuwait's ambassador to Syria, will try to salvage the
cease-fire and finalize deployment of a multinational Arab observer
force.
   On Tuesday, Aoun called the Arab plans a ``breakthrough.''
   ``The observers will be watching the Syrians here and our
problem will be discussed by the forthcoming Arab summit
conference'' this month, Aoun said.
   He and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of breaking
their peacekeeping mandate by siding with the Moslems against the
Christians.
   In Damascus, Syria, diplomatic sources said the Syrian
government told the Arab League representatives that fighting would
persist until Aoun lifted the blockades.
   Ibrahimi was to meet Wednesday with acting Premier Salim Hoss,
head of the Moslem Cabinet in Lebanon's dual government.
   An aide to Hoss said they will discuss a compromise calling for
the deployment of Arab observers at militia-run ports to
``guarantee that they are not used for illegal activities.''
   The aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was
Ibrahimi's responsibility to convince Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt
and Shiite Moslem leader Nabih Berri to accept the proposed
solution.
   Syrian gunners maintained a sporadic bombardment of Lebanon's
310-square-mile Christian enclave throughout Tuesday. Each side
accused the other of starting the barrage.
   A police spokesman said Syrian gunners targeted the coastal
strip north of Beirut and prevented the French tanker Penhors from
approaching a power station to unload fuel oil.
   A main power cable was damaged in the barrage, stripping the
capital of its daily two-hour ration of electricity, said the
spokesman, who customarily is not named.
   Most civilians deserted their apartments and sought refuge in
underground shelters as they have most of the time since the
fighting began.
   A U.N. report published Tuesday said the battles have caused
$250 million in damage, destroyed two-thirds of Lebanon's fuel
storage facilities, hit 150 factories and 3,000 residential blocks,
and paralyzed industry.
   The Geneva-based Office of the U.N. Disaster Relief Coordinator
said the priority is setting up an emergency food reserve for
50,000 families and supplying drugs for the chronically sick.
   It said two-thirds of Lebanon's population is affected by the
strife, which has caused more than 100,000 people to flee abroad
and 500,000 to escape Beirut for safer parts of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
