<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     05-02 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Militants Attack Army Garrison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers at Sri Lanka's largest army
garrison Tuesday repelled an attack by Sinhalese militants who may
have been searching for weapons and killed at least three raiders,
a military official said.
   Five soldiers were injured in the raid, which came during a
heavy downpour said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   At least 100 militants attacked the Panagoda army garrison 12
miles southeast of Colombo with grenades and automatic weapons, he
said. The garrison usually holds between 10,000 and 15,000 soldiers.
   It was the biggest raid on an army post by militants since they
launched a bloody campaign to protest government peace overtures to
Tamil rebels, who are fighting for a separate homeland, the
official said.
   The Sinhalese militants, who belong to the left-wing People's
Liberation Front, said a 1987 India-backed peace accord giving the
Tamil minority limited autonomy made too many concessions. They
began killing government officials and ruling party members.
   India sponsored the accord, sending troops to northern and
eastern Sri Lanka, because of the sympathies of its own 60 million
Tamils to the rebel cause.
   Indian Foreign Secretary Shailendra Kumar Singh met Tuesday with
President Ranasinghe Premadasa to discuss the withdrawal of Indian
peacekeeping troops.
   Sri Lankan officials were to meet Wednesday with Tamil rebel
leaders for talks on ending their 6-year-old separatist war.
   The campaign for a Tamil nation has claimed 10,000 lives.
Sinhalese militants have been blamed for more than 3,000 killings
since January.
   The militants have attacked army camps and police stations to
get weapons. The military official said the attackers of the
Panagoda garrison penetrated the camp's perimeter and came within
yards of its armory before being beaten back.
   Army soldiers searched rice paddies and jungles near the camp
for the militants, he said.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, form 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 18 million people. They control the government and the
military.
   Tamils, predominantly Hindus, make up 18 percent of the
population and allege discrimination in jobs and education by the
Sinhalese.
</TEXT>
