<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1611EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Cheney-Soviet     05-02 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-Soviet,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney's Gloomy Soviet Forecast Was Personal View</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO Missiles Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney was just
speaking his mind and not representing the Bush administration when
he forecast failure for Kremlin chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
administration officials said Tuesday.
   There is widespread hope inside the government that the United
States can seize on Soviet arms control concessions, according to
official spokesmen.
   Cheney has been defense secretary for just over one month, and
his prediction in a televised weekend interview that Gorbachev
would fail and be replaced by a hardliner caused a stir in official
Washington.
   President Bush, Secretary of State James A. Baker III and White
House chief of staff John Sununu quickly stepped forward with more
optimistic assessments, although they did not publicly rebuke
Cheney.
   Despite the official optimism, there was cause to worry about
the future of Gorbachev's reform, officials said. Cheney's
pessimistic predictions came just a day after the Soviet Communist
Party newspaper Pravda, in an unprecedented development, published
five pages of speeches by party officials saying Gorbachev's
reforms had damaged the economy and were undercutting the Kremlin's
authority.
   And the Central Intelligence Agency declassified a report on
April 23 saying Gorbachev had been forced to alter or postpone many
planned reforms, including a key one, decontrolling prices.
   A significant segment of the U.S. intelligence community
believes that Gorbachev faces limited chances of success, although
many government analysts think the United States ought to take
advantage of his arms control concessions, according to
administration and congressional sources.
   Cheney predicted in a weekend interview that Gorbachev would
fail in his effort to reform the Soviet Union and likely would be
replaced by a hardliner. Therefore, he said, the United States
should not take any unilateral steps, such as removing any of the
324,000 U.S. troops stationed in Western Europe.
   A Pentagon official, speaking anonymously, denied that Cheney
was trying to offset West German pressure on the United States to
negotiate with Moscow to eliminate short-range nuclear missiles.
   ``He was not trying to be Machiavellian,'' said the Pentagon
official. ``He was just saying what he believes. In his mind, he is
still on Capitol Hill,'' where Cheney served congressman from
Wyoming for 12 years and was No. 2 in the Republican leadership.
   Bush, speaking Monday in New York, said the United States
``wanted to see perestroika (reform) succeed in the Soviet Union.
And likewise, we want to see success for the economic reforms in
China.''
   Success for Gorbachev would give the Bush administration a
chance to capitalize on the Kremlin leader's sweeping offers to cut
Soviet conventional forces in Europe and overall strategic arsenal
by half.
   Baker reaffirmed U.S. hopes for Gorbachev by reissuing the text
of a speech he gave last month.
   ``We very much want perestroika to succeed, and we very much
want the General Secretary (Gorbachev) to succeed. We think that's
in the best interest of the United States and the best interest of
the world because it will result in a more open, stable and secure
Soviet Union,'' said Baker's statement.
   Cheney sparked the controversy by saying in an interview
broadcast last Saturday that ``if I had to guess today, I would
guess ultimately he would fail,'' and would be replaced by a leader
``far more hostile'' to the West.
   Cheney said much the same thing last Tuesday, telling Congress
he had become convinced Gorbachev's reforms were sincere because it
was clear that ``the Soviet system has been a failure.''
   ``I think it's going to be extremely difficult for him to
succeed, and I think there is a very real likelihood that he'll
either have to reverse course, or that or one reason or another,
ultimately have to resort to force, perhaps in Eastern Europe,
perhaps in terms of dealing with the ethnic unrest inside the
Soviet Union,'' Cheney told the House Armed Services Committee.
   Cheney's remarks mirrored an assessment voiced last October by
Robert Gates, then the No. 2 official at CIA and now the deputy
White House national security adviser. Gates' comment sparked a
similar controversy, because then-President Reagan and George
Shultz, who at the time was secretary of state, publicly had placed
great faith in Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
