<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Weather     05-02 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Weather,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA: Wheat Crop Still Very Dry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains have helped the western Corn Belt
and nothern Great Plains, but much of the sorely damaged winter
wheat area is still parched from lack of moisture, a government
report said Tuesday.
   Winter wheat was in ``mostly fair to poor'' condition during the
final week of April, particularly in the central and southern areas
of the plains, the Joint Agricultural Weather Facility said. Butg
rain helped improve winter wheat in the northern Great Plains.
   ``In Kansas, high temperatures and wind stressed winter wheat,''
the report said. ``Condition was mostly very poor to poor. Crop
development was poor in most fields. In Texas, winter wheat was
mostly fair to poor.''
   Lack of moisture continued to put stress on Nebraska's winter
wheat, and crop condition was reported as mostly poor to fair. Rain
improved the crop in Montana and South Dakota.
   Rain slowed planting of spring wheat, which is far behind for
this time of season. In North Dakota, planting was 16 percent
complete, 23 percentage points behind normal.
   But corn planting spurted ahead sharply, reaching 25 percent
completion, a 17-point advance from the week before, the report
said. Producers planted over a third of their corn acreage in
Illinois, Kansas and Missouri during the week.
   Corn planting progress was 13 percentage points behind the
normal pace of of 25 percent in Indiana, and 22 points behind in
Ohio, where 28 percent of the acreage is usually planted by now,
the report said.
</TEXT>
