<FIRST>r w AM-US-MiddleEast 380   05-02 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Middle East, 380</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Alarmed Over West Bank Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed alarm on
Tuesday about ``the rising tide of violence'' in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip as it offered its first public comment about recent
assassinations of Arabs accused of collaborating with Israeli
occupation troops.
   The killings of Palestinians by other Palestinians, occurring
amid the backdrop of the uprising in the occupied territories, have
increased after a Palestinian underground group issued a call for
stepped-up action against collaborators.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the killings
on either side ``frustrate the search for peace.''
   The Palestinians attacked as collaborators were accused of
working with the Israeli army, the occupation administration or the
Israeli intelligence service.
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens has accused the Palestine
Liberation Organization of conducting a ``wave of terror'' to
undermine Israel's proposal for elections in the occupied
territories.
   Israel plans to hold elections among the 1.4 million
Palestinians on the West Bank and Gaza to choose leaders to
negotiate an interim self-rule arrangement. Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir has barred negotiating with the PLO, which last year
declared a Palestinian state.
   President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III have
endorsed the proposal as a step toward an overall settlement of the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Asked about the killings, State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler said:
   ``We are alarmed by the rising tide of violence, and are shocked
by the increasing human toll in the West Bank and Gaza.''
   The spokeswoman pointed out that during the past two weeks, 20
Palestinians have been killed and about 200 others wounded in
clashes with the Israeli Defense Forces.
   ``Fourteen Palestinians have been killed by other Palestinians
during the same period. These actions by both sides frustrate the
search for peace,'' Ms. Tutwiler added.
   She said the United States urges all sides to ``exercise
restraint and replace violence with a climate conducive to
political dialogue.''
   Asked if the killings could make it more difficult for Israel to
conduct the elections, Ms. Tutwiler said ``any type'' of violence
was ``not conductive to moving the peace process forward.''
   Some 458 Palestinians and 18 Israelis have died since the
uprising began in December 1987.
</TEXT>
