<HEAD>Walesa To Address AFL-CIO in First U.S. Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AFL-CIO Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa will visit the
United States for the first time in November to address an AFL-CIO
convention, federation leaders said Tuesday.
   Walesa has been denied permission in the past to visit the
United States but an adviser in Washington to attend the spring
meeting of the AFL-CIO's governing body said Walesa would be
allowed to travel to the convention.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland, whose efforts to visit Walesa
in Poland have also been stymied by Warsaw, has accepted a
reciprocal invitation to visit Poland next year, a Kirkland
spokesman said.
   Kirkland said that, with the Polish government's recent
recognition of Solidarity and announced plans for democratic
election reforms, the AFL-CIO will support Bush administration
plans to give new economic aid to Poland.
   The federation's support, he said, was dependent ``on continued
progress in the area of human rights.''
   Still, while calling the apparent approval of Walesa's U.S.
visit a welcome step, Kirkland could not disguise his contempt for
the Polish government, which had outlawed Solidarity since its
inception in the early 1980s.
   ``I don't give a damn about the backing of the Polish
government,'' Kirkland said when asked whether Walesa would be
addressing the convention as a representative of Warsaw. ``He is
not an emissary of his government. I'm not interested in dealing
with emissaries of his government. He, all his life, has been a
fighter for free and independent trade unionism and that's what he
represents and what he stands for in the world today.''
   Jacek Kuron, a Walesa adviser and candidate for Parliament in
the June 6 Polish elections, met with the AFL-CIO executive council
Tuesday afternoon to discuss the Walesa visit and ways U.S. unions
could assist Solidarity.
   AFL-CIO spokesman Rex Hardesty said that support in the past has
been limited because Solidarity was banned but has included basic
printing and office supplies.
   Now, Hardesty said, the federation and a number of its member
unions were interested in providing Solidarity with additional
financial support and equipment as it works to recruit members and
support candidates in elections.
