<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FreeArms     05-02 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Free Arms,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Would Give Away Arms to Fight Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration asked Congress on
Tuesday for authority to give away weapons to help Western
Hemisphere armies fight drug traffickers.
   Lt. Gen. Charles W. Brown, head of the Defense Security
Assistance Agency, said weapons furnished without charge would be
``excess defense articles.'' He told the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee that they would be given to military forces in Latin
America and the Caribbean.
   He said the administration is asking $21 million for the purpose
in the year that begins Oct. 1, beyond the present spending level.
   ``The biggest increase in this group is for Colombia, where the
activities of drug barons and insurgent groups, sometimes working
together, threaten the very survival of the legal system and
democratic government,'' he said.
   He added that the next largest increase would go to Peru because
it is in a similar situation, and there would also be increases for
Bolivia and the eastern Caribbean. Drug traffickers often use
Caribbean islands as relay points for drugs from South America.
   His prepared testimony did not mention Mexico, another major
source of narcotics. Nor did it list the arms to be given under the
new program.
   The ``intention would be to make equipment available at the
low-tech end of the spectrum, (that is) basic military equipment
suitable for use in low-intensity conflict against drug
traffickers,'' he said.
   Brown said that U.S. efforts at cooperation had been mostly with
local police, with occasional use of U.S. military transport.
   ``We believe that local military forces are ready to and must
take a larger role in these efforts,'' he added.
   ``They are the only forces large enough to do it; they have the
infrastructure; they can act as a disciplined and trained force,
and it is far better that they take this role rather than U.S.
combat forces.''
   At home the Pentagon has resisted any move to have its forces
take part in drug arrests or investigations, though it cooperates
in the battle against narcotics by lending its equipment to law
enforcement agencies.
   Brown said that in Latin America, the armed forces need U.S.
money for equipment, training and support if they are to do more
against drugs.
   ``This is not to say that the military can supplant the local
police forces, but they have a role to play,'' he added.
   He noted that the Colombian and Peruvian forces are also
fighting insurgents who have roots and objectives independent of
drug dealers, though he said there are tactical alliances between
them.
</TEXT>
