<SECOND>AM-Pa Lottery,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Ticket Holders Claim Share of Pennsylvania Jackpot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two couples checked in at Pennsylvania
lottery headquarters Tuesday to claim a share of a North American
record jackpot of $115.5 million, leaving only one of the 14
winning tickets unaccounted for.
   The 12th and 13th ticketholders included a naturalized American
couple from China, Alex and Typin Mark of Wayne, a Philadelphia
suburb. They said they would use their winnings to educate their
three children and quit their jobs.
   Mark said he would ``invest the money and live comfortably for
the rest of my life.''
   Also presenting a ticket from the April 26 drawing were Ray and
Diane Novotny, both 46, of the Philadelphia suburb of Malvern. They
refused to talk with reporters.
   Lottery spokeswoman Terry Murphy said the Novotnys had bought 50
tickets and let the computer pick the numbers. Novotny would not
tell lottery officials where he worked.
   Each winning ticket is worth $8.3 million, to be paid in 26
annual installments of $317,524.67 before taxes.
   The remaining ticket holder has until April 26, 1990, to claim a
share of the Super 7 prize.
   Mark said he will leave his job as a mechanical engineer at the
Philadelphia Navy Yard, where he has worked for 27 years. He said
his wife already quit her job at a Chinese restaurant.
   Both are 56 and came from Canton, China. Mark has been in the
United States since 1947 and his wife has been here since 1950.
   Mark said he waited until Tuesday to come forward because he
wanted to check with a lawyer and plan what to do with the money.
Mark said he bought 30 tickets and let the computer pick the
numbers. He usually spends $5 a week on the lottery.
   Ms. Murphy said validation of the winning tickets should be
completed later this week, and the first checks presented next week.
   Other unofficial winners in the jackpot so far include 14
workers from a Windham, Ohio, brick factory; a 74-year-old widow
from Lebanon, Pa., and a chiropractor and his wife from New
Brighton.
</TEXT>
