<FIRST>r w AM-SubRadiation     05-02 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sub Radiation,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenpeace Cites Radiation Threat From Sunken Soviet Sub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corrosion of the nuclear reactor aboard a
Soviet submarine that sank off Norway April 7 may eventually lead
to the release of huge amounts of radioactivity, the environmental
group Greenpeace said Tuesday.
   The group said a study done for it by John Large and Associates,
a nuclear engineering consulting firm in London, concluded that the
submarine may release up to 20 million curies of radioactivity if
the vessel is not recovered.
   That is equal to about one-third of the radiation released by
the April 1986 explosion at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in
the Soviet Ukraine, Greenpeace said. Thirty-one people died in the
Chernobyl accident.
   The Soviet submarine caught fire and sank in 5,000 feet of water
off northern Norway. Soviet officials said 42 of the 69 sailors on
board were killed.
   Moscow said earlier this month that a decision on whether to
attempt to raise the sub will not be made for several months. It
said the vessel's two nuclear reactors were shut down before the
crew evacuated and that there was no danger of radiation leaks. But
Greenpeace took issue with that assertion.
   ``Even if the reactor containment structures weren't damaged by
the fire, the collision with the ocean floor or the deep water
pressure, the protective structure will erode before the reactors
are safe,'' said Steve Shallhorn, a Greenpeace representative.
</TEXT>
