<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-US     05-02 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-US,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister's Visit to U.S. Returns Attention to Trade Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All dollar figures U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's trip to the
United States this week puts the spotlight back on the Canada-U.S.
free trade agreement while his government faces heated debate over
efforts to cut the budget deficit.
   He receives an award Wednesday in Boston from the private World
Affairs Council, in large part for his role in leading Canada to
sign the sweeping trade agreement that eases investment barriers
and phases out all remaining tariffs between Canada and the United
States over the next decade.
   On Thursday, he visits the White House, where he will meet with
President Bush for the second time this year. The talks are
expected to concentrate on the trade pact and acid rain, always a
major topic in Canadian-U.S. relations.
   Mulroney led his Progressive Conservative Party to a second
consecutive majority government last fall in a campaign dominated
by the issue of whether to proceed with the trade agreement he
signed in January 1988 with President Ronald Reagan.
   With Mulroney's victory clinching the way for the pact to take
effect as scheduled Jan. 1, the attention of the prime minister and
other senior officials turned to the budget deficit, which is
higher per capita in Canada than in the United States.
   His opponents, who charged that free trade would force Canada to
cut its traditional network of social protection for its
population, now say the election did not give Mulroney a mandate to
tackle the soaring public debt.
   ``It is a full-scale, all-out assault on the weak, the poor, the
disadvantaged, the dispossessed,'' Liberal Party leader John Turner
said after the budget for the 1989-90 fiscal year was released last
week.
   ``This budget is proof that nothing they said, nothing the prime
minister committed himself and his government to during the last
election, is true,'' Turner said.
   The budget raises taxes and cuts federal spending in areas from
the military to rail service and child care plans, although it
still leaves a deficit of $25.6 billion. Among the most unexpected
steps was the elimination of the controversial program to spend
$6.7 billion for a fleet of nuclear-powered submarines.
   The prime minister has said repeatedly that the effort to bring
the deficit under control is critical to Canada's future.
   ``Only by measures to reduce the burden of the debt can
Canadians avoid a repetition of the excessive unemployment and
inflation rates of the early 1980s,'' he wrote in the speech that
opened the new session of Parliament last month.
   The debt now stands at $273 billion after the government ran a
$25.2 billion deficit in the 1988-89 fiscal year. The amount is
about 5 percent of gross domestic product, about double the U.S.
ratio.
   Bush made Ottawa his first foreign stop after his inauguration
with a half-day visit to meet with Mulroney in February. The U.S.
leader promised to move quickly with congressional legislation to
control acid rain, which Canada blames for killing 14,000 lakes in
the eastern part of the country.
   The two nations are each other's largest trading partner, with
two-way trade amounting to more than $150 billion annually.
</TEXT>
