<FIRST>r w AM-US-WHO     05-02 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-WHO,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Leader Complains of Baker Position on PLO, WHO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker's threat to
cut all U.S. financial support to the World Health Organization if
it admits the PLO is ``beyond comprehension,'' a representative of
the Arab League complained on Tuesday.
   Clovis Maksoud, Arab League representative to the United States
and United Nations, said in a statement that Baker's position was
``deeply regrettable.''
   On Monday, Baker said he would recommend to President Bush that
the United States withhold contributions to any U.N. organization
that votes to admit the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Baker argued that PLO admission would harm the Middle East peace
process and the U.N. itself.
   The PLO has applied for full membership in the WHO, the U.N.
agency that oversees health programs around the globe. The
166-member organization is due to vote on the matter next week in
Geneva.
   Meanwhile, Hiroshi Nakajima, the head of the organization,
visited the State Department to discuss the matter, according to
department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   Ms. Tutwiler said Nakajima, a Japanese physician, met with the
acting assistant secretary of state for international
organziations, N. Charles Smith.
   Nakajima also met with some of more than 50 members of Congress
who have written a letter to Baker saying they favored cutting off
funds to the WHO or any other U.N. agency that admitted the PLO.
   Nakajima has said he has tried to persuade PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat to withdraw the application, apparently as a means to defuse
the situation.
   Maksoud, of the Arab League, argued in his statement that
inclusion of the PLO would contribute to the WHO's ``universality
and effectiveness,'' and that the PLO was seeking ``to benefit from
membership in these humanitarian agencies.''
   ``The threat `to make no further contribution, voluntary or
assessed,' might be the language of a big power but not the
parlance of a great power. We in the Arab world would want to
preserve our assessment of the great United States,'' Maksoud's
statement said.
   The United States pays about 25 percent of World Health
Organization expenses. This amounted to about $150 million in the
past two years.
   The PLO is recognized by all 21 Arab governments as the
legitimate representative of the Palestinian people.
   Last year, the PLO declared statehood on land held by Israel.
However, the State Department contends the PLO is not a state,
failing to meet the criteria of being a state, such as control of
territory.
</TEXT>
