<FIRST>r w AM-Skinner-Spill     05-02 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Spill,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Says Nature Can Do Some Spill Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said
Tuesday that some of the Alaskan oil spill will have to be left to
the cleansing forces of nature, but he said an all-out cleanup
effort still is needed.
   Skinner, who is to make his second trip to Alaska Wednesday as
overall coordinator for cleanup of the March 24 oil tanker spill,
said he expected forces involved in the effort to double or triple
in size by the end of the month.
   In a speech at the National Press Club, Skinner called the
spilling of 11 million gallons of crude oil into Prince William
Sound ``the most significant environmental disaster this nation has
ever faced.'' But he said the cleanup operation, to be paid for by
the oil industry, could add $100 million to $500 million to
Alaska's economy, which he said is more than the effect of the
fishing industry.
   Skinner said he would reserve judgment on Exxon's latest plans
for the cleanup, which include burning and burying recovered sludge
and leaving some lightly soiled beaches to the cleansing forces of
nature.
   The plan requires the approval of the Coast Guard commandant,
Adm. Paul A. Yost, who criticized some aspects of it Tuesday as
thin. The transportation secretary, who oversees the Coast Guard,
said he would decide within a week whether to approve the plan.
   Skinner said that on some beaches, ``nature will do its work,''
but he said the state and Exxon will have to focus all summer on
cleaning up as much as possible.
   ``My position is that we can't do enough (cleaning up,)'' he
said. ``If it's anywhere close to being a viable opiton, we ought
to do it.''
   Skinner cautioned against cleanup efforts that may do damage to
the environment, but did not point to any specific plan of Exxon.
   ``When you are dealing in an area that is remote and has a lot
of nature at work, you want to be sure you don't cross the line,''
he said.
   ``The oil industry will have to demonstrate that it is capable
of cleaning up its mess,'' Skinner said. ``If they don't, it will
be very difficult for them to develop domestic reserves.''
   The secretary said he was traveling to Alaska with officials
from the Coast Guard, White House and Congress.
</TEXT>
