<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay 1stLd-Writethru a0629 05-02 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Paraguayans Satisfied With Rodriguez Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-13, `His coup...the coup.' with four grafs to
UPDATE with U.S. reax; pickup 14th pvs, `Partial official...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents complained of voting
irregularities, but it was clear Tuesday that most Paraguayans were
solidly behind the general who overthrew dictator Alfredo
Stroessner.
   Official returns gave Gen. Andres Rodriguez nearly three-fourths
of the vote for president in Monday's election, and his Colorado
Party won firm control of Congress.
   ``Half the vote for Rodriguez was a `thank you' for overthrowing
Stroessner,'' said Aldo Zuccolillo, editor of the newspaper ABC
Color. His paper resumed publishing in March, five years after
Stroessner's regime closed it.
   Susana Jara, a 50-year-old fruit vender at the Asuncion public
market, said: ``After 35 years of dictatorship, you could not
expect any other result because the people are very grateful to him
for putting his life in danger to bring us freedom.''
   Rodriguez, who has been provisional president since the coup
Feb. 3, said Tuesday he was ``pleased and happy that I have the
affection of the people and that they showed their confidence in
me.''
   ``Maybe there were small flaws,'' he said in response to
opposition charges of irregularities, ``but our intentions always
were the best and we wanted the general elections in Paraguay to be
free and clean.''
   Speaking to reporters at the national palace, he said the nine
Cabinet members he appointed immediately after the coup had offered
their resignations. He said no decision had been made on the
resignations.
   Fernando Vera, presidential candidate of the Revolutionary
Febrerista Party, said: ``In spite of the irregularities, I
recognize that he won and, I would say, it was a landslide
victory.''
   The Central Electoral Board said Tuesday that Rodriguez got
178,313 of the 240,379 votes counted for president, or 74.18
percent.
   Domingo Laino, a former national deputy who returned from exile
after the coup, was second with 43,148 votes, or 17.95 percent,
Vera was third and six other candidates divided the remainder, the
board announced.
   Rodriguez, 65, led by similar margins in unofficial tallies by
opposition parties and monitoring groups, also with Laino and Vera
running second and third respectively.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said the U.S. Embassy and international election observers saw
several instances of questionable, but not illegal procedures.
   She added, however, that U.S. diplomats saw no pattern of
``centrally directed fraud.''
   Rodriguez' coup ousted 76-year-old Stroessner a year after the
dictator won his eighth presidential term. Stroessner, also a
general, went into exile in Brazil.
   Voting Monday was for a successor to finish the five-year
presidential term and to fill the two houses of Congress, which
Rodriguez dissolved after the coup. The elections were the most
democratic this South American nation has held in decades.
   Partial official results gave the Colorado Party 156,247 votes,
or 66.43 percent, of the 235,203 counted for the 36-member Senate
and the Chamber of Deputies, which has 72 seats.
   Unofficial tallies gave a similar edge to the Colorados, who
have been in power since 1947 and were a bulwark of the Stroessner
regime.
   Under Paraguayan law, the party getting the most votes is
awarded two-thirds of the seats in Congress _ 24 in the Senate and
48 in the lower house.
   Rodriguez, the Colorado candidate, has pledged to reform the
constitution and electoral law and not to seek reelection.
   Laino and Vera were elected to the Senate. Both headed their
party slates for congressional seats in addition to running for
president.
   Flaws cited by international observers and party officials
included lack of privacy at some voting stations, ballots for all
parties not available everywhere, some registered voters not
permitted to cast ballots, indelible ink to prevent multiple voting
not always available or applied properly.
   No official figures on voter turnout were given. The election
board acknowledged before the election that the registration list
of 2.2 million voters in this nation of 4 million people might
contain up to 600,000 extra names.
   Paraguayans voted in large numbers, often standing patiently
outdoors on a drizzly day, chatting and drinking mate, a bitter
herbal tea.
   The president and new Congress are to be sworn in May 15.
</TEXT>
