<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-INS-SalvadoranDeportations     05-02 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS-Salvadoran Deportations,0521</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Immigrant Advocates Declare Small Victory With Order for Legal
Sessions for ^By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legal workers seeking refugee status for
Salvadorans declared a small victory Tuesday after a judge ruled
that Salvadorans may not be deported from South Texas before being
apprised of their rights.
   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon in Los Angeles issued the
preliminary injunction made public Monday after finding the
Immigration and Naturalization Service violated his previous order
to provide Salvadorans access to legal counsel.
   ``This is a small victory,'' Jonathan Moore, a paralegal with
the Harlingen-based Central American legal advocacy group Proyecto
Libertad, said Tuesday. ``It's a recognition that there is a
problem. I think it's significant.''
   Both sides in the case said they expect the number of
Salvadorans actively fighting deportation to increase as a result
of the judge's order.
   In the injunction, Kenyon noted that none of 67 Salvadorans
deported April 20 from the INS minimum-security Port Isabel Service
Processing Center at Bayview near the Mexican border had lawyers at
their deportation hearings.
   ``The court finds it difficult to believe that each of these
individuals learned of and knowingly and effectively waived his or
her right to counsel,'' the judge said.
   The order is part of a 1982 class-action suit accusing the INS
of failing to provide Salvadorans access to legal representation.
The plaintiffs in March had asked that the INS be held in contempt
and ordered to comply.
   Friday's injunction remains in effect until a May 30 hearing.
   The 1,471 aliens detained at Bayview as of Monday included 495
Nicaraguans, 334 Salvadorans, 194 Hondurans and 173 Guatemalans.
   ``Basically, it says we won't be able to deport any Salvadorans
until one of the immigrant rights groups, Proyecto Libertad, has a
chance to talk to them as a body,'' said Duke Austin, an INS
spokesman in Washington.
   Austin said the INS has encouraged groups such as the American
Bar Association to provide legal representation for Salvadorans and
other detainees.
   Proyecto Libertad eadvocates refugee status for Salvadorans on
grounds that they are fleeing war and political persecution. The
United States deports most Salvadorans, ruling that they are coming
to this country for economic reasons only.
   Proyecto Libertad was designated by the plaintiffs to conduct
the legal briefings. Proyecto held its first session Monday night
for men at the Port Isabel center. A second session was held
Tuesday for the women, he said.
   ``Even though the INS is slowly complying, the judge recognizes
that for several months they have been out of compliance,'' said
Mark Schneider, a Proyecto attorney.
   ``Our concern is that for over two months, over 1,500 people
have been deported, many of whom were never advised of their
rights, who may have had strong cases,'' he said.
   U.S. officials have granted refugee status to only six
Salvadorans and 78 Nicaraguans in the Harlingen District since Feb.
21.
   The INS last month installed cellular telephones for the Bayview
detainees and added pay phones in an effort to comply.
</TEXT>
