<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-PrisonRiot     05-02 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Prison Riot,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Rioters Smash Walls, Flood Cells</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prisoners awaiting trial smashed down
walls and flooded cell blocks Tuesday, the third day of a riot
against conditions at the Risley holding center in northern England.
   Chief Guard Graham Harrison said inmates used torn-off cell
doors to break down walls and threw bricks and rubble at guards who
tried to intervene.
   ``It was an orgy of destruction,'' he said.
   Guards and police with riot gear watched from below as prisoners
on the jail roof displayed banners protesting conditions in the
25-year-old center near Warrington, 10 miles east of the port city
of Liverpool.
   Guards said 55 rioters controlled the roof and two top floors of
D-wing and had ``absolutely obliterated'' the top floor of B-wing,
smashing all 48 cells. Water damaged an additional 60 cells on two
floors below, they said.
   The riot started Sunday. Paul Lynch, a recently released
prisoner, said the main complaints were overcrowding and
``atrocious food.''
   The complex, which also holds women prisoners, was opened in
1964 as a short-stay prison for inmates who could not get bail.
   Home Office Minister Douglas Hogg, who is in charge of prisons,
said in a radio interview that plans called for Risley to be
completely rebuilt and within eight years it would be an entirely
new prison.
   He called Risley a ``particularly difficult establishment.''
Hogg said the inmates could not be made to work because they were
awaiting trial. He said he was satisfied with staffing levels.
   But John Bartell, the guards' national association chairman,
said: ``There were 25 staff on duty for 550 prisoners ... We are
short of resources and staff and we are afraid that this incident
may presage a summer of discontent throughout the prison system.''
   After seven suicides in 18 months, Judge Stephen Tumim, the
government chief inspector of prisons, described Risley last summer
as ``barbarous and squalid ... a poorly designed institution where
many inmates are kept in appalling and unacceptable conditions.''
   Tumim said Risley and other prisons built in the 1960s were
constructed without cell toilets, just like the Victorian prisons
which still hold most of the country's 50,000 inmates.
   The government began rebuilding Risley after Tumim's report.
</TEXT>
