<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionPicketsTrial     05-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Pickets Trial,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Picketers Remain 400 Feet From Doctor's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine anti-abortion protesters have
been ordred to pay $810,000 in damages and stay away from the house
of a doctor who said demonstrators at his home made life miserable
for him and his family.
   State District Judge Jack Hunter on Tuesday issued a permanent
injunction barring pickets from coming within 400 feet of the home
of Dr. Eduardo Aquino.
   On Monday, a jury decided 10-2 that the picketers should pay
Aquino $810,000 in damages.
   ``I feel my family will be left alone now,'' Aquino said.
   Abortion opponent Cliff Zarsky, one of two attorneys who
represented the defendants without a fee, said he will ask for a
new trial.
   Jurors ruled Monday the protests caused mental anguish to
Aquino, his wife, Mercedes, and their four children. Protesters
carried placards that suggested Aquino was a murderer, but both
sides described the demonstrations as peaceful.
   Aquino testified his wife suffered from depression and ulcers,
that one son was institutionalized and that his three school-age
children suffered academically after the picketing began.
   Zarsky, who said the demonstrators' actions were protected by
the Constitution, argued that the pickets broke no laws and felt it
was their ``duty to protect unborn children.''
   The damages included $140,000 in past and future suffering of
the couple, $170,000 in past and future suffering of the children
and $500,000 in punitive damages.
   It was not clear if each defendant would be able to pay the
damages. Aquino's attorney, Tony Bonilla, said he would pursue the
award.
   Aquino said, however, that he was ``not really interested in the
money.''
   Aquino said he has been performing abortions since 1978 and
anti-abortionists had picketed his office since 1982. They began
picketing at his home in March 1988, the same month the suit was
filed.
   The phone at Zarsky's office went unanswered Tuesday.
   The defendants in the case were Eliseo Valenzuela Jr., Charles
W. Bolton, Carol Setliff, Sara Hood, Wade Pritchett, Lynn
Pritchett, T.C. Chedden, Dawn McGee, David Martinez and South
Texans for Life.
</TEXT>
