<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1908EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     05-02 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Premier Reports Split In Resistance Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian Premier Hun Sen reported
``quite big progress'' with resistance leaders on Tuesday in talks
to end a decade-long war, but he said the resistance appeared split
on key issues.
   In Thailand, shells crashed into the largest Cambodian refugee
camp in the latest in a recent surge in border assaults, Western
relief officials said.
   Three rounds flew over a border camp known as Site 2, and two
shells landed in the camp 30 minutes later, said Patrick Van de
Velde, deputy director of the U.N. Border Relief Operation. No
casualties were reported.
   It was not known who is responsible for the recent shellings.
Van de Velde said 15 shells have landed in the past 10 days near
the camp, home to 180,000 refugees.
   In Jakarta, resistance coalition leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk
and anti-communist faction chief Son Sann negotiated separately
with the premier, who said the two faction leaders differed on key
issues.
   The Khmer Rouge, the largest and best armed faction in the
three-party resistance, were not directly represented in Jakarta.
Sihanouk said their absence was a consensus decision.
   Sihanouk, Son Sann and their aides were not available for
comment Tuesday. Both canceled news conferences.
   Hun Sen did not indicate whether he considered the split a
barrier to further progress. He said the talks would resume
Wednesday, with further negotiations in Paris or Jakarta.
   Sihanouk expressed willingness on Sunday to drop his demand that
a U.N. force supervise the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from
Cambodia and keep the peace after Hun Sen's government was
dismantled. Hun Sen said Sihanouk ``agreed to maintain the present
constitution and make a few more amendments (to it).''
   But Son Sann still insists on the U.N. force, suspension of the
constitution and a four-sided coalition government until elections
are held, Hun Sen said.
   Hun Sen said the first day of talks achieved ``quite big
progress if we compare it with the recent and not so recent past.
... We recognize that both of us made concessions.''
   Sihanouk and Hun Sen agreed to stop receiving military aid from
abroad as soon as the Vietnamese troop withdrawal is completed. It
was not clear whether Son Sann also agreed to that.
   U.S. officials estimate that 60,000 to 70,000 Vietnamese troops
remain in Cambodia. Vietnam has promised to withdraw them by the
end of September.
   Hun Sen said the government would invite Sihanouk home to head
the government. The 67-year-old prince agreed to return to Cambodia
after Vietnamese forces departed, Hun Sen said.
   Speaking through an interpreter, Hun Sen said he favors the
creation of a supreme national council, headed by Sihanouk, with
leaders of the other three factions as deputies.
   The council would draft election rules and supervise the
election, Hun Sen said.
   ``Our government will remain only to maintain social order,'' he
said. After the votes are counted, his government would be
dissolved.
   The armed forces would remain at the same strength and in the
same places until after the elections.
   Millions have been killed in Cambodia since 1970, when a coup
ended Sihanouk's 30-year rule. Cambodia became engulfed in the
Vietnam War, and then the Khmer Rouge won a civil war in 1975.
   The current war erupted when Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late
1978 and pushed out the Khmer Rouge, which was blamed for killing
hundreds of thousands of people.
</TEXT>
