<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AerospacePlane     05-02 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aerospace Plane,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Urged to Seek Reversal of Pentagon Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers on Tuesday urged Vice President Dan
Quayle as chairman of the National Space Council to try to reverse
a Pentagon decision to scale back funding for a futuristic
high-speed plane.
   Nineteen members of the House said that Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney's plan to cut the project's fiscal 1990 budget from $300
million to $100 million and place it under exclusive NASA
jurisdiction will result in the plane's demise. The project has
been a joint effort of the Defense Department and NASA.
   ``NASA officials have made it clear that withdrawal of DoD
support for NASP (National Aerospace Plane) would ultimately kill
the program,'' the seven Democrats and 12 Republicans said in a
letter.
   They said the plane, a transport that could fly around the world
in just two hours, is ``a natural product of our intense need to
return to the forefront of space technology.''
   Cheney determined that the plane is a civilian aviation program.
But the lawmakers argued it represents technology that will provide
national security ``well into the 21st century.''
   ``As vice president, as chairman of the National Space Council
and as one who advocates U.S. competitiveness in the world, you
have a key role in U.S. technological development,'' the lawmakers
wrote Quayle. ``To cancel the National Aerospace Plane in 1990 is
to ensure our technological mediocrity beyond.''
   Signing the letter were Reps. Dave McCurdy, D-Okla.; Robert Roe,
D-N.J.; Beverly Byron, D-Md.; Ronnie Flippo, D-Ala.; Tim Valentine,
D-N.C.; Dan Glickman, D-Kan.; Bob Livingston, R-La.; Robert Walker,
R-Pa.; Bill Young, R-Fla.; Robert Davis, R-Mich.; Duncan Hunter,
R-Calif.; Denny Smith, R-Ore.; George Brown Jr., D-Calif.; Elton
Gallegly, R-Calif.; James Inhofe, R-Okla.; Christopher Shays,
R-Conn.; Jack Buechner, R-Mo.; Tom Lewis, R-Fla.; and Dana
Rohrabacher, R-Calif.
</TEXT>
