<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   05-02 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0650,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Moves, Unenthusiastically, to Consider 1990 Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new to show Senate debate begun, picks up 4th graf
pvs, `Both plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress on Tuesday began consideration of the
fiscal 1990 budget with the kind of enthusiasm usually reserved for
getting one's teeth drilled.
   Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, said he disagreed with those who characterize the
deficit reduction plan as ``smoke and mirrors, as deception, as
sleight of hand, or even worse.''
   ``But I sympathize completely with the frustration behind it,''
he said, as the Senate began debate on its version of the $1.17
trillion spending late Tuesday. ``This resolution simply doesn't go
far enough. We all know it.''
   ``There is something in it for everyone to hate, yet without it
we're in big trouble,'' said Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, senior
Republican on the House Budget Committee, testifying in favor of
the House plan.
   Both plans are based on the deficit-reduction agreement
announced last month at the White House. The pact claims about $28
billion in deficit reduction through limits on federal spending
growth combined with revenues from selling government assets,
raising fees, and about $5.3 billion in still-to-be-negotiated new
revenues.
   The budgets promise to bring the deficit down below the $100
billion goal of the Gramm-Rudman law, for the fiscal year beginning
Oct. 1. But critics contend that claim is based on overly
optimistic assumptions, and much of the ``savings'' is illusory.
   ``I believe we are doing a great disservice,'' said Rep. Anthony
Beilenson, D-Calif., a member of the House Rules Committee said
Tuesday as that panel prepared to prescribe a House debate to
assure passage of the plan.
   ``The votes are not there'' to do more, lamented Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget Committee. He and
others said perhaps more could be done next year.
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., said after a White
House meeting that the budget was ``close to what the
administration had asked for.'' He and the Democratic leaders were
working to make sure there would be no amendments allowed that
would ``upset the whole apple cart.''
   ``Obviously, this budget has been heavily criticized,'' said
Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M. ``I know of no one who has a better
plan.''
   Under the White House pact, both the House and Senate budgets
envision $299.2 billion in military spending next year, about the
same as the current year. The Pentagon would be given total
spending authority of $305.5 billion, a figure which includes some
outlays which stretch past the end of the fiscal year.
   Foreign aid spending would be set at $17 billion.
   Entitlement programs would be allowed to grow so that individual
benefits and their cost-of-living increases would escape cuts.
However, a variety of cost-cutting actions _ some of them just
bookkeeping changes _ would allow for $8.3 billion in total savings
from Medicare, agriculture, federal pensions, and other
entitlements.
   The White House agreement set an overall spending cap, but not
specifics, for non-entitlement domestic programs.
   The House and Senate budget committees took somewhat difference
approaches to dividing that pie, with the House favoring education,
health and veterans programs compared to more Senate emphasis on
agriculture, energy and law enforcement.
   In the House, the rules committee was limiting amendments and
debate so that the package could be completed on Thursday. In the
Senate, the rules allow individual senators the right to offer
amendments at any time, but budget supporters were confident the
plan would survive essentially intact.
   ``We'll have substantial help for the cause,'' Domenici said.
   Once the House and Senate complete their budgets, the two
chambers must agree on a single resolution. The document then
serves as the guide for the annual spending and tax legislation
produced by the Congress.
</TEXT>
