<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SovietMole     05-02 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Mole,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired British Spy's Memoirs to Name Soviet Mole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired British spy writes in his memoirs that
British intelligence has been irreparably damaged by Soviet agents,
and he names another mole among its ranks, The Independent reported
Tuesday.
   Desmond Bristow's book, ``A Game of Moles,'' may face the same
government ban attempted on former agent Peter Wright's book
``Spycatcher.''
   Bristow spoke of his memoirs in an interview at his home in
Malaga, Spain, the newspaper said.
   He was quoted as saying British intelligence officials already
have tried, over a bottle of claret wine, to have him scrap the
book or submit it to government censors.
   Bristow, 73, once was chief of counterintelligence for southwest
Europe for MI6, The Independent said. MI6 is Britain's foreign
intelligence agency. MI5 handles domestic affairs.
   ``The CIA and MI6 were equals before,'' the newspaper quoted
Bristow as saying. ``Now they're not. The CIA doesn't share its
supersecret stuff with us anymore. Personally I don't blame them.''
   Bristow said he left MI6 in 1954, after his cover was blown by
Kim Philby, the notorious British traitor-spy, but continued to do
occasional work for the agency, The Independent reported.
   Philby, Guy Burgess, Donald Maclean and Anthony Blunt were
upper-class Englishmen who were unmasked in the 1950s and 1960s as
Soviet agents.
   The Independent said that in ``A Game of Moles,'' Bristow claims
the late David Footman, a chief of MI6's political section for
central Europe, also worked for Moscow.
   Bristow, the paper said, claims Footman tore up a report written
for him in 1951 on Burgess' suspicious activities, fired a Spanish
agent of Bristow's who was uncovering KGB plots in Spain, and
buried top-secret files on links between the KGB and Communist
parties in southern Europe.
   The paper did not say whether Footman has any family to respond
to the allegation, and the Home Office said: ``We don't comment on
security matters.''
   The Independent did not say when the book was to be published,
but reporter Sarah Helm told The Associated Press the book is not
yet completed and Bristow is talking with publishers.
   The government fought a three-year court battle to suppress
Wright's book, saying it violated the lifelong oath of secrecy
taken by intelligence employees.
   The courts eventually lifted an injunction banning newspapers
from serializing ``Spycatcher,'' but its publication in book form
remains banned in Britain, although its publishers can distribute
the Australian edition here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
