<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-SpyTrial     05-02 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Spy Trial,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Convicted Of Selling Military Information To Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state court on Tuesday
convicted a West German engineer of selling sensitive information
on NATO military aircraft to the Soviet Union.
   Helmut Stefan Kolasch, a 45-year-old former employee of the
Siemens electronics firm, was sentenced to three years and nine
months in prison and fined $10,700.
   Kolasch sold technical information to the KGB Soviet
intelligence agency on NATO's Tornado warplane and on the Jaeger 90
fighter jet now under development, the Stuttgart court ruled.
   The court determined that Kolasch had worked for the KGB from
1973 to 1984, and was given $14,430 by his KGB contacts.
   Kolasch was involved in research work on electronics for
military aircraft at Siemens. He was arrested on March 23, 1988.
   The court, however, said prosecutors did not prove Kolasch
handed over results of all his research team's work on aircraft
electronics.
</TEXT>
