<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MiniumumWage     05-02 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miniumum Wage,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>House-Senate Negotiators Reach Quick Agreement; Veto Looms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate and House negotiators quickly agreed
Tuesday on legislation to raise the hourly minimum wage to $4.55 by
1991 and promised to move for swift congressional passage of the
bill which President Bush has vowed to veto.
   There were 18 areas in which the terms of House and Senate bills
differed but the conference committee took only about an an hour to
complete work, made easier by staff negotiations during last week's
congressional recess.
   Fourteen of the differences were worked out between
representatives of each chamber's labor committees. The Senate
conferees then met with representatives of the House Ways and Means
Committee and stripped off four tax-related Senate amendments
including a proposal to raise the amount of outside income a Social
Security recipient can earn before losing some enefits.
   Democrats from both the Senate and House conference teams
pledged swift final legislative action on the compromise, with a
consensus prediction that the bill would reach the White House in
about two weeks.
   Between Bush and Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, the
administration has vowed more than a dozen times to veto the
measure, which has a final minimum wage target 30 cents higher than
the president proposed and contains a so-called training wage far
more restrictive than the six-month provision demanded by Bush.
   Sponsors said they had scaled back their bill considerably to
meet administration concerns and would go no further without
concessions by Bush.
   ``We are hard-pressed to offer any further compromise,'' said
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, even tried to strip the
two-month training wage Democrats reluctantly added to their bill
in hopes Bush would then accept it.
   ``Unless we can work out a compromise with the White House we
ought to dump the training wage,'' Metzenbaum said. But he withdrew
the attempt after House Democrats told him the provision was
essential to maintain support among moderate Democrats and a small
number of Republicans who voted for the original House bill.
   Bush appears to have the votes to sustain a veto but Democrats
promised nonetheless to try to override. To assist that effort, the
AFL-CIO is contemplating an advertising campaign in hopes of
rallying the public behind the legislation. The federation's
governing body also issued a statement Tuesday supporting the
legislation.
   The sponsors on both the House and Senate side, however, concede
Bush likely will win the first confrontation between the Congress
and the White House over domestic policy but they have promised to
try to send Bush another minimum-wage bill this year if that
happens.
   The final product endorsed by the conferees would raise the
hourly minimum from $3.35, its level for more than eight years, to
$4.55 through three increases _ beginning Oct. 1 and ending on Oct.
1, 1991.
   Both the House and Senate bills contained those targets. The
major issue resolved in conference was the training-wage provision
allowing employers to pay some new workers a subminimum wage for 60
days.
   The House bill allowed a subminimum only for first-time entrants
in the job market while the Senate language, adopted by the
conference, requires once a person held a job at the submininum
wage for 60 days he would be no longer eligible for the subminimum
even if he changes jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
