<FIRST>r w AM-GlobalInflation     05-02 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Global Inflation,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Inflation Jumped to 58.3 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices paid by consumers in Third World
countries jumped an average 58.3 percent last year, up from 35.7
percent in 1957, the International Monetary Fund reported.
   The average rise in the United States and 20 other industrial
countries was only 3.3 percent, a rise from 2.9 percent.
   The figures come from a monthly report distributed Tuesday.
   Inflation figures for the Third World were heavily influenced by
Latin America _ Brazil's 682 percent, Argentina's 343 percent and
Mexico's 114 percent. These are the Third World's three biggest
debtors as well.
   Mexico reported a slowdown from last year's 132 percent but
Brazil and Argentina were moving up. Argentina's annual rate was
over 387 percent in December, and Brazil's 1,170 percent in January.
   Nicaragua surpassed them all with 10,205 percent for 1988 and an
annual rate of just under 24,000 percent in December but the
country is too small to count for much in the overall average.
   There was also a rise of inflation in Asia, to 11.6 percent from
7.3 percent. China's rate was up beyond 20 percent, compared less
than 9 percent in 1987.
   Returns from Africa and the Middle East were too fragmentary for
an overall figure.
</TEXT>
