<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Broadcasters-FCCChairman     05-02 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Broadcasters-FCC Chairman,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outgoing FCC Chairman Boasts of ``Seismic'' Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outgoing chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission pointed with pride Tuesday to an opening
up of competition in broadcasting during the ``seismic change'' of
his six years at the agency.
   In a swan song address to industry executives, Dennis Patrick
ticked off a list of benefits he said broadcasters had received
since he joined the FCC in 1983.
   He thanked his audience at the National Association of
Broadcasters convention ``for being courageous soldiers in this
battle for freedom'' and for ``unflagging support'' of his policies
against critics in Congress and non-broadcast media.
   ``Through this period of seismic change ... I have held firmly
to the notion of open entry to create a competitive marketplace for
the media,'' he said. ``This policy has led to a proliferation of
information outlets unimaginable even six years ago.''
   The average American home today has access to 25 video channels,
he said, and half of all Americans receive at least 28 radio
stations.
   ``We have tried to foster competition at the FCC by lowering
barriers to entry, and by permitting broadcasters to compete as
freely as those with whom they compete _ namely cable,'' Patrick
said.
   While saying that more competition can be a double-edged sword
for broadcasters, he said the ``competitive genie is out of the
bottle'' and ``neither Congress nor the commission will stuff her
back in.''
   Patrick anounced last month he had resigned from the agency
where he has been chairman for the past two years but would stay on
until his replacement is confirmed.
   During Patrick's tenure the FCC repealed the Fairness Doctrine
that required broadcasters to air opposing views in controversial
issues. Congress is expected to vote to reinstate the policy this
year, posing a possible veto fight with President Bush.
   The FCC also revised the means by which stations renew their
licenses to bar sham competitors who just want money to drop their
challenges to licensees.
   ``No longer will you be held hostage to petitions to deny filed
because you refuse to concede to extortion ... nor will we tolerate
those who seek to extort cash payments by masquerading as competing
applicants,'' Patrick said to a round of applause.
   He also noted the FCC's decision last year to make sure that a
U.S. standard for high-definition television will not make obsolete
the huge investment TV stations have in current equipment.
   American industry is racing to adopt standards with which to
build an HDTV system and stave off the expected appearance in the
next couple of years of foreign-made HDTV VCRs and movies.
   He urged the broadcasters not to delay reaching agreement on an
HDTV transmission standard so America can ``regain the lead in
broadcast technology.''
   He also said broadcasters need further protection from the cable
TV industry in the form of a requirement that cable systems pay for
the over-the-air programs they feed to their subscribers.
   ``They should no longer be permitted to take the product that
you have bought, you have promoted, you have earned and pass it
off, without asking, as theirs,'' Patrick said to more applause.
   He said the future holds new challenges for broadcasters:
fiber-optic cable and telephone entry into video programming,
competition from foreign media, further loss of audience and the
shifting of advertising from video to point of sales.
   He said network affiliates and networks may have to forge
stronger bonds, and broadcasters may have to work with cable to
survive against global competitors
   ``In this complex future,'' he said, ``may you have convictions,
may you have the courage of your convictions, may you succeed.''
   Patrick's address concluded the 67th annual NAB gathering, which
was attended by a record 50,136 broadcast executives and exhibitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
