<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Lid     05-02 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Lid,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Surprises Press, Calls It a Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A familiar-sounding voice boomed out over
White House loudspeakers Tuesday evening announcing the end of the
business day.
   It was President Bush, personally announcing he was going home.
   It was the first time in anyone's memory that the president,
himself, had performed the daily chore.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen of the press, the president having gone
home for the day, there is a lid on,'' Bush said. A ``lid'' is the
term used to tell reporters that no more paperwork or presidential
actions are expected.
   Bush made the announcement while walking from the Oval Office to
his residence in the White House. Noticing a gathering of reporters
hanging around the press office, Bush asked why they were still
there.
   They said they had to wait for him to leave and for the White
House to announce a lid. Bush asked what a lid was, and a reporter
explained the term.
   Usually a lid is announced by a press aide using a telephone
that is hooked up to a White House announcement system. Bush asked
for the telephone and made the announcement himself at 6:40 p.m.
EDT.
   He departed for his quarters as the press cheered his
announcement.
</TEXT>
