<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Shooting     05-02 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Shooting,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father's `Gentle, Quiet Son' Held in Random Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITLEY BAY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old civil servant
described by his father as a ``gentle, quiet son'' was ordered held
in custody on a murder charge Tuesday after a shooting spree that
killed one person and wounded 14.
   Robert James Sartin, a social security official who lives in
this seaside resort, was accused in North Shields Magistrates Court
of killing 41-year-old Kenneth Mackintosh. Sartin made no plea.
   Authorities say Mackintosh was killed during 15 minutes of
terror when Sartin fired a shotgun at people at random Sunday in
Monkseaton, a suburb of the Whitley Bay sea resort in northeast
England. The gunman was dressed all in black and wore sunglasses
and an ammunition belt.
   The defendant's father, Brian Sartin, a weapons coordinator for
a warship builder, hugged his wife, Jean, and they both wept
Tuesday while facing reporters outside their home.
   He said his family felt ``so terribly sorry'' for the people
shot on Sunday.
   He said he saw his son at a police station, and it was as if
``there are two people down there.''
   ``There is our gentle, quiet son, who loves kids, loves animals
and loves people. He is just so gentle. ... Then there is another
son sitting down there who doesn't know what it is all about,'' he
said.
   ``You just cannot explain it _ he is not aggressive. He has
never had a scrap in his life. He has never been aggressive to
anybody. It is completely alien,'' the father said.
   The couple has an older son, Andrew, who works as a weapons
engineer on the aircraft carrier HMS Ark Royal.
   Sartin said he had invited his younger son to his clay
pigeon-shooting club a few times and he was ``quite a good little
shot,'' but they never shot anything live.
   A friend described the accused man as shy and reluctant to leave
home for entertainment. His girlfriend is a police officer's
daughter.
   Authorities have said Sartin probably will be charged with other
offenses later.
</TEXT>
