<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Glance     05-02 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Glance,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Tuesday in the Alaskan oil
spill:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>COAST GUARD COMMANDANT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Coast Guard Commandant Paul A. Yost, in Alaska for a
weeklong progress survey, said Exxon's revised plan to clean up the
oil spill was ``thin'' and lacked ``backup or substantiation,'' but
promised the cleanup will be completed this summer.
   Yost must approve Exxon's cleanup strategy and said he will pass
on the proposal within a week.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EXXON BOYCOTTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers joined a coalition of environmentalists and
politicians endorsing a one-day national boycott of Exxon products.
   ``We want to show Exxon that corporations who harm the
environment will pay a price in the marketplace,'' said California
Assemblyman Tom Bates.
   Rallies and news conferences were scheduled in at least nine
states, and consumer advocate Ralph Nader led the boycott call from
Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BOYCOTT REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon said 10,000 credit cards out of 7 million have been cut up
and returned since the spill. The company called the boycott unjust
but said it has no reports lower gasoline sales.
   J. Edward Surette Jr. of Massachusetts dealers' association,
said it was too early to assess the impact of the boycott. While
criticizing Exxon's ``obvious negligence,'' Surette said it was
unfair for consumers to vent their anger at dealers, most of whom
are small, independent businessmen.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GASOLINE PRICES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sens. Jim Exon and Bob Kerrey, both Nebraska Democrats, asked
U.S. Attorney General Richard Thornburgh to investigate potential
price gouging by the oil industry. The senators noted gasoline
prices in Nebraska rose 20 percent from the first of March until
the middle of April.
   The attorneys general of Oregon, Washington and Idaho said
Monday they would ask the federal government to investigate the
price increases.
   Since the accident, gas prices have increased an average 10
percent nationally, while the Pacific Northwest saw surges as high
as 25 percent in less than a month.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TANKER REPAIRS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon has decided not to seal the large holes ripped in the hull
of the Exxon Valdez and intends to bring it to Portland, Ore., in
mid-June. The Port of Portland drydock is the only one on the West
Coast large enough to handle the 987-foot vessel.
   The tanker is undergoing preliminary repairs off the Alaskan
coast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EXXON EXECUTIVE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon President William D. Stevens defended his company's
actions, saying Exxon responded quickly and is committed to
cleaning up the spill.
   In an address to the Offshore Technology Conference in Houston,
Stevens said there was little he would do differently if faced with
the situation again. He said Exxon, the Alaska Department of
Environmental Conservation and the Coast Guard should share the
blame for not immediately authorizing the use of chemical
dispersants and the open burning of oil in hopes of containing the
spill more quickly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
