<HEAD>Head of Communist Government's Church Agency Retires</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0640 to restore writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to DELETE reference to newsletter, adds details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the communist government's
agency to regulate church matters has been replaced as part of a
program to relax control of religion, the official news agency MTI
reported Tuesday.
   It said Imre Miklos, long associated with strong government
control, retired May 1 as president of the State Office for Church
Affairs and the duties were assumed by his deputy, Barna Sarkadi
Nagy. MTI said the agency would be remodeled and given a new name
to conform with the new approach.
   Miklos retired after ``crucial changes'' in policy toward
religion, the agency said, and state control will be withdrawn from
all aspects of church life in order to ``finalize the separation of
the state and churches.''
   A law on the freedom of religion and conscience has been
prepared, according to MTI. About half the nation's 10.5 million
people are Roman Catholic.
   The agency said the new policy would provide an opportunity to
expand cooperation between the government and churches in the
social, political, cultural and educational field.
   ``There is a need for open political activity in order to create
a forum for coordination of interests that would attract ...
church, state and party officials, as well as independent and
prestigious politicians,'' MTI reported.
   Sarkadi Nagy was quoted as saying: ``This policy of genuine
cooperation between equal partners deserves better than the usual
official style.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
