<FIRST>r w AM-Holocaust-Capitol     05-02 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holocaust-Capitol,1st-Ld Writethru,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candles Lit in Rotunda in Memory of Holocaust Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to change ``people'' to ``Jews''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six white candles, each symbolizing a million
lost lives, were lit in the rotunda of the U.S. Capitol on Tuesday
in a memorial to the six million Jews killed in the Holocaust of
World War II.
   ``Our memories are of the millions who died, and the many, many
others who _ though they survived _ carried with them throughout
their remaining lives the permanent scars of the horrors they
suffered,'' said Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, R-Kans.,
himself a wounded veteran of the war.
   With the division flags of the U.S. military units that
liberated the Nazi concentration camps posted as sentinels in the
background, the Eisenhower Liberation Medal was presented
posthumously to General of the Army Omar N. Bradley, who was
present at the liberation of the Ohrdruf concentration camp in 1945.
   The medal was accepted by Bradley's daughter, Mrs. Benjamin
Henry Dorsey, who said that when he returned from the war the first
thing the general told his wife was about his visit to the camp,
saying he had been ``almost overcome by the stench of death.''
   ``Nothing he had seen during the war had prepared him for this
horror,'' Mrs. Dorsey said. ``The memory of what he saw stayed with
my father all his life.''
   The general died in 1981.
   Speakers at the ceremony noted that construction will begin next
month of the United States Holocaust Museum near the mall leading
from the Capitol to the Washington Monument.
   Harvey M. Myerhoff, chairman of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial
Council, said its purpose will be ``to tell the story of the
victims in their own words with a few material remnants of their
destroyed culture.''
   He issued an appeal for the donation by governments and
individuals of artifacts of the Holocaust period ``so that we can
tell the story accurately and powerfully.''
   ``This museum will rise like a phoenix from the ashes to be a
symbol of remembrance for all Americans,'' Myerhoff said.
   Each of the six candles were lit by two people, one a member of
Congress, the other a survivor of the death camps.
   Later, at a meeting called to present a progress report on fund
raising for the museum, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of
Maine said the new institution will be a symbol of a certain kind
of hope: ``Hope that no other such memorial need ever be built
anywhere on the earth.''
</TEXT>
