<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     05-02 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Agrees To Move Military Bases From Seoul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has agreed to move
its military headquarters in South Korea from central Seoul to
rural areas, the Defense Ministry announced Tuesday.
   Under an agreement with South Korea, the headquarters and other
U.S. bases in central Seoul will be moved by the mid-1990s, the
ministry said.
   South Korea wants to relocate the bases to help meet growing
demands for new offices and homes in the crowded capital. The
Americans promised to move the bases if South Korea provides
comparable facilities elsewhere.
   ``The first element of this plan calls for the early return of
the 8th U.S. Army golf course during 1990, with the full relocation
of the affected forces in (the) mid-1990s,'' the announcement said.
   South Korean officials said they probably will convert the
course into a public park.
   The Seoul barracks have been headquarters of the 8th U.S. Army
and other American forces since the United States backed South
Korea in the 1950-53 Korean War.
   U.S. and South Korean officials agree political and economic
changes have caused South Korea to reassess its relationship with
the United States.
   The two sides are negotiating the future of U.S. bases in South
Korea, and South Korea wants to revise agreements to secure greater
jurisdiction over the 43,000 U.S. soldiers stationed under a mutual
defense pact.
   A majority of South Koreans support the presence of U.S.
soldiers in their country. U.S. officials say the forces will
remain as long as their presence is desired by a majority of South
Koreans.
   Dissidents and radical students demand the immediate withdrawal
of the U.S. troops, contending they hamper unification with
communist North Korea.
   Korea was divided in 1945, when U.S. and Soviet soldiers
terminated Japan's colonial rule at the end of World War II.
</TEXT>
