<FIRST>u w AM-ABA-Judges 1stLd-Writethru a0719 05-02 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA-Judges, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0719,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA, Thornburgh At Odds Over Judicial Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs two and four to clarify nature of proposed change,
INSERTS one graf after 13th graf pvs bgng: ``The attorney'' with additional
Justice Department statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Bar Association officials took
exception Tuesday to a statement by Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh that the ABA had agreed to stop assessing the political
and ideological views of judicial nominees.
   Harold R. Tyler Jr., chairman of the ABA's Standing Committee on
Federal Judiciary, said no formal agreement with the Bush
administration has been reached on changing the wording of the
screening panel's guidelines.
   Tyler said the ABA has ``expressed a willingness'' in informal
discussions with Thornburgh to change or delete a sentence from its
guidelines which says: ``Political or ideological philosophy are
not considered, except to the extent they may bear upon the other
factors.''
   ``I don't think we have reached any agreement on the exact
language'' of the changes to be made, Tyler said.
   Even if the sentence is changed or deleted, Tyler said, ``we
don't think there has been any change at all'' in the way the
committee will screen candidates for the federal bench.
   Earlier in the day, Thornburgh told a House committee that ``we
are pleased that the American Bar Association's Standing Committee
on the Judiciary has seen fit to withdraw from an area not only
contentious but in my view improper for their consideration _ that
is to say the political and ideological views of the prospective
nominees.''
   Tyler also expressed puzzlement at Thornburgh's characterization
of the role of Robert B. Fiske Jr. in forging the ``agreement.''
   ``I don't know what to say about Fiske. I am in the peculiar
position of being a friend of Fiske.''
   Tyler acknowledged he had discussed the issue and others with
Fiske. ``The problem is I didn't realize I was in any
negotiation,'' Tyler said.
   The attorney general's statements crediting Fiske's role in the
discussions appeared to be an attempt to mollify conservative
opposition to the New York lawyer's anticipated nomination as
deputy attorney general.
   Fiske, whom Thornburgh told the committee is his choice for the
job, has been criticized by conservatives for subverting Reagan
administration judicial nominees when he chaired the ABA panel.
   The attorney general told the House Judiciary Committee that
``largely through the efforts of Robert Fiske... we have reached
agreement with the ABA (that) they will revert to their prior role
in handling judicial assessments and will henceforth ... restrict
their examination and assessment only to those areas where they
have special expertise.''
   The attorney general's aide, David Runkel, said Fiske ``played a
central role'' in mediating the issue and ``in getting the
committee to agree to the points raised by the attorney general.''
   Told of Tyler's statements, Runkel said ``it is our
understanding based on personal discussions between ABA leaders and
top aides to the attorney general'' that the group had agreed to
delete the phrase ``except to the extent they may bear upon other
factors.''
   Runkel said this understanding was ``based on an exchange of
letters.... between the attorney general and the ABA last week.''
   Thornburgh said the ABA's judicial screening unit had agreed to
restrict its review to judicial competence, temper and integrity.
   Following the Senate defeat of Robert Bork's nomination to the
Supreme Court, the ABA's committee has been the object of
criticism, particularly, but not exclusively, from Republicans,
that it improperly considers a nominee's political views.
   Tyler told the Senate Judiciary Committee in 1987 that four of
the panel's members voted against recommending Bork because of his
``comparatively extreme views respecting constitutional
principles.''
   But ABA officials deny that ideology or politics are sole
factors, except insofar as they might influence judicial
candidate's temperament.
   ``We have never gotten into political ideology, so there is no
change,'' ABA President Robert Raven said, when told of
Thornburgh's remarks.
   Thornburgh's comments about Fiske appeared to be aimed at
mollifying Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., and other conservatives
who could make trouble for Fiske if he is nominated for deputy
attorney general.
   In an April 17 letter to President Bush, Humphrey charged when
Fiske chaired the ABA standing committee ``there is evidence that
that committee's evaluations were tainted with ideological bias
against conservative nominees selected by President Reagan.''
   Humphrey said that ``careful consideration be given the
complaints raised against him.''
</TEXT>
