<FIRST>r i AM-AfghanKing     05-02 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan King,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Foiled Scheme To Return Afghan King To Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain, the Soviet Union and India were involved
in a foiled plot to return exiled King Zahir Shah of Afghanistan to
power, a broadcast report said Tuesday.
   Independent Television News said Afghan rebels prevented the
king's return by cutting off Kandahar airport in southern
Afghanistan in a fierce battle. The independent commercial network
did not say when the battle took place.
   In Rome, where the 74-year-old king now lives, his spokesman,
Gen. Abdul Wali, said of the report: ``It's absolutely new to me. I
know nothing about it.''
   ITV quoted the Moslem rebels fighting Afghanistan's Marxist
government as saying the plan was discussed when British Foreign
Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe met with them during his March visit to
Pakistan, where major guerrilla groups are based.
   It said the rebels also believe it was discussed during Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's trip to London last month, and
between Howe and Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
   A spokesman for the Foreign Office said: ``We haven't seen it
(the report) ourselves, so we're not in a position to comment.'' He
spoke anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   The Kabul government and some of the moderate, traditionalist
rebel groups have tried to work out a role for the former monarch,
who has lived in Rome since he was ousted in a 1973 coup.
   But hard-line rebel leaders reject any role for the king in
future Afghan governments. The king has said he is willing to help
end the fighting but has refused to serve in any Marxist-dominated
government.
</TEXT>
