<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Quake     05-02 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Quake,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Tremor Shakes Two Mexican States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook the states of
Mexico and Guerrero in the pre-dawn hours Tuesday, frightening
people but causing no casualties or damage, officials said.
   The quake measured 5 on the Richter scale and was centered about
60 miles northeast of the Pacific Coast resort of Acapulco in
Guerrero state, the National University's Geophysical Institute
said.
   It said the temblor could be felt in Mexico City, where a large
quake measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale caused panic a week ago.
The April 25 quake killed one person and injured four people.
   In 1985, a quake in Mexico City crumbled many buildings in the
capital and killed at least 9,500 people.
   Seismologists in Acapulco said the temblor on Tuesday lasted
seven seconds. The Central Fire Station in Mexico City said the
ground in the capital shook for 20 seconds.
   An earthquake measuring 5 on the scale can cause considerable
damage in populated areas and one measuring 6 can cause severe
damage.
   The Richter scale gauges the energy released by an earthquake as
measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every
increase of one number of the scale indicates a tenfold increase in
the magnitude.
</TEXT>
