<FIRST>u a AM-LucyCard     05-02 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucy Card,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>`We Love Lucy,' Says Block-Long Sympathy Card</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA5 of May 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucille Ball's fans gave her
widower a block-long sympathy card Tuesday amid a worldwide
outpouring of affection for the comedian who died last week.
   Gary Morton, widower of the redheaded clown from TV's ``I Love
Lucy,'' accepted the missive contained on 127 poster-sized cards
stretched along the Walk of Fame on Hollywood Boulevard. Miss Ball
had two stars embedded in the walk, honoring her film and
television careers.
   ``When you're married to someone for 29 years, you just don't
know _ you don't take it for granted _ but you just don't know the
love that's out there,'' Morton said.
   ``This is beyond all expectations. I can't believe how beautiful
the world has been to her.''
   Miss Ball died at age 77 Wednesday of a ruptured aorta while
recovering from heart surgery. She was buried over the weekend
after a private service at Forest Lawn Memorial Park in the
Hollywood Hills.
   The cards were presented by Peggy Robinson, a shoe store manager
who put out blank cards over a five-day period.
   Ms. Robinson, 35, said she found the first card at one of Miss
Ball's starts Thursday morning. Fans were so eager to sign it that
they were writing over each other's words, so she bought six cards
which were completely filled in 15 minutes.
   She bought another six, and the same thing happened.
   ``I just kept going until I finished the sidewalk,'' Ms.
Robinson said.
   The cards lay undisturbed until she picked them up Monday.
   ``People were still signing as I was taking it up. People were
saying, `Oh, I didn't get a chance to sign yet,''' Ms. Robinson
said.
   Her favorite expression was written by street gang members:
``The homeboys of East L.A. love and miss Lucy.''
   One woman left a lock of her red hair and signed, ``From a
fellow redhead.''
   The cards, folded into a manageable stack, were presented by Ms.
Robinson and Hollywood Chamber of Commerce officials Bill Welsh and
Johnny Grant on a sidewalk outside a Sunset Boulevard office
building.
   They said the crowds that gathered by the sidewalk star all
weekend were unusually large, even in this celebrity-worshipping
city.
   ``We have never seen a demonstration of affection such as we
have seen on this particular occasion,'' Welsh said. ``She was a
part of people's lives so many years.''
</TEXT>
