<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0662 05-02 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Not A Candidate, But He Campaigns Hard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 4th graf, `But Noriega ...' to UPDATE with
general's appearance Tuesday. Pickup 5th graf, `Noriega has ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Latin America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has been
burning up the campaign trail even though he remains an issue, not
a candidate, in Sunday's presidential elections.
   Noriega, whose command of the Panamanian Defense Forces gives
him de facto control of Panama, is supporting a business associate,
Carlos Duque, against an opposition coalition headed by Guillermo
Endara.
   ``He cannot stay impartial in this campaign,'' said Maj. Edgardo
Lopez, a Defense Forces spokesman. ``Impartiality at this time
would be irresponsibility on his part.''
   But Noriega has made few joint appearances with his candidate.
Instead, he has been working on his own image with regular visits
to hamlets, labor unions and civic groups.
   On Tuesday, Noriega laid the cornerstone of a housing project
for the poor in Panama City. A truck stopped by and served free
beer to the estimated 200 people who showed up for the general's
appearance.
   Noriega has survived all attempts to oust him, from U.S.
economic sanctions to a failed coup last year. He has retained his
grip through government political parties and the Defense Forces,
whose members are the only visible authority in most rural towns.
   He has also tried to build an image as a Panamanian nationalist
persecuted by the U.S. government, and as a champion of the poor.
   In his visits to small towns, Noriega mingles with residents and
listens to their complaints and requests for help with community
projects. Many of those projects are then carried out by the local
Defense Forces unit.
   In his speeches, Noriega has said the 500 municipal councilmen
to be elected Sunday must be turned into a ``people's power''
assembly.
   Noriega went from a close friend and associate of intelligence
agencies in the United States to a wanted man last year after he
was indicted in Florida on drug-trafficking charges.
   He denies the charges, saying they stem from his refusal to
cooperate with U.S. government plans to train Nicaraguan rebels
here for an invasion of Nicaragua.
   Former White House adviser Adm. John Poindexter ``came to try to
convince the general in 1985,'' said Maj. Lopez, a close associate
of the general. ``When he left, he refused to shake Noriega's hand
and told him `be prepared to face the consequences.'''
   Shortly thereafter, Lopez claimed, the campaign against Noriega
began in the United States.
   Washington demanded Noriega's ouster last year after he was
indicted. But President Eric Delvalle, who had been handpicked by
Noriega, was deposed when he tried to fire the general.
   The U.S. government imposed economic sanctions and the
opposition has echoed demands that the general must leave.
   Noriega personally answered charges by opposition vice
presidential candidate Ricardo Arias Calderon, the only time he got
directly involved in the campaign.
   Arias had called Noriega a ``nail in the side'' that had to be
removed. Noriega said he would drive the nail deeper. It became a
government slogan.
   Arias also angered Noriega and the military recently when he
said publicly that a opposition government could live with any
military leader except Noriega. It was seen as an invitation to a
coup.
   On April 21, Noriega joined Duque on a four-hour march at the
head of the largest demonstration held by pro-government groups.
But the rally was not overtly political _ it was organized by the
Defense Forces under the banner ``March of Friends of the Defense
Forces.''
</TEXT>
