<FIRST>u a AM-MidwifeManslaughter     05-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Midwife Manslaughter,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midwife Enters Surprise Guilty Pleas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unlicensed midwife on trial for murder in
the deaths of three babies unexpectedly pleaded guilty Tuesday to
involuntary manslaughter and insurance fraud in a plea bargain with
the prosecution.
   Dolores Doyle, 36, had been accused along with Dr. Milos Klvana
of bungling high-risk out-of-hospital baby deliveries in which
mothers should have been hospitalized.
   Mrs. Doyle, who has been in jail for more than two years while
awaiting trial, was immediately sentenced to eight years in prison.
The sentence was stayed, and she was to be released within 24 hours
on five years probation, according to Deputy District Attorney
Brian Kelberg.
   Klvana's trial in the deaths of eight infants and a fetus
between 1982 and 1986, will continue, Kelberg said. It is in recess
because Klvana, 47, is ill and undergoing medical tests in jail.
   Mrs. Doyle pleaded guilty to three counts of involuntary
manslaughter, seven counts of insurance fraud, five counts of
unlawfully practicing medicine without a license and one count of
conspiracy to practice medicine without a license.
   Mrs. Doyle had been charged in three of the eight baby deaths
involving Klvana, who is charged with second-degree murder,
insurance fraud and grand theft.
   In return for her guilty plea, prosecutors dropped three
second-degree murder charges.
   Kelberg said Mrs. Doyle had been offered the same deal earlier,
but decided to accept it after becoming so emotionally distraught
in court last week that she had to be taken to see a psychiatrist.
   The agreement was approved by Superior Court Judge Judith
Chirlin.
   As a condition of her probation, Mrs. Doyle was ordered not to
engage in the practice of medicine or associate with anyone
practicing medicine.
   Mrs. Doyle's attorney, Maxwell Keith, told jurors in his opening
statement last month that the midwife believed in childbirth as ``a
spiritual experience'' and was dedicated to tending women who
shunned hospital births for religious or economic reasons.
   He said she insisted on strict prenatal care and protected the
health of mothers and babies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
