<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Kasuga     05-02 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Kasuga,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Founder Of Democratic Socialist Party Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder and former chairman of Japan's
opposition Democratic Socialist Party, Ikko Kasuga, died Tuesday of
pneumonia, hospital officials said. He was 79.
   Kasuga, a member of Parliament, died Tuesday at Nagoya City
University Hospital, said a spokesman for the hospital in Nagoya,
central Japan.
   In 1960, Kasuga left the Japan Socialist Party over an
ideological difference and formed the Democratic Socialist Party _
now Japan's third largest opposition party _ along with the late
Suehiro Nishio. Kasuga became the party's secretary-general in 1967
and was elected chairman in 1971.
   During his tenure as chairman, Kasuga proposed forming a
coalition government along with other opposition party members or
some members of the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
   He was not successful, and he resigned in 1977. He had been an
adviser to the party since his resignation.
   Kasuga was born into a farm family in central Gifu Prefecture
(state) in 1910 and was first elected to Japan's lower house of
Parliament on the Japan Socialist Party ticket in 1952.
   With the death of Kasuga, the number of seats held by the
Democratic Socialist Party in the powerful 512-member House of
Representatives fell to 28. The largest opposition party is the
Japan Socialist Party with 85 seats, followed by the Komeito, or
Clean Government Party, with 56.
   The Liberal Democrats have a commanding 296 seats in the House,
and the Japan Communist Party has 27.
</TEXT>
