<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-FarmerProtest     05-02 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farmer Protest,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Injured in Violent Farmers' Protest in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POTENZA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas Tuesday at
bottle-throwing farmers who were demonstrating for drought aid in
this southern region, police said. At least five people were
wounded.
   Italian news media gave this account:
   About 1,000 farmers came to Potenza Tuesday demanding to see the
president and agriculture adviser of the regional government based
in the city. After a long wait, the demonstrators got word they
would be received. .
   However, a scuffle broke out. A police spokesman said it began
when demonstrators blocked the doors of the regional government
building, preventing employees from leaving.
   Demonstrators said police charged them without reason.
Government employees said the demonstrators started violently
shoving the police.
   Police, firing tear gas and waving truncheons, waded into the
demonstrators and were met by a barrage of rocks and bottles,
authorities reported.
   The Italian news agency ANSA reported that five police officers
were treated at San Carlo Hospital for injuries. The Italian news
agency AGI said one demonstrator also suffered a head wound.
   No one answered the telephone at regional government offices
later Tuesday.
   The extended drought in the region, 200 miles southeast of Rome,
has hurt the farmers.
</TEXT>
