<SECOND>AM-Four Slain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son of Slain Minister Questioned By Police; Divers Search Pond</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with funeral plans.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKEVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities questioned the son of a
minister found shot to death with his wife and two daughters in
their rural parsonage, but declined to say Tuesday whether the
teen-ager was a suspect.
   Robert J. ``Jeff'' Pelley, 17, was questioned Monday night, said
St. Joseph County sheriff's Sgt. Charles Feirrell. He declined to
say whether Pelley had requested legal counsel.
   No arrests have been made in the shooting deaths of the youth's
father, the Rev. Robert L. Pelley, 38; his wife, Dawn, 32; and
daughters Janel, 8, and Jolene, 6.
   The victims' bodies were found Sunday morning in the parsonage
of the Olive Branch Church of the United Brethren in Christ, about
two miles northwest of Lakeville, after the minister failed to show
up for the service.
   Autopsy results indicated the minister and his wife died
Saturday of close-range shotgun wounds to the head, said Feirrell.
Autopsies on the children were incomplete.
   No further information on the autopsies was provided.
   ``This is information known to the suspect and the police, and
at this point we'd like to keep it that way,'' said Feirrell.
   Jeff Pelley returned to his home Tuesday and left with some
personal belongings, police said. He was accompanied by his
grandfather, who police identified as Jack Armstrong of Burlington,
Ky.
   The younger Pelley told authorities he had spent Saturday at
high school prom activities, police said. Police found him Sunday
at an amusement park north of Chicago, where he had driven with
friends.
   Police divers searched a pond across the road from the parsonage
Tuesday, looking for the weapon and other evidence, said Feirrell.
No weapon was found.
   Investigators ruled out burglary and robbery as motives because
the home showed no sign of forced entry. The absence of a weapon
ruled out murder-suicide.
   The parents had been married almost four years; their first
spouses both died, congregation members said. Jeff and Jackie, 14,
were Pelley's children from his first marriage, and Jessica, 10,
Janel and Jolene were Ms. Pelley's daughters.
   Jackie was attending a church camp when the killings occurred,
and Jessica was spending the night with friends, police said.
   A pastor colleague said the Pelleys had experienced some turmoil
in merging the two families, but declined to explain.
   A memorial service for the Pelleys was scheduled for Wednesday
afternoon at their church, with burial in South Bend, which is
about 10 miles north of Lakeville.
</TEXT>
