<FIRST>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0767 05-02 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>6 Riot Troopers Killed In University Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with hostages freed, more police comment. ADDS
byline. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six riot troopers were killed in
fighting with radical students on Wednesday when police raided a
university in the southern port of Pusan to rescue five officers
being held hostage, officials said.
   The officials said students set fire to a barricade doused with
paint thinner when the raiding force burst in, setting several
police ablaze.
   Police, who refused to give their names, said about 700 troopers
launched a dawn raid on Dongui University to rescue five officers
taken hostage Tuesday after a demonstration by students.
   About 20 other troopers and radical students were injured in the
fighting, 10 of them seriously.
   Students holding the hostages on the seventh floor of the school
library set the thinner-drenched barricade aflame when troopers
burst in and several attacking officers were set on fire, the
officials said on condition of anonymity.
   Some troopers, wrapped in flames, leapt out of windows. Others
choked to death on the smoke or were badly burned, they reported.
Three troopers were dead on arrival at a hospital and three died
while undergoing emergency treatment, they said.
   All of the hostages were later freed when professors intervened
and persuaded the students to let them go, officials said.
   Korean Broadcasting System, the state television network, said
88 students were arrested in the fighting in South Korea's second
largest city.
   National Police Headquarters in Seoul said it was the worst loss
of police life in recent years. Officers could not recall any
comparable incident.
   The students had seized five officers as hostages to protest an
incident Monday when a police officer fired warning shots as
protesters attacked a police station. Radical students claimed
police overreacted by firing. They also demanded release of a
fellow student being held by police, officials said.
   Police officials negotiated unsuccessfully through the night for
the hostages' release and authorities then ordered a raid to free
them.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent protests in recent
weeks by radical students and dissidents demanding the overthrow of
President Roh Tae-woo's government.
   Pusan and other South Korean cities experienced violence Monday
in protests marking the international May Day labor holiday. The
protests came the day after riot police blocked a major labor rally
in Seoul.
   Protests rarely result in deaths in South Korea, however, in
spite of the fury of street clashes in which protesters battle riot
police with firebombs and rocks. Riot police are normally only
armed with tear gas and batons.
</TEXT>
