<FIRST>r a AM-TruckOverturns     05-02 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Truck Overturns,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Officials Clear Rocket Explosives From Interstate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SWEETWATER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army experts cleared military rockets
off an interstate highway Tuesday after the truck carrying them
overturned when its driver swerved to avoid hitting a deer.
   A seven-mile section of Interstate 20 running through this
central Texas town was closed for more than 14 hours after the
truck, carrying eight rocket pods loaded with six rockets each, ran
off the road, authorities said.
   Explosives experts from Fort Hood and Fort Sill, Okla., worked
for more than three hours to remove the rockets, each of which
carried 644 M-77 grenades, said officials with the Texas Department
of Public Safety.
   The rockets were not armed and posed no danger, said David
Harris, spokesman for the U.S. Army Missile Command near
Huntsville, Ala.
   ``Part of the development program involved taking fully loaded
rockets and dropping them 20 to 30 feet onto concrete to see if
they could withstand that kind of impact,'' Harris said.
   Officials evacuated one resident of a mobile home located about
200 yards from the accident site, but allowed her to return seven
hours later, police Sgt. Don Willingham said.
   The driver and a passenger suffered minor injuries, police said.
   ``All I know is I saw a deer and I swerved to miss it,'' said
the driver, Byron Robertson, 27, of Fouke, Ark.
   ``There was no indication of any problem physically with either
the driver or the truck,'' said state Trooper Don Rannefeld.
   The rockets were being transported from the LTV Corp. factory in
Camden, Ark., where they were produced to Concord, Calif., and
ultimately were bound for South Korea, said Col. Bob Richards, a
combat support group commander from Dyess Air Force Base.
   The cargo was taken to the base in Abilene, about 40 miles east
of the accident site, for inspection, said Master Sgt. Al Dostal, a
Dyess spokesman.
</TEXT>
