<FIRST>r i AM-School-Murderer     05-02 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School-Murderer,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Keep Convicted Murderer as Honorary President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the London School of Economics failed
to muster the two-thirds majority they needed Tuesday to oust the
convicted murderer of a policeman as honorary president of their
union.
   School and government officials responded with anger to the
vote, which allows Winston Silcott to keep the honor given to him
by the students on Thursday. The college's governors said they were
reviewing the school's annual $439,000 grant to the union.
   Education Secretary Kenneth Baker, speaking to the House of
Commons, called the vote ``shameful and despicable.''
   ``This is the loony left hijacking a great institution,'' he
added.
   The students voted 530-305 in favor of removing the jailed man
from the post. However, that tally narrowly failed to meet the
two-thirds majority that would have overturned his election.
   In a separate vote, the students agreed to raise money to buy
flowers for the family of the murder victim.
   Silcott, 29, is one of three men jailed for life for hacking a
policeman to death during a riot in a north London housing project
in 1985.
   Amnesty International, the human rights organization, and Lord
Gifford, a leading jurist, have investigated the case and cast
doubt on the convictions.
   Silcott was nominated for the one-year post by a member of the
school's socialist Labor Club. Just 150 of the school's 4,000
students voted him in to show their belief he may have been wrongly
convicted.
   After the initial vote, the college's Afro-Caribbean Society
said the election of Silcott, who is black, was ``deplorable,
insensitive and patronizing to the black race.''
   On Tuesday, heated exchanges broke out among students after
their new vote. Amanda Hart, the general secretary of the student
union, said she had received several death threats after last
week's vote.
   ``Obviously I am scared, but I will stand by the union's
decision,'' she said.
   Sir Peter Parker, chairman of the school's governors, termed the
students' decision to keep Silcott as their honorary president
``appalling.''
   He said the school could not overturn the decision under the
union's constitution.
   But he added, ``It is very embarrassing and damaging to the
school.
   ``Whatever happens in the union, nothing must happen there that
will damage the worldwide reputation of this school,'' he said.
   The school's director, Indraprasad Patel, said he was seeking
ways for the college to reverse the decision.
   ``They have got to use every device in the rule book to overturn
this disgraceful decision,'' said Sir Marcus Fox, a lawmaker from
the governing Conservative Party.
</TEXT>
