<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms Whip Through Much of the Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Cool weather ...,' to CORRECT low-temperature
record in Ozark to 38 degrees, sted 35.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms swirled across much of New England,
parts of the South and the Midwest on Tuesday, and a blast of cold
air swept through Arkansas, setting two low-temperature records.
   Much of New England and northern New York were drenched Tuesday
afternoon by continuing showers and thunderstorms.
   Showers and thunderstorms whipped through north central Texas,
eastern and central Oklahoma, southeast Kansas and southwest
Missouri.
   Occasional thunderstorms and showers were widely scattered over
Wisconsin, northern Illinois, Indiana, lower Michigan, southwest
Ohio and northeast Kentucky.
   Cool weather chilled the lower Mississippi Valley early Tuesday,
and several low-temperature records for May 2 were broken or tied
in Arkansas. It was 33 degrees in Calico Rock, breaking the 1973
and 1976 records of 35 degrees; 36 degrees in Ozark, where the
38-degree mark had stood since 1909; and 37 degrees in Fort Smith,
which tied its record set in 1909.
   By contrast, it was 90 degrees in Miami, tying the
high-temperature record set in 1981.
   The nation's low temperature Tuesday morning was 22 degrees in
Kearney and Kimball, Neb. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m.
EDT ranged from 40 degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 94 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
   The national weather forecast for Wednesday called for showers
from northern New England to inland New York and northern
Pennsylvania, as well as over northwest Montana and along the
Oregon coast; and showers and thunderstorms from Oklahoma to
Arkansas.
   High temperatures for Wednesday were forecast in the upper 40s
and the 50s in northern New England, northwest New York, western
Pennsylvania, eastern Ohio, northern lower Michigan and upper
Michigan, as well as much of Montana; the 80s from Florida to the
Gulf Coast states, Texas and much of New Mexico; the 80s and 90s
from southwest Texas to the desert Southwest; and in the 60s and
70s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
