<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     05-02 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Rejects Opposition Demand For More Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government on
Tuesday rejected an opposition demand to negotiate for more
legislative reforms to guarantee fair elections next year.
   But both government and opposition representatives agreed to
meet again and present their cases to a panel charged with
evaluating whether the Sandinistas have fulfilled promises made in
regional pacts.
   ``To accept (negotiations) is to accept that the government has
not fulfilled its part of the El Salvador accords,'' Rene Nunez,
minister of the presidency, said after a two-hour meeting of the
Committee for National Reconciliation.
   ``The step previous to acknowledging this request is for an
evaluation to be made on whether the El Salvador accords have been
met,'' he added.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the archbishop of Managua and
president of the committee, said the panel would meet again May 10
to hear both sides and would then issue its evaluation.
   Nunez attended the meeting representing Vice President Sergio
Ramirez, a committee member representing the Sandinistas.
   Mauricio Diaz, leader of the Popular Social Christian Party and
panel's opposition representative, presented the demand in a letter
addressed to Obando that he read to reporters.
   President Daniel Ortega and the presidents of El Salvador,
Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala signed an agreement in El
Salvador Feb. 14 in which Nicaragua promised electoral and other
legal reforms to ensure fair general elections, which Ortega moved
up by 10 months to Feb. 25, 1990.
   The Sandinista-controlled National Assembly passed the reforms
to electoral and news media laws in March. But the opposition said
their demands were ignored and that the laws passed give the
Sandinistas unfair advantage in balloting.
   Ortega is now on a 10-country tour of Western Europe to seek
financial and political support for Nicaragua. Some of those
governments have said more money to this Central American country
depends on the Sandinistas' fulfillment of regional peace accords.
   At a news conference Tuesday in Athens, Greece, Ortega said he
was trying to find a way to improve relations with the United
States and declared, ``We are not its enemy.''
   He expressed hope that President Bush would change the policies
toward Nicaragua pursued by President Ronald Reagan.
   Bush ``must know that policy failed and that is why he should do
something different,'' he said.
   Nicaragua is suffering a severe economic crisis and badly needs
foreign aid.
   The government blames the crisis on eight years of war with the
U.S.-supported Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras, a four-year U.S.
economic blockade, and devastation wrought by Hurricane Joan in
October.
   The opposition says the Sandinistas' managerial ineptness has
had much to do with the country's economic problems.
</TEXT>
