<FIRST>u i AM-Missiles-Europe 1stLd-Writethru a0712 05-02 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missiles-Europe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Compromise Does Not Address Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD Kohl, De Mita comments. Pickup 4th
graf, `Most of ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO-Missiles Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. proposal for resolving the
internal NATO dispute over short-range nuclear missiles does not
address West German demands for East-West negotiations on the
weapons, an alliance official said Tuesday.
   In Rome, Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany said he was open
to ``reasonable compromise'' but wants talks to begin soon. The
United States and Britain have rejected such negotiations.
   Kohl, however, expressed hope the allies could reach a unified
position on the issue during a summit at the end of this month. He
said NATO could negotiate on the battlefield weapons at the same
time it discusses strategic arms, conventional forces and chemical
weapons.
   The comments came after a meeting with Premier Ciriaco De Mita,
who said Italy supports linking the proposed talks on reducing the
short-range nuclear weapons to progress in conventional arms talks.
   In Paris, Foreign Ministers Roland Dumas of France and
Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany told reporters it is
essential that a common position emerge from the NATO summit.
   Most of the short-range Lance missiles are in West Germany, and
a battle fought with such weapons would take place on its territory.
   The NATO official said the American plan suggests the 16-member
North Atlantic Treaty Organization announce unilateral reductions
in its short-range nuclear arsenal and challenge the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact to meet those levels.
   In London, A British Defense Ministry policy paper said the
Soviets have modernized or replaced 95 percent of their short-range
nuclear missile systems in Eastern Europe in the past five years.
   A separate ``fact sheet'' said the Soviet Union ``has been
aggressively pursuing'' modernization of its short-range forces and
now has a 16-1 advantage over NATO west of the Ural Mountains.
   As described by the alliance official, the U.S. plan calls for
reducing the number of weapons as part of a NATO program of
modernizing the Lance missiles.
   Additional reductions in those arms would be linked to progress
in East-West negotiations in Vienna on conventional forces in
Europe, the official said.
   A U.S. official in Washington confirmed the account but said
several other options were under consideration. He said one was
resumption of research and development by West Germany on a missile
that could attack airfields and other targets now covered by the
Lance.
   In Bonn, a German official said: ``The German position remains
clear and unchanged. No decision on modernization until 1992 and
prompt superpower talks on the short-range missiles.''
   He dismissed the U.S. suggestions as ``old stuff that people are
using to divert the discussion from the real issues.''
   None of the three officials would let his name be used.
   Alliance members are seeking acceptable language on the weapons
issue to write into the Comprehensive Concept, a blueprint for NATO
strategy to be presented to the May 29-30 summit at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
   The NATO official said the American plan pulls together several
ideas that have been put forward in the alliance.
   It would take reductions proposed by U.S. Gen. John Galvin, NATO
supreme military commander in Europe, and challenge the Soviets to
meet them.
   Galvin has urged NATO to upgrade the Lance, arguing that its
modernization would permit a substantial reduction in nuclear
artillery. Military analysts say the missile, introduced in 1972,
will become obsolete in 1995.
   It has a range of a little more than 60 miles, which would be
extended by modernization to more than 250 miles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
