<FIRST>r a AM-AtlantaEditor     05-02 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta Editor,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Newspapers Name Ron Martin New Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald D. Martin, vice president and executive
editor of USA Today, was named editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution on Tuesday, five months after Bill Kovach
resigned the post in a dispute with the newspapers' management.
   Publisher Jay Smith said Martin, 51, was a ``superb newsman who,
better than anyone else I know, understands the importance of a
newspaper that connects with the readers. That's a pressing issue
now.''
   Martin will take over Monday, Smith said.
   Arnold Rosenfeld, who served as interim editor, will become
editor in chief of Cox Newspapers, Smith said.
   Martin was USA Today's original executive editor and got the
title of vice president in 1987. As vice president, he coordinated
USA Today's news activities with other Gannett Co. Inc. members.
   He previously was editor of the Baltimore News-American and US
magazine and was managing editor of several papers including the
Rochester Democrat and Chronicle, The Miami Herald and the New York
Post.
   Martin said he planned to spend some time getting to know
Atlanta before setting any goals.
   ``I'm very excited about the prospects,'' he said. ``I've been
looking at the newspaper very closely the last few days. There are
a lot of good things happening here ... it's a great base to build
on.''
   The Journal-Constitution, which won the 1989 Pulitzer Prize for
investigative reporting, publishes in the morning as The Atlanta
Constitution and in the afternoon as The Atlanta Journal on
weekdays and in a combined edition on Saturday and Sunday. The
newspapers have a combined reporting corps but separate editorial
page staffs.
   Kovach, a former Washington bureau chief for The New York Times,
resigned from the Atlanta newspapers last November after a
disagreement over control of the Cox chain's Washington bureau. He
currently is a Nieman Fellow at Harvard University.
</TEXT>
