<FIRST>r a AM-ABCAdvertisers     05-02 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABC Advertisers,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Pulls `Crimes of Passion II' for Lack of Advertisers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC pulled a program dealing with crimes of
passion after advertisers showed no interest in the show, which
included re-enactments of violent crimes, the network announced
Tuesday.
   ``Crimes of Passion II'' was replaced Saturday night by ``Livin'
Large'' and ``Heart and Soul,'' two 1988 comedy pilots that did not
make ABC's program schedule.
   Advertisers have begun to shun explicit programming in response
to protests by viewers. Their decision not to back ``Crimes of
Passion II'' did not appear related to ratings, since an earlier
episode of the show aired last October and did well.
   The first ``Crimes of Passion'' garnered a 13.2 rating and 23
share in the Wednesday time period now occupied by ``China Beach.''
By comparison, ``China Beach'' had a 12.2 rating and 21 share last
week. The rating is a percentage of the nation's 90.4 million
households with television. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   Advertisers pulled out of NBC's Geraldo Rivera special on devil
worship earlier this season and others backed off from NBC's
satirical ``Saturday Night Live.'' A Michigan woman's campaign
against Fox's raunchy ``Married ... With Children'' received
publicity earlier this year. Fox says the relatively high-rated
show remains sold out nonetheless.
   An ABC press release for ``Crimes of Passion II,'' whose host is
Bruce Dern, said it ``explores real-life cases in which people have
committed an act of violence aimed against someone they love.''
   It's replacements, ``Livin' Large'' and ``Heart and Soul,'' were
among the lowest-rated shows of the week.
</TEXT>
