<FIRST>u a AM-SecondAbduction 2ndLd-Writethru a0759 05-02 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0759,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Leads In Search For Missing Baby</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf to CORRECT sheriff's name to Yocom, sted Yocum.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched Tuesday for a 6-week-old girl
whose parents said was abducted under circumstances almost
identical to the disappearance of their other daughter three years
ago, officials said.
   About 20 local, state and federal law enforcement officers aided
by tracking dogs have been looking for Heather Sims since Sunday,
police Sgt. Rick McCain told a news conference.
   Parents Robert Sims, 37, and Paula Sims, 30, said the baby was
abducted Saturday night in almost exactly the same way their
13-day-old daughter, Loralei, was taken three years ago. Loralei's
body was found later.
   Mrs. Sims said a gunman approached her outside their home around
10:30 p.m. Saturday while her husband was at work at a steel plant.
She told police she was forced back into the house and knocked out.
   An hour later, she told authorities, her husband returned home,
revived her and discovered the baby missing.
   In June 1986, Mrs. Sims told police a masked gunman broke into
their home around 10:20 p.m. while her husband was at work and took
Loralei.
   The baby's body was found five days later, about 150 feet from
the couple's home in Brighton, which is about 10 miles north of
this town of 40,000 people across the Mississippi River from St.
Louis. No cause of death was determined and no arrests were made in
that case, although authorities said the parents were suspects.
   The two failed a lie detector test of their account of Loralei's
disappearance, said Jersey County Sheriff Frank Yocom. They claimed
Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination and didn't
testify before a county grand jury that investigated the death, he
said.
   Investigators said Tuesday they had no evidence to doubt the
couple's claim in Heather's disappearance. ``There's nothing to
indicate that the Sims are anything but victims at this time,''
McCain said.
   Investigators have found little evidence and have few leads, he
said.
   ``We haven't given up hope of finding the baby alive,'' the
sergeant added.
   A hospital found no evidence Mrs. Sims was injured Saturday
night, he said.
   The couple's 15-month-old son, who was sleeping at home at the
time, was not disturbed, officials said. No valuables were taken
and no ransom note was left.
</TEXT>
