<DOCNO> AP890502-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Cusack Adv08   05-02 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Cusack, Adv 08,0827</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, May 8 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Say Anything'' opened April 14 in New York and Los Angeles.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before agreeing to star in ``Say Anything,''
John Cusack insisted on a few changes.
   First of all, the script.
   ``The essence was there, but it needed to be fleshed out,'' said
the 22-year-old actor, who portrays Lloyd Dobler, a down-to-earth
high school senior in love with the class valedictorian (Ione Skye).
   ``I saw things inherent in the structure but I said, `If you
want me to do the film, I'm going have to do this, this and this.
I'm not going to do this, this and this.'
   ``He (writer-director Cameron Crowe) said, `Great, bring it on.'
I was very flattered and grateful they trusted me enough.''
   Then came the wardrobe.
   ``I'm at the point where I costume myself. I went in and met
with the costume designer, who to me is someone who tries to find
out what I'm going for and helps me along that way. This costume
designer had a whole rack full of clothes. There were V-neck
sweaters and corduroy pants.
   ``I said, `I will never wear anything on this rack, anything
like this rack. Go get me a `Clash' T-shirt. Go get met me a
trenchcoat. Get me hats, different high-top sneakers.'''
   Finally, there was the matter of Crowe, who has written
extensively about rock music and authored the best-selling account
of teen-age life, ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' later made into
a feature film. Cusack hesitated to work with a first-time director
but was impressed by Crowe's enthusiasm.
   ``He was really persistent. He flew out to Chicago and handed me
a copy of `Catcher in the Rye.' He said, `You're 21 years old,
you're never going to be able to play a younger guy again. Why not
end it with a positive note.''
   Cusack, who has also starred in ``The Sure Thing,'' ``Eight Men
Out'' and ``Tapeheads,'' was determined to make Lloyd believeable,
wanting to avoid another angry young man such as Sean Penn, or the
``so hip and so cute'' teen-agers portrayed by Michael J. Fox and
Kirk Cameron.
   ``Here's a guy who knows what's going on in the world, who's
emotionally political,'' Cusack said of his character.
   ``He's a pretty smart guy who just doesn't have the skills to
express himself. He doesn't buy into the hype. He doesn't believe
the hype. He's not negative. He's not going to be a negative force
in the world. He can't live his life in a negative way.
   ``We (Cusack and Crowe) had a great rapport about what was right
for Lloyd. By the end of the film, he would start a sentence and I
would finish it.''
   Cusack, the brother of actress Joan Cusack (``Working Girl,''
``Broadcast News'') and son of documentary filmamker Richard
Cusack, grew up in Chicago and was just 9 when he began taking
classes at the Piven Theatre Workshop in Evanston, Ill. He had
minor roles in the movies ``Sixteen Candles'' and ``Class'' before
being cast by director Rob Reiner for the lead in ``The Sure
Thing.''
   ``I was amped, just ready to go. I wasn't smart enough to be
nervous. I was just excited to be working with Rob,'' recalled
Cusack, who would later work with Reiner on ``Stand by Me.''
   ``I just really dug his work process, it was real similar to
mine. Rob is this guy who directs by saying, `Match my passion.'
There was great energy on the set.''
   But Cusack went on to appear in a series of poorly received
films, including ``Better Off Dead'' and ``One Crazy Summer.'' He
became frustrated from reading an endless number of bad scripts,
and admitted that his career was ``in the pits.''
   ``I remember reading the script for, `Some Kind of Wonderful.'
They wanted me do that. At the end of the film the guy takes all
this college money to buy a jet, a Cadillac, a helicopter. He
completely woos this girl with material possessions and symbols of
wealth. What kind of story is that?''
   He was happier making films such as ``Tapeheads,'' a parody of
the music video business that starred Cusack and his friend, Tim
Robbins, as a pair of sleazy producers.
   ``We were so sick of these run-of-the mill scripts _ same
characters, same plots, not funny, not fresh. Somebody sent me this
script called `Tapeheads,' and we saw the name and said, `Let's do
it.'
   ``It sounded really sick,'' he said. ``It was a black comedy on
the music business and I got to finally play a guy who wasn't a
good guy, who would sell out his mother for the right price.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
