<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-02 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0835</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   WPP Group PLC's proposal to expand its
advertising and marketing empire with the $730 million acquisition
of Ogilvy Group Inc. got a solid vote of confidence from investors.
   The price of Ogilvy's stock skyrocketed more than $17 a share
Monday and surpassed WPP's proposed bid.
   Ogilvy announced Sunday that WPP Chief Executive Martin Sorrell
had proposed to pay $45 a share for the parent of the advertising
agency Ogilvy &amp; Mather Worldwide. It would be the biggest takeover
of an advertising holding company ever.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending, hit by a sharp drop in
the highway category, suffered its third consecutive monthly
decline in March, the first time building activity has shown such
weakness since just before the last recession, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Monday that spending on public and
private building projects declined by 0.3 percent in March,
following even larger declines of 0.8 percent in February and 0.7
percent in January.
   The February decline represented a sharp revision from the
original report a month ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in the case of a woman who
says she was denied promotion because others thought she acted too
much like a man, made it more difficult for employers to win
lawsuits accusing them of sexual stereotyping and other bias.
   By a 6-3 vote Monday, the justices ordered further lower court
hearings in a suit against the accounting firm Price Waterhouse by
a former employee, Ann Hopkins.
   Separately, the high court agreed to hear arguments on the
proposed joint operating agreement between the Detroit Free Press
and the Detroit News.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite President Bush's ``read my lips'' vow
against new taxes, his administration is considering higher
gasoline taxes for 1991 as part of a possible trade for concessions
such as a lower capital gains tax, officials said.
   Administration sources said Monday it is unlikely Bush can hold
his no-new-taxes stance for more than one year, given the
difficulty of reaching budget-deficit targets by adjusting only the
spending side of the ledger.
   The sources said planning was under way for a possible fiscal
1991 budget pact with Congress that would indeed include new taxes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines indicated it was moving rapidly
with its plan to sell $1.8 billion in assets and it downplayed
proposals by suitors interested in buying the entire airline.
   In a filing submitted Monday to federal bankruptcy court in New
York, Eastern disclosed it had firm sales contracts or received
acceptable offers for about $1.1 billion of its assets.
   As the crippling strike against the carrier heads into its third
month, Eastern's unions say they remain solid, although some
employees _ both union and management _ are bailing out.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If there is a smoking gun in Polaroid Corp.'s
giant patent infringement lawsuit against Eastman Kodak Co., it may
be a note that Kodak's former chairman jotted in the margin of an
internal memo.
   As the trial got under way in federal court in Boston Monday,
Polaroid's lawyers cited the two-word scribble as evidence that
Kodak deliberately violated seven Polaroid patents and should be
ordered to pay its rival nearly $12 billion for lost profits,
interest, and punitive damages.
   If U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone awards Polaroid anything
near that amount, it will be the largest patent infringement
decision in history.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midwest department store operators Carson Pirie
Scott &amp; Co. and P.A. Bergner announced they have agreed to merge,
with Bergner acquiring Carson for about $454 million.
   Monday's announcement wraps up a month-long courtship of Carson
that began in mid-April when Bergner made a $282 million buyout
offer worth about $20 a share.
   That bid from the Swiss-owned chain was rejected, as was the
sweetened offer one week later of $24 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. opened its $400
million Disney-MGM Studios theme park, hoping to lure the nostalgic
to its version of Hollywood's golden era and thrill-seekers to
rides that will take them to places like Catastrophe Canyon.
   The 135-acre complex opened Monday blends filmmaking with
backstage studio tours and ride-through, walk-through attractions.
   Movie and television production began last summer on its three
sprawling sound studios and backlot street scenes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground Monday, faced with news suggesting
persistent strength in the economy. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials lost 3.84 points at 2,414.96.
   The dollar wound up higher against all major currencies. Gold
prices barely budged.
   Bond prices fell.
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose strongly; gasoline and
crude oil futures rallied; cattle and hogs were up; and gold and
silver prices gained moderately.
</TEXT>
