<FIRST>r f PM-PanAm-Johnson     05-02 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am-Johnson,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Agrees to Sell Security Unit to Johnson Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnson Controls Inc. of Milwaukee has agreed to
buy the security and maintenance unit of Pan Am Corp., the
companies announced Monday.
   The sale price, in cash, won't be disclosed until the sale is
completed sometime during the second quarter, the companies said
Monday. The transaction is subject to regulatory approval.
   Pan Am, strapped by losses from Pan American World Airways, its
main subsidiary, put its Pan Am World Services Inc. unit up for
sale in January. The subsidiary, based in Cape Canaveral, Fla.,
markets security, maintenance and other services to government
agencies, the military and other airlines.
   World Services, with about 10,000 employees at over 100
locations worldwide, had revenue of $600 million in 1988. Financial
analysts estimate the unit's potential sale value at around $200
million.
   Johnson Controls provides operations services on a contract
basis to airports, sports arenas, schools, hospitals and other
facilities. The company, which had revenue of $3.1 billion in 1988,
also makes heating and cooling controls, automotive seating,
batteries and plastics.
   Pan Am's Northeast shuttle service and Pan Am Express, a
commuter airline, also are considered profitable operations. But
they are more closely tied to Pan Am's main airline business than
is the World Services unit.
   Some analysts hav wondered whether the World Services move
represents a new Pan Am strategy to sell performing assets rather
than strip away parts of loss-making World Airways, such as routes
and airport facilities.
   Pan Am officials say the sale of World Services is designed to
help finance the company's planned investments for the near future.
Those investments include $61 million for improvements at World
Airways' main terminal at Kennedy International Airport in New
York, $25 million for refurbishing aircraft interiors, $20 million
for improvements in information systems and other programs,
according to Pan Am.
   Rival Eastern Airlines announced plans Thursday to lease 14
Boeing 727-200s to Pan Am's World Airways for $96.6 million over
five years. The deal must be approved by federal bankruptcy court,
where strikebound Eastern filed for protection from creditors on
March 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SchererPurchase     05-02 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scherer Purchase,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Lehman Hutton Unit Agrees To Acquire Scherer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc. unit
agreed to acquire gelatin capsule manufacturer R.P. Scherer Corp.
in an offer worth nearly $407 million, the companies announced.
   RPS Acquisition Corp., formed by Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings
and its Merchant Banking Partnerships, will commence a
$31.75-a-share tender offer for Scherer stock on Friday, Shearson
spokesman Steve Faigen said Monday.
   The tender offer would total $352 million and RPS would assume
debt totaling $54.9 million, for a $406.9 million total, Faigen
said.
   Scherer would become a privately held company, with interests
held by entities including Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings and its
Management Banking Partnerships, Faigen said.
   Scherer opened several purchase offers last Wednesday, then
began negotiations that led to the RPS transaction, Scherer
spokeswoman Jayne Colombo said. She didn't identify other bidders
or say how many there were but said the capsule maker didn't expect
further offers.
   Scherer stock closed Friday at $33.37{ a share. The company
asked the National Association of Securities Dealers not to permit
over-the-counter trading in its stock Monday because of the
impending announcement, Colombo said.
   Scherer decided in September to consider offers after a dispute
between former president Peter Fink, who opposed selling, and his
estranged wife Karla Scherer Fink, a board member and daughter of
the company founder.
   Karla Fink's pro-sale forces prevailed in a proxy fight and
Peter Fink left, forming another company, Quantum Corp. of St.
Clair Shores. Fink, who said he might try to buy Scherer, didn't
return a telephone call Monday.
   Scherer has about 4,400 employees in 22 facilities in 13
countries. It reported sales of $290.7 million in its fiscal year
ended March 31, 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ogilvy-WPP Bjt   05-02 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ogilvy-WPP, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>WPP Likely To Succeed In Ogilvy Bid, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industry analysts expect Ogilvy Group Inc. to
fight a takeover from London-based WPP Group PLC, but ultimately
they expect WPP will succeed in creating an ad agency holding
company that will vie for the title of world's largest.
   Wall Street reacted enthsiastically Monday to the $730 million
WPP bid, disclosed Sunday, bidding up the price of Ogilvy's stock
more that $17 and surpassing WPP's bid.
   WPP Chief Executive Martin Sorrell has proposed to pay $45 a
share for the parent of the advertising agency Ogilvy &amp; Mather
Worldwide.
   Ogilvy's stock soared $17.12{ a share to close at $49.12{ Monday
in over-the-counter trading.
   If the deal goes through, it would be the biggest takeover of an
advertising holding firm ever, breaking the record set by WPP's
purchase of JWT Group Inc., parent of J. Walter Thompson Co., two
years ago.
   Ogilvy, meanwhile, says it wants to remain independent.
   ``Mr. Sorrell's proposal letter to Ogilvy appears primarily to
be a sales pitch which suffers from serious flaws in business
logic,'' Ogilvy Chairman Kenneth Roman said in a statement Sunday.
   Analysts said the British firm would likely win the fight.
   ``There's a real possibility that Sorrell will succeed,'' said
Fred Anschel, an advertising industry analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., adding that many shareholders would find WPP's
all-cash offer hard to turn down.
   ``They have some (defenses),'' said John Dougherty, an analyst
with County NatWest USA. ``But I don't think they have enough to
resist a bid that I think ultimately will go into the mid-50s.''
   The deal would create an advertising and marketing holding
company that would rival Britain's Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC as the
world's largest.
   WPP had international billings last year of $7.8 billion,
ranking it third among the world's ad agency holding companies,
according to Advertising Age, a trade publication. Ogilvy, with
billings of $5.7 billion, placed fifth.
   Combined, their billings would have about equaled Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi's $13.5 billion.
   An industry source said WPP wants to become the best
multinational marketing service and not necessarly the biggest.
   But WPP may yet achieve that distinction. Ogilvy would be the
latest entry on a lengthy list of advertising and marketing firms
bought by WPP.
   In the two years since it picked up JWT, WPP has purchased
Einson Freeman, a sales promotion agency; Anspach Grossman Portugal
Inc., a corporate identity consultant; Reese Communications and
Target Systems, two U.S. companies specializing in public affairs
and direct mail marketing; Stewart McColl Associates PLC, a British
design firm; and Mendoza Dillon &amp; Associados Inc., an advertising
firm specializing in the Hispanic market.
   Earlier this year, WPP agreed to buy PARG Public Affairs
Resource Group of Toronto, one of Canada's largest public affairs
consulting and public opinion research firms.
   WPP's acquisitive strategy is much like Saatchi &amp; Saatchi's _
which comes as no surprise to industry watchers because Sorrell was
the architect of much of that firm's expansion, including the
purchase of Ted Bates Worldwide for a then-record $450 million in
1986.
   Analysts said WPP's latest proposal was more a result of
Sorrell's expansion plans rather than any problems at Ogilvy.
   Ogilvy ``seems to fit in pretty well with Martin Sorrell's
goals,'' said Vicki Weber, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
``This is not a company that was begging to be taken over.''
   Said Anschel, the Dean Witter analyst, ``The biggest knock
against them (Ogilvy) is their earings have been basically flat
since 1985.'' But, he said, ``It has a very fine brand-name in the
advertising business.''
   For Sorrell, expansion has not been without trouble: His
purchase of JWT, which included the advertising agency Lord Geller
Federico Einstein Inc., led top Lord Geller executives to defect
and start their own company. Thetwo sides are fighting in court.
   WPP's major clients include Ford Motor Co., Quaker Oats Co.,
Kellogg Co., Eastman Kodak Co., and the Kraft operations of Philip
Morris Cos. Inc.
   Ogilvy's major clients include American Express Co., Polaroid
Corp., Seagram Co. Ltd., the Shell oil company and Unilever, the
Anglo-Dutch consumer products company.
   Ogilvy earned $32.9 million last year on revenue of $838
million. WPP earned $38.1 million on revenues of $974.7 million.
</TEXT>
