<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   05-02 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Forging Ahead with Asset Sales, Filing Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines, downplaying
proposals from suitors interested in buying the entire carrier,
indicated it was speeding ahead with its plan to sell $1.8 billion
in assets separately.
   In a filing submitted Monday to federal bankruptcy court in New
York, Eastern disclosed it had firm sales contracts or received
acceptable offers for about $1.1 billion of its assets.
   Those assets include Eastern's Northeast shuttle service,
already slated to be sold to developer Donald Trump for $365
million, airport gates in Philadelphia and routes between that city
and others, said Eastern spokesman Robin Matell. He declined to
elaborate on the non-shuttle deals.
   Another $300 million in asset sales ``are subject to serious
discussion where reasonable offers have been received,'' while an
additional $400 million in sales are being discussed with
``responsible and interested parties,'' Eastern said in the filing.
   The Miami-based airline said it expects to announce several
deals in the coming weeks.
   All such sales must be approved by the federal bankruptcy court
overseeing the airline's Chapter 11 reorganization under protection
from creditors.
   Eastern's Machinists, pilots and flight attendants unions, which
have been off the job since March 4, have opposed sales of the
airline's assets. U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland has
pushed to have the company sold in its entirety and has scheduled a
Wednesday hearing for arguments over why such an auction of the
whole airline _ including the shuttle _ should not take place.
   In its filing, Eastern said it recently received an offer from
billionaire hotel executive Jay Pritzker to buy all of the airline.
Eastern described the offer as ``at best, a generalized expression
of interest.''
   On Friday, a statement was issued on behalf of a group of
unidentified New York financial institutions that indicated the
consortium was developing a proposal under which it might pay $1
billion for Eastern if the deal included assets sold by the airline
since its 1986 acquisition by Texas Air Corp.
   An attorney for the group later said the statement was issued in
error but the group actually was formulating a proposal.
   Eastern, in its filing, countered that the group lacks ``the
financial resources to consummate any purchase and, indeed, has
only the vaguest hope of obtaining such resources.''
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, who owns Trans World Airlines
Inc., has expressed interest and was expected to submit a formal
bid in the near future.
   Eastern plans to restructure to operate at one-third its
pre-strike size and raise $1.8 billion to pay debts by selling
planes, airport gates and landing slots at unspecified locations.
   As a first step, the airline announced plans Thursday to lease
14 Boeing 727-200s to Pan American World Airways for $96.6 million
over five years.
   All transactions and any sale of the entire airline must be
approved by U.S. bankruptcy court, where Eastern filed for
protection from creditors on March 9. However, Texas Air can't be
compelled under the bankruptcy laws to sell Eastern in its entirety
if it does not want to.
   Eastern management has the exclusive right until early July to
present a reorganization plan for court approval.
   Eastern's Machinists union struck the carrier on March 4 after a
long wage dispute. They were joined by pilots and flight
attendants, virtually grounding the airline and forcing it to seek
bankruptcy protection five days later.
   Eastern said Monday its non-union employees have delivered
petitions with more than 6,200 signatures to the bankruptcy court
expressing their support for the plan to rebuild as a smaller
carrier.
</TEXT>
