<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Workers     05-02 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Workers,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Eastern Employees Bailing Out As Strike Lengthens</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a crippling strike at Eastern Airlines heads
into its third month, the carrier's unions say they remain solid,
although some employees _ union and management _ are bailing out.
   Karen Ceremsak, a company spokeswoman, can't estimate how many
of Eastern's 12,000 non-union employees have taken other jobs since
the March 4 strike by the company's Machinists, pilots and flight
attendants virtually grounded the airline.
   ``As more time passes, more people will go on to other things,''
she said.
   The Machinists union estimates that departures among Eastern's
17,000 union workers number only in the hundreds, although nearly
all of the remaining union employees still refuse to work for the
airline.
   Eastern has cut back to 10 percent of pre-strike operations, has
about 4,500 active employees and has entered Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization and protection from creditors.
   Parent Texas Air Corp. plans to rebuild Eastern as a smaller
airline without the unions. But the unions are optimistic that new
ownership for the entire airline still can be found, even though
Eastern insists that none of the offers it has received are viable.
   Wally Haber, general chairman of the Machinists union, chuckled
recently when reminded of his March 4 prediction that the strike
would last only 10 days. Eastern's March 9 bankruptcy filing
``threw a monkey wrench into the whole system,'' putting the
company into the slow-moving procedures of bankruptcy court, he
said.
   Haber, noting that few of the 8,500 Eastern machinists were
around for the last Eastern strike, for 42 days in 1966, said:
``I've been amazed at the resolve, the way the people are really
sticking together.''
   United Airlines, Boeing Corp. and several other companies have
been wooing Eastern mechanics, Haber said, but the union estimates
departures have been only in the hundreds. He said about one-third
of the union membership is working at some type of job, but most
are temporary or part time.
   Officials at the pilots union _ whose members would sacrifice
seniority that determines their salaries and flight assignments if
they switched airlines _ say there have been few departures. Flight
attendants union officials say many of their members have taken
other jobs but would prefer to return o Eastern if possible.
   Strikers have been aided somewhat by their own union benefits _
Machinists receive $100 a week in union strike benefits and the
pilots $2,400 a month _ and from elsewhere in organized labor. The
AFL-CIO has about $1 million for Eastern strikers, with the
financially-strapped flight attendants union set to receive
two-thirds of that amount.
   Thousands of dollars worth of groceries and frozen meats have
been donated to the unions, Haber said, and South Florida farmers
have invited crews of strikers to come to their fields for all the
vegetables they could pick.
   ``The economic situation is different now than it was 23 years
ago,'' Haber said. ``Over half of our people have two jobs in the
family.''
   Many non-union employees _ who have no strike benefits _ can't
afford to be as patient, especially given the uncertainty of what
the ultimate resolution of the strike will be.
   Karen Madsen, former manager of Eastern benefits compensation,
moved March 20 to Southeast Banks for a similar job offering more
money and more security.
   ``I hope they make it and in a way I'd sort of like to be
there,'' said Ms. Madsen. ``After 19 years, there's still a place
in my heart for Eastern. But I couldn't afford to take the
financial risk and I got the opportunity to go with a good
company.''
   Among pilots, Eastern's generally are some of industry's most
experienced, the pilots union says. But although other major
carriers are anxious to hire experienced pilots, the Eastern
veterans are reluctant to trade their seniority for new jobs
elsewhere.
   ``The seniority repercussions...are more acceptable to a younger
gentleman at lower seniority levels, as opposed to me when I've
been here 16 years,'' said pilot Gary Greksa.
   Within a couple of years at Eastern, Greksa said, he would move
from his $65,000-a-year job as a senior co-pilot to captain. At
another airline, he said, he would have to sign on at an initial,
probationary salary of $18,000, rising to $25,000 as a second
officer the year after that.
   ``That's why we're staying to fight,'' he said.
   But many pilots nevertheless have applied to other airlines,
Greksa said.
   ``We all buy life insurance, but we don't want to die,'' he said.
   Roger Dubois, an Eastern mechanic since 1980, is among strikers
who have other jobs but still hope to return to Eastern. The
35-year-old married father of one, facing mortgage payments, has
started his own home improvement business with another Eastern
Machinist.
   Dubois and friends who also have taken new jobs remain
optimistic about working again for Eastern under new management.
   ``We love the job when we don't think about the last three
years,'' Dubois said. ``We want to go back. We left a part of our
lives there.''
</TEXT>
