<FIRST>r f PM-Kollmorgen-Vernitron     05-02 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kollmorgen-Vernitron,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technology Company Merges With Smaller Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kollmorgen Corp., a maker of electrical
and optical equipment, has agreed to be taken over by the smaller
Vernitron Corp. for $25 a share, or about $250 million, ending a
five-month battle.
   The agreement Monday followed two weeks of maneuvering by
Stamford-based Kollmorgen as it searched for another buyer and a
better offer for shareholders.
   The merger still depends on the approval of Kollmorgen
shareholders and financing.
   The merger would create a larger technology company, with
products in optics and electronics and more than $400 million in
annual sales.
   The combined assets and sales would provide a larger base needed
to support advanced research and development at Vernitron, a
Deerfield, N.Y.-based company that specializes in electromechanical
devices, officials said.
   Officials said Vernitron is positioning itself for the
unification of the European Common Market in 1992.
   The agreement ended a contest that began with a friendly
Vernitron offer of $20 a share in December, included several
lawsuits, two unfriendly tender offers and Kollmorgen's decision to
search openly for another buyer.
   Vernitron has commitments for $425 million in financing _ $250
million from Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and $175 million from
Banque Paribas, a French investment bank.
</TEXT>
