<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     05-02 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
following a three-day May Day holiday weekend in most financial
capitals. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar appears to have lots of
support, partly from high interest rates.
   ``The market doesn't appear to be afraid of anything right
now,'' said Oswald Diettrich, head market risk adviser for Bank of
America in Frankfurt.
   Other traders said the holiday-shortened week could result in
thin volumes exaggerating any changes in the dollar. Some European
markets will also be closed on Thursday for Ascension Day.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.05 yen to a closing 133.85. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8871 West German marks, up from 1.8805; 1.6847
Swiss francs, up from 1.6742; 6.3804 French francs, up from 6.3650;
2.1265 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1220; 1,380.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,377.50; 1.1838 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1835
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6831, more than 1 cent
cheaper than $1.6945 Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $377.25 a troy ounce,
down from $378.25 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $376.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $377.40, down from $377.75 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.41 to close at a bid $378.18.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.64 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $5.63.
</TEXT>
