<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     05-02 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Soar, Dollar Dips In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index climbed to a
new high for the fifth consecutive trading day today, while the
dollar fell slightly against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar, after gaining a total of 2.73 yen in four trading
days, closed at 133.85 yen, down 0.05 yen from Monday's close of
133.90 yen. It opened at 133.75 yen and ranged between 133.65 yen
and 134.05 yen.
   A Mitsubishi Bank dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market in the afternoon,
checking the dollar's rise from its opening level.
   Despite the central bank's dollar-selling, he added, there was
not much movement in exchange levels during the day.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 33,954.99, up
161.82 points, or 0.48 percent.
   ``Even though the index rose considerably, the volume was low,''
said a trader at Nomura Securities, adding that the rise was spread
over a wide variety of issues including housing, electricals and
pharmaceuticals.
   ``There is a pattern of buying stocks before extended
vacations,'' the dealer continued, ``and today's actions fit into
that pattern.''
   Japanese markets will be closed from Wednesday until Monday for
a series of holidays, part of Japan's ``Golden Week.''
</TEXT>
