<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TankerSpill-Glance     05-02 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill-Glance,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief comparison between Exxon's
revised plan to clean up the Alaskan oil spill and its original
plan submitted April 15.
   PERSONNEL _ The latest plan calls for 3,400 cleanup workers,
plus an unspecified number outside Prince William Sound. The
original plan recommended a total of 4,000 workers, virtually all
within Prince William Sound. The workers are being paid $16.67 an
hour.
   TIME _ Both plans envisaged completion by Sept. 15. The original
plan was based on assumptions that weather delays would be minimal.
The revised proposal concedes that inclement weather and logistical
problems could idle crews on half the potential workdays.
   NATURAL CLEANSING _ Exxon's revised proposal says that 191 miles
of lightly oiled beach may be left untouched to be cleansed by the
environment. The original proposal did not address ``natural
cleansing.''
   MILES _ The latest plan calls for a cleanup along 364 miles of
coastline, as opposed to about 300 miles in the April 15 proposal.
   PROSPECTS _ Coast Guard Commandant Paul A. Yost, Jr. rejected
the April 15 plan as incomplete. He said he will decide on the
latest proposal within a week.
</TEXT>
