<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     05-02 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower In Lackluster Trading At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were mostly lower in lackluster
trading at midday Tuesday, as the market ran out of reasons to
extend last week's strong gains after a three-day holiday weekend,
traders said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 8.1
points, or 0.3 percent, at 2,109.9 at 12:17 p.m. The index opened
3.2 points down and then fell as much as 10.1 points at midmorning.
   Volume was 166.0 million shares by midday compared with 373.9
million shares on Friday.
   Fresh concern about the outlook for international interest rates
took the wind from the market's sails at the outset of trading, but
there was scant selling pressure to give the market much momentum,
traders said.
   ``Very little volume, that's really characterizing the market at
the moment,'' said one equities salesman. ``The institutions do
want to come in. If opportunities presented themselves, if this
market does come back a little more, then you will get some
buying.''
