<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Oregon-GasStations     05-02 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oregon-Gas Stations,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Rules May Force Station Closures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENDLETON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only gasoline station in the small
town of Echo, Ore., has closed and the same fate may be in store
for a string of others, a result of tougher federal regulations on
underground storage tanks.
   Dennis Gronquist, Arlington mayor and Texaco franchise owner,
said there soon may be no stations in the 160 miles between the
Eastern Oregon communities of Arlington and John Day.
   He said station owners and consumers are just beginning to feel
the effects of U.S. Environmental Protection Agency regulations
intended to prevent gasoline leaks from underground storage tanks.
   The EPA estimates 43 percent of all service stations in the
nation with underground tanks will close within the first five
years the policies are in effect.
   Gasoline station owners are being required to upgrade tanks,
install leakage detection devices and obtain leakage accident
insurance. Estimates of the cost range from $12,000 to $50,000 per
station, not including insurance.
   ``We're going to lose all our service stations because nobody
can afford it,'' said Herb Wright, owner of Wright's Chevrolet in
Fossil.
   But Ronald Moyer, a state Department of Environmental Quality
tank specialist, noted that leakage from underground tanks has
sometimes resulted in buildings being blown up or in contamination
of a city's water supply.
   ``Entire communities could be left without water if somebody's
tank leaked,'' Moyer said.
   Dave Barnett, who owns the only station in Ione, Ore., said
Congress and EPA are taking the wrong approach.
   ``I think these people are kind of like the ostrich. They hide
their heads in the sand and think it's going to go away, but it
isn't,'' he said.
   ``The town needs this service,'' Barnett added.
   In order to continue operating, Barnett said he'd have to spend
about $12,000 to install leakage detection devices on his two
underground gasoline storage tanks.
   Barnett also would be required to hold a $1 million insurance
policy.
   ``Quite frankly, it's not good. It's going to close a lot of
stations,'' Barnett said of the regulations.
   ``I think if I had more money, I'd drop everything I was doing
and go to Washington, D.C., and hound them until they hated me,''
Barnett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 0929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fairchild-Fasteners     05-02 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairchild-Fasteners,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Objects To Suspension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fairchild Industries Inc. says the
decision by the Defense Logistics Agency to suspend purchases from
the company's Voi-Shan fastener division was an unnecessary
precaution.
   In a statement Monday, Fairchild said it was surprised by the
DLA's decision to suspend Voi-Shan from new government contracts
because of allegations that the division's employees had falsified
testing data on aerospace fasteners.
   The suspension does not affect Fairchild's other federal
contracts.
   Fairchild stock fell 1] Monday on the New York Stock Exchange,
closing at $16. That's $1 below the price offered by the Carlyle
Group, which is seeking to buy the company.
   David Rubenstein, managing partner of the Carlyle Group,
declined to comment on whether the suspension would affect the
group's interest in Fairchild. ``We're studying it carefully,'' he
said.
   Voi-Shan fastener sales to the government accounted for less
than 2 percent of Fairchild's total 1988 revenues. However, a
source quoted today by The Washington Post said the suspension
could scare away commercial customers.
   The suspension comes in the wake of a widespread Pentagon
crackdown on faulty bolts. Several congressional and Pentagon
investigations have revealed that bad fasteners in all types of
military hardware and vehicles is a major problem.
   The Pentagon said former and current employees have told
investigators that they falsified test data when testing equipment
did not work, when tests could not be accomplished in the allotted
time, and when parts failed tests but management decided to approve
them anyway.
   Fairchild said that shortly after learning of the allegations,
it placed three Voi-Shan employees on administrative leave and
conducted an extensive review of inventories. Fairchild said that
no parts failure were found by Fairchild or its customers.
</TEXT>
