<FIRST>r f BC-Hammer-Sequel     05-02 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hammer-Sequel,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oilman Hammering Out A Sequel To `Hammer' At Company's Expense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Petroleum Corp., which usually
spends money to dig for oil, now is digging into the recent past of
Chairman Armand Hammer at a cost of $367,000, according to a proxy
statement sent to shareholders.
   The company is footing the bill for a sequel to the 91-year-old
industrialist's 1987 autobiography ``Hammer,'' with publication
expected next year, said Occidental spokesman Frank Ashley.
   ```Hammer' only went through 1985,'' Ashley said. ``This book
tells of more recent activities at Occidental and of Dr. Hammer's
activities around the world.''
   Ashley said the boss has had a busy 3{ years.
   In 1986, for example, Hammer helped pay for medical treatment
for victims of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant disaster.
   And last year, he stunned the art world by announcing plans to
build a museum for his $250 million art collection rather than
donate it to the Los Angeles County Museum of Art.
   Occidental has spent $255,000 so far for the book, much of it
for research and traveling expenses for writer Neil Lyndon, who
helped pen ``Hammer.'' The company expects to spend another
$120,000 to finish the sequel, the proxy statement said.
   Lest any investor worry about misspent funds, the cost of the
sequel represents a sound investment; ``Hammer'' so far has turned
into a literary gusher, earning more than $600,000 in royalties for
Occidental.
