<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-USX     05-02 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USX,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time For Bush's Lips To Move, USX Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 days into his presidency, it's
time for George Bush to make good on his promise to renew five-year
quotas on steel imports, says the outgoing chairman of the nation's
largest steelmaker.
   USX Corp. Chairman David M. Roderick said Monday steelmakers
count 225 sponsors in the House and 56 in the Senate _ a majority
in both houses _ for legislation authorizing the president to renew
the quotas, called Voluntary Restraint Agreements.
   ``This ... should encourage the Bush administration to publicly
announce its plan to extend the VRAs,'' he told shareholders at
their annual meeting.
   Bush said late in the 1988 presidential campaign that he would
renew the program, but has not said how long the quotas might
continue or what products and countries might be covered.
   ``We haven't heard from his lips,'' Roderick said.
   The quotas are scheduled to expire Sept. 30. The three-month
delay between orders and shipments could make the domestic market
uncertain and vulnerable to foreign predators, he said.
   ``If we don't have a clear definition of the VRAs and a clear
definition of when they're going to be extended, you're going to
find a lot of people in here trying to dump steel,'' he said at a
news conference before the meeting.
   Dumping is selling at illegally low prices, such as below the
cost of production.
   Roderick said USX nearly has finished preparing trade suits
against steelmakers in Japan, Germany, Brazil and most other major
steel exporting nations. The suits will be filed if there is any
gap in the quota program.
   USX said 65 percent of its customers support renewal, 25 percent
to 30 percent were indifferent and only 5 percent oppose it.
   The Bush administration should release terms of the renewal by
May, Congress should act by June, and negotiations with nations on
their individual quotas should begin by July 1, he said.
   ``Their extension for a five-year period is essential to the
continuing turnaround of American steelmaking,'' Roderick said.
``Failure to extend them would cast a cloud over our steel unit's
prosperity.''
   The quotas were intended to limit foreign steel to around 20
percent of the U.S. market, protecting hard-pressed American
producers from losing customers to predatory pricing by
government-subsidized producers overseas. The quotas fell short of
the goal in the first few years but are now on target.
   Meanwhile, Roderick announced plans to spend $240 million to
further modernize its largest plant, at Gary, Ind. The keystone of
the improvements will be a continuous slab caster designed to shape
1.6 million tons of molten steel directly into slabs, using less
energy and less time and leaving fewer blemishes in the steel.
   The new caster, planned to begin operating in mid-1991, will
eliminate 400 to 500 of the 7,500 jobs at the Gary Works, Roderick
said. Attrition will ease the effect of the cuts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
