<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-DetroitNewspapers 1stLd-Writethru f0028 05-02 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court To Review JOA; News Cheers, Free Press Glum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to add investor concern; INSERTS one graf after
the 7th, ``The mood,'' with union action; and INSERTS one graf after the
14th graf pvs, ``On the other,'' to add investor quotes.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Supreme Court decision to review the
proposed partial merger of Detroit's daily newspapers spread gloom
at the Detroit Free Press, but competitors at The Detroit News
cheered the ruling.
   The high court's announcement Monday that it will hear arguments
on the proposed Joint Operating Agreement set the stage for its
first review of the 19-year-old Newspaper Preservation Act. A
decision isn't expected until next year.
   Analysts said the wait will force Knight-Ridder Inc. to
determine how much longer it can absorb losses from its Detroit
Free Press. A major Knight-Ridder stockholder, the University of
California, said it will reconsider its investment.
   After being briefed at a staff meeting, Free Press employees
trudged back to work at telephones and computer terminals. For
feature writer Neal Rubin and others, the decision means more
uncertainty.
   ``We've been punched around so many times. It's like, `OK, we'll
waltz with it again,''' Rubin said.
   A few blocks away, at Gannett Co. Inc.'s News, most employees
oppose a JOA, said reporter Louis Mleczko, also president of Local
22 of The Newspaper Guild of Detroit.
   ``The mood today was just ebullient _ cheering and applause in
the newsroom,'' Mleczko said.
   He also said the union will press for new contracts talks. Amid
uncertainty over the JOA, more than 3,000 union employees at News
and Free Press have been without contract wage increases since 1986.
   The newspapers have sought since May 1986 to cut costs by
merging business, advertising and production departments while
maintaining separate news and editorial staffs. They would split
profits and losses equally for most of the 100-year agreement.
   The papers said the Free Press was in danger of failing. Gannett
said it would spend as much as needed to force the 157 year-old
Free Press out of business. Knight-Ridder said without the
agreement, it would close the Free Press.
   Then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the agreement in
August 1988, but challenges by the Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press and the Washington-based advocacy group Public
Citizen delayed implementation.
   No stay is in effect, and the newspapers would have the option
of merging while awaiting the Supreme Court's decision.
   Knight-Ridder's president and chief executive officer, James K.
Batten, said the organization continues ``to believe strongly in
the fairness and justice of our case on behalf of a JOA in
Detroit'' and will decide in coming days what to do next.
   ``Clearly, from their point of view, they would like to
eliminate the cash drain of the Free Press,'' said John S. Reidy,
communications industry analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert in New
York.
   ``On the other hand, if they wait it out, then they'll have half
interest in a JOA, which will earn considerably more for them than
the loss last year. So it is a tough decision.''
   ``There are some second thoughts,'' said Leslie Gallaugher, who
manages 2.1 million shares of Knight-Ridder stock owned by the
University of California. ``We're going to take a hard look at our
investment in Knight-Ridder.''
   The Free Press lost $18.5 million in 1988, Knight-Ridder said in
recent court filings. Gannett has released no annual loss figures
but has said the 115 year-old News lost $64.95 million from 1980
through 1987.
   ``It would be my hope that we would stay the course,'' Free
Press Managing Editor Heath Meriwether said. He acknowledged
employees are discouraged.
   Gannett, through spokeswoman Sheila Gibbons, said it was
reviewing the decision and would not comment.
   The Michigan Citizens' group argued that the newspapers' losses
resulted from struggles to force each other out of business rather
than conditions inherent in the Detroit market.
   ``We think that the tendency of these types of monopolistic
arrangements is negative,'' said State Sen. John Kelly, a leader of
the group.
   The Newspaper Guild first opposed the agreement, though it
dropped opposition in 1988 when Knight-Ridder said a JOA would mean
closing the Free Press.
   The newspapers say closing the Free Press would cost 2,200 jobs
while a joint operating agreement would mean a total of 600 to 800
jobs lost at the two papers.
   Gannett, based in Arlington, Va., is the nation's largest
newspaper publishing group. Knight-Ridder, headquartered in Miami,
is the second largest.
</TEXT>
