<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Autos 1stLd-Writethru f0046 05-02 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0046,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf pvs, ``Last month ...'' to UPDATE
with best first quarter in Big Three history, picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Chrysler,
whose ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said today its first-quarter
earnings rose 91 percent over the same period last year, when the
corporation's profits were dented by the closing of some parts
plants.
   The No. 3 U.S. automaker said it earned $351 million, or $1.50 a
share, during the first three months of this year, compared with
$184 million, or 83 cents per share, in the same period last year.
   Chrysler's profits came on first-quarter 1989 revenues of $9.95
billion, up 16.3 percent from its first-quarter revenues last year.
   The year-ago results included a $93 million, or
42-cents-a-share, one-time charge the company incurred from closing
some Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary's plants.
   Without the closings, first-quarter earnings last year came to
$277 million, or $1.25 a share, 26.7 percent less than
first-quarter profits this year.
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca said the company's share of the
car market dipped during the first quarter. But it maintained a
strong presence in the light truck market, especially in the
minivan segment, where Chrysler makes about half of such vehicles
sold in the United States.
   Last month, General Motors Corp. reported its first-quarter
earnings rose 42.2 percent, to $1.55 billion, or $2.37 per share,
over last year. Ford Motor Co. said that in the first quarter this
year, it earned $1.64 billion, or $3.44 a share, up 0.9 percent
from a year ago.
   The combined Big Three earnings made for the best first quarter
in the companies' history as they earned $3.54 billion, topping by
$324 million the first-quarter record set in 1984.
   Chrysler, whose earnings have been hit hard in the past by
incentive costs, was the last of the Big Three to jump into the
latest incentive pool, offering free financing on two-year loans
for all of its cars and some trucks. GM and Ford offer interest as
low as 2.9 percent.
   Much of the cost of those incentives will show up on the Big
Three's second-quarter balance sheets.
   Iacocca said the company benefited from sales of the Dodge
Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim, which replaced its compact K-series
cars, and in the more-expensive models. Also during the quarter,
Chrysler began two shifts of production at its Newark, Del., plant,
which makes the Spirit-Acclaim line.
   Meantime, Chrysler Financial Corp., the automaker's financing
arm, said it earned $65 million during the first quarter, the same
as the first three months of last year.
   The subsidiary's automotive lending operations, Chrysler Credit,
reported the number of new and used vehicles it financed rose 11.4
percent during the first quarter from the same period last year.
</TEXT>
