<FIRST>u f PM-AMR-Planes     05-02 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMR-Planes,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: AMR Considering Commuter Plane Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent of American Airlines is nearing an
announcement that it is ordering up to 100 commuter aircraft to
equip its regional airlines, a newspaper reported today.
   The Dallas Morning News quoted unnamed industry sources as
saying they believe Fort Worth-based American is leaning toward
Sweden's Saab for the order although the airline is still
evaluating different aircraft types.
   An announcement of firm orders for 50 aircraft and options for
50 more is expected within a few weeks, the sources told the
newspaper.
   American's parent, AMR Corp., would use the planes to outfit
regional airlines operated by its AMR Eagle Inc. commuter
subsidiary. Sources said the order has a potential value of $700
million to $1 billion, depending on the aircraft models ordered.
   American officials reportedly are also considering turboprop
aircraft produced by Boeing Co.'s Canada-DeHavilland Division,
based near Toronto; ATR, a joint French-Italian company; and Saab.
   But the News' sources said American favors Saab because of price
and partly because the Swedish manufacturer would have delivery
positions available earlier than the other two candidates.
   The new aircraft would be used both to replace older planes at
AMR's commuter subsidiaries and to enlarge their fleets, said
Robert E. Martens, president of AMR Eagle.
   American, since 1987, has acquired five of the commuter airlines
it formerly had marketing arrangements with. The carriers feed
traffic into American's hubs such as Dallas-Fort Worth.
</TEXT>
