<FIRST>r f BC-LawyersPublishing     05-02 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lawyers Publishing,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law Book Publisher Sold to Canadian Conglomerate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers Co-operative Publishing Co., a
leading publisher of law books in the United States, said Tuesday
it agreed to be sold to a Canadian conglomerate for $810 million.
   International Thomson Organization Ltd. of Toronto was the
highest of four bidders for the law book publisher, which was
founded in 1882 in Rochester by two attorneys.
   The buyout agreement is pending a vote by Co-op's shareholders.
   International Thomson, which had sales of $3.7 billion last
year, is a diversified company specializing in publishing and
information services that is controlled by Kenneth Thomson and his
family.
   Thomson also controls Thomson Newspapers Ltd., a chain of
newspapers in North America with a total circulation topping 3
million.
   The $810 million pricetag is four times Lawyers Co-op's 1988
annual revenue of about $200 million.
   Lawyers Co-op, with subsidiaries in San Francisco and New York,
has about 2,150 employees. Thomson's President W. Michael Brown
said no personnel, name or location changes are planned.
</TEXT>
