<SECOND>BC-Boeing Order,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Airways Orders $400 Million Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. announced Tuesday that Thai Airways
International has ordered eight Boeing jets valued at $400 million.
   The order for seven Boeing 737-400 jets and a 747-400 jumbo jet
is expected to be delivered by 1993.
   So far this year, Boeing has announced orders for 525 jetliners
worth about $28.4 billion, just shy of the record $29.7 billion for
636 jets ordered in 1988.
   Thai will be the first airline in Southeast Asia to operate the
737-400, a stretch version of Boeing's best-selling twin-engine
jet. The airline already has orders placed for two other 747-400s.
   Boeing's newest version of its 747 can carry 412 passengers
8,000 miles.
   Boeing has received 257 orders for 737s this year and 39 orders
for 747s. Airlines have ordered 2,521 737s and 922 747s since the
planes were introduced in the late 1960s.
</TEXT>
