<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PolaroidVsKodak 1stLd-Writethru   05-02 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid Vs Kodak, 1st Ld-Writethru,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Seeks Huge Damage Award From Kodak</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with start of testimony. Picks
up pvs 3rd graf pvs, Polaroid's lawyers ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. took great pains to avoid
competition with well-established Eastman Kodak Co., the Polaroid
chairman testified today as a court tried to determine how much
Kodak should pay for infringing on its rival's instant-photography
technology.
   Chairman William J. McCune Jr., the opening witness of the
trial, began outlining the corporate history of his company,
beginning with founder Edwin Land's quest for instant photography
in the 1940s after his daughter asked why she could immediately see
a picture her father had taken.
   McCune said throughout its history Polaroid had tried to avoid
direct competition with Kodak, the leader in the photography field.
   He said Kodak could have taken the ``bread and butter'' from the
Polaroid plate and the firm took pains to avoid a marketing
competition.
   In opening arguments Monday before U.S. District Judge A. David
Mazzone, Kodak argued that the $12 billion that Polaroid is seeking
in its patent infringement lawsuit against Kodak is greater than
all of Polaroid's profits from 1947 to 1987.
   The Kodak lawyers sought to portray Polaroid as a corporate
opportunist looking for a windfall from the 13-year-old lawsuit.
   Polaroid's lawyers, on the other hand, pointed to a Kodak
internal memo as evidence that the Rochester, N.Y.-based company
knowingly violated seven of Polaroid's patents when it began
selling instant cameras in 1976.
   They said Walter A. Fallon, who was then Kodak's chairman and
chief executive, personally reviewed the memo and jotted the words
``big block'' in the margin next to a paragraph about Polaroid's
patents.
   Kodak's lead counsel, Richard E. Carlton, did not discuss the
memo in his opening statement. But he argued that Kodak's foray
into instant cameras and film was based on advice from a New York
City law firm, Kenyon &amp; Kenyon, that turned out to be faulty.
   If Mazzone awards Polaroid anything close to $12 billion, it
will be the largest patent infringement decision in history, far
surpassing the record $207 million that Smith International Inc.
was ordered to pay Hughes Tool Co. three years ago for copying
drill bit technology.
   Whether Kodak violated Polaroid's patents is no longer in
question. A judge ruled in 1985 that Kodak had done so, and the
U.S. Supreme Court let that ruling stand Monday.
   The only issue in the current trial is how much Kodak's
violations hurt Polaroid and whether they were deliberate, which
would open the way to punitive damages.
   Kodak argued in its pre-trial briefs that the most it should
have to pay Cambridge-based Polaroid is $177 million, or 5 percent
royalties on the instant cameras and film Kodak sold from 1976
until 1985.
   Polaroid bases its huge damage claim on the grounds that Kodak
deprived it of billions of dollars in sales and started a price war
that forced it to sell some cameras below cost. In addition,
Polaroid contends that Kodak caused long-term damaged to the market
by portraying instant cameras as cheap toys rather than serious
equipment.
   Kodak contends, however, that its entry into the market actually
benefited Polaroid, because the millions of dollars it spent on
advertising and promotion increased demand for both brands of
instant cameras.
   The case was been divided into two portions, the first dealing
with whether Kodak violated Polaroid's patents, and the second with
financial compensation.
   The first portion went to trial in 1981 and resulted in an
October 1985 ruling by U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel that Kodak had
infringed some of Polaroid's most essential patents. On her orders,
Kodak quit the instant photography business in January 1986 after
losing more than $600 million.
   Kodak appealed Mrs. Zobel's decision, arguing that she had a
conflict of interest because her mother-in-law owned 1,000 shares
of Kodak stock. But a federal appeals court affirmed the ruling,
noting that Mrs. Zobel had told both companies in 1981 that her
mother-in-law owned the shares, and neither company had objected.
   The U.S. Supreme Court announced Monday it would not review the
appeals court's ruling, which means Mrs. Zobel's decision is the
final word.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoEngineers     05-02 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Engineers,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Seeks Broad Approach to Auto Fuel Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and the automotive industry must
intensify efforts to find new ways of fueling the nation's vehicles
if an oil crisis is to be averted in the 1990s, Sen. John D.
Rockefeller IV said Tuesday.
   ``We need to think systematically about what must be done by the
end of the next decade to displace millions of barrels a day of
imported oil with alternative fuels,'' the West Virginia Democrat
told the Society of Automotive Engineers.
   ``It is time for us to get on with the job of making the United
States energy secure again.''
   Rockefeller's remarks came at the opening of the society's
three-day conference on technical and regulatory issues facing the
automotive industry, including fuel economy, safety and alternative
fuels.
   The major U.S. automakers have built prototypes of cars using
alcohol-based fuels. However, efforts to promote such vehicles as
commercial products have been constrained by relatively cheap oil
prices during much of the 1980s and the lack of a national
distribution network for fuels other than gasoline.
   ``The assumption that we can become dependent on imported oil
because it is now cheap will become a very expensive assumption in
the long run. It does not take much imagination to envision an
energy crisis in the 1990s,'' Rockefeller said.
   Rockefeller said the government must avoid a narrow focus in
making automotive policy.
   ``We cannot assume that all the world's problems can be solved
just by regulating ... the automobile,'' Rockefeller said.
   Rockefeller said the Senate energy subcommittee on research and
development would hold hearings in June aimed at finding ways to
encourage the replacement of gasoline with alternative fuels, such
as methanol, ethanol and natural gas.
  
</TEXT>
