<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-02 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed lower on the London stock
exchange Tuesday as renewed inflationary fears and light buying
interest after a long holiday weekend combined to undo some of the
gains the market made last week.
   The trading session was one of the quietest since early January,
with volume amounting to 333.9 million shares.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 index closed 14.9 points,
or 0.7 percent, lower at 2,103.2, the day's lowest level but just
above the psychologically important 2,100 point barrier.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed at 1,736.3, down 14.1.
   The Financial Times 500-share index finished at 1,195.76, down
7.42.
   Dealers said the market was upset by renewed fears of an upward
drift in world interest rates, with much of the concern stemming
from Monday's release of a survey of U.S. purchasing managers which
pointed to still-buoyant growth in April.
   Those fears had receded last week, pushing the FT-SE 100 over 50
points higher during the five days.
   As well as international pressures, the British government may
also be forced to raise interest rates again for domestic reasons,
dealers said, especiallly if the pound comes under renewed downward
pressure.
</TEXT>
