<FIRST>r f AM-Carson-Bergner     05-02 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carson-Bergner,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bergner Is Inclined To Keep Headquarters In Milwaukee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of P.A. Bergner &amp; Co. said Tuesday he
is inclined to keep the department store company's headquarters in
Milwaukee after acquiring Chicago-based Carson Pirie Scott &amp; Co.
   Bergner and Carson announced the $453 million merger Monday,
which would create one of the Midwest's largest retail chains.
   ``We have always had ambitions of being a major player in the
Chicago market,'' Alan Anderson, chairman and chief executive
officer of Bergner, said at a news conference Tuesday.
   The combined companies will control more than 60 stores in
Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Minnesota and Iowa, and they will
have a single headquarters, Anderson said.
   ``We are inclined to leave the headquarters in Milwaukee,'' he
said. ``However, before we make a final decision, we will see if
there are significant business reasons for changing our position.''
   Bergner moved its headquarters from Peoria, Ill., to Milwaukee
when the company bought the Boston Store chain, which operates in
Wisconsin.
   But Anderson said officials made that decision because they felt
they needed to be more attuned to the Milwaukee market. Anderson
said Bergner already operates stores in the Chicago area, and ``we
know the market there.''
   Officials said the merger would have little effect on the
individual stores, which will retain their names.
   Anderson described the merger with Carson as an ``outstanding
fit,'' because the two retail companies cater to similar customers
and because their markets are adjacent to each other.
   ``This isn't like buying a chain spread out across the U.S.,''
said John Landschulz, a retail analyst with the Chicago brokerage
firm of Cowen &amp; Co.
   The two chains overlap only in one shopping center, at Randhurst
outside Chicago, and Anderson said no immediate decision has been
made on whether to close one of the stores.
   Anderson said, however, Bergner will sell off Carson's specialty
store operations, which include 391 County Seat casual wear stores
and 23 Arcadia novelty shops.
   ``We are a department store operator,'' Anderson said. ``That's
the business we know.''
   Bergner, owned by the Maus and Nordmann families of Switzerland,
had sales of $470 million last year. Carson had sales of $1.02
billion in 1988.
   Anderson estimated the merger would bring about $300 million in
debt to Bergner, but part of that money would be paid off through
the sale of the specialty stores.
</TEXT>
