<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Autos Bjt   05-02 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Autos, Bjt,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Up; Big Three Set 1st-Quarter Earnings Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s first-quarter earnings rose 91
percent from last year's depressed level, pushing profits for the
Big Three to a quarterly record, according to figures released
Tuesday.
   Chrysler said it earned $351 million, or $1.50 a share, during
the first three months of the year, compared with $183.7 million,
or 83 cents a share, during the same time last year. Revenue rose
16 percent to $9.95 billion from $8.56 billion.
   The earnings benefited by comparison with last year, when the
No.3 automaker closed a number of its Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary
plants. Those closings cut profits by $93 million, or 42 cents a
share.
   Without the reduction last year, Chrysler's first-quarter
profits would have been 26.7 percent higher. The company's profits
came on revenues of $9.95 billion this year, up 16.3 percent from
its first-quarter revenues last year.
   Late last month, General Motors Corp. reported it made $1.55
billion and Ford Motor Co. said it earned $1.64 billion, bringing
the Big Three profits during the quarter to $3.54 billion. That's
the best first quarter on record, topping the first period of 1984,
when the companies made $3.22 billion.
   Analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton of New York
said some of Chrysler's increase came because of lower incentive
costs during the period this year.
   In the past, Chrysler has used incentives liberally to entice
buyers. In very late March and early April, each of the Big Three
introduced new incentive packages, with cash rebates and low _ or
in Chrysler's case no _ financing charges on some loans.
   Much of the cost of the new incentive packages, which have given
a boost to car and truck sales, will be charged against
second-quarter profits.
   ``They're talking (a cost of) $800 per car versus $600 in the
first quarter,'' Phillippi said Tuesday.
   Chrysler's incentive package runs indefinitely, Ford's expires
May 31 and GM's runs out June 5.
   Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca said the company benefited from
sales of the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim, which replaced its
K-series compact cars, and in its more-expensive models. Also
during the quarter, Chrysler began two shifts of production at its
Newark, Del., plant, which makes the Spirit-Acclaim line.
   Iacocca also said Chrysler is holding its share of the
sport-utility market, through its Jeep line, and in the minivan
segment, where the company commands better than 50 percent of the
sales.
   ``Jeeps and minivans, that's the money pump,'' Phillippi said.
   Meantime, Chrysler Financial Corp., the automaker's financing
arm, said it earned $65 million during the first quarter, the same
as the first three months of last year.
   The subsidiary's automotive lending operations, Chrysler Credit,
reported the number of new and used vehicles it financed rose 11.4
percent during the first quarter from the same period last year.
</TEXT>
