<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher in Europe; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: An AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against most major currencies
in slow European trading Tuesday after the May Day holiday on
Monday. Gold prices were lower.
   Foreign-exchange dealers said the dollar was well supported
despite the lack of news to influence exchange rates. They said the
dollar held steady despite intervention by the U.S. and Canadian
central banks and most European central banks, which sold dollars
to drive down the currency's value.
   There were plenty of buyers around to snap up the offered U.S.
currency, the dealers said.
   Trading was slack because most markets will close again Thursday
for Ascension Day.
   One dealer in Frankfurt, West Germany, attributed the dollar's
strength to the weakness of the West German mark, the relatively
strong performance of President Bush in his first 100 days in
office and the steady course of the U.S. economy.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6845 late Tuesday,
unchanged from late Friday.
   Other late rates for the dollar compared with late rates last
Friday: 1.8875 West German marks, up from 1.8805; 1.6805 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6742; 6.3735 French francs, up from 6.3650;
2.1270 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1220; 1,379.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,377.50; and 1.1830 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1835.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 133.85 Japanese yen, up
from 132.49 yen late Friday. In London late Tuesday the dollar
traded higher at 133.82 yen.
   The late bid price for gold in London, the major market, was
$377.50 a troy ounce, down from $378.25 late Friday. The late bid
price in Zurich, Switzerland, was $377.30, down from $377.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $375.75 bid, down from
$381.85 last Friday.
   Silver bullion went slightly against the trend, trading late in
London at $5.65 bid a troy ounce, up from $5.63.
</TEXT>
