<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-02 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders reacted to
short-term weather forecasts calling for above-average rainfall.
   Wheat prices rose in anticipation of an announcement by the Bush
administration on whether there will be additional subsidized grain
sales to the Soviet Union.
   Wheat prices also were helped by word that the condition of the
red winter wheat crop in Kansas and Oklahoma has deteriorated
further.
   ``There was light volume,'' said Steve Freed, an analyst with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``The market is nervous about
the weather.''
   Lower soybean and corn prices followed the release of the
National Weather Service's 6- to 10-day forecast for
wetter-than-normal conditions next week in the Midwest and the
Central Plains.
   Soybean prices also were forced down by the selling of soybeans
by farmers taking advantage of Monday's rise in soybean futures
prices, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc. in
Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2} cents lower with May at $2.73{ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 3
cents lower with May at $1.84\ a bushel; soybeans were \ cent to 5
cents lower with May at $7.35 a bushel.
