<DOCNO> AP890502-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FactoryOrders Bjt   05-02 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Orders, Bjt,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Propelled by Demand for Aircraft, Orders Rise in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported Tuesday that orders to
U.S. factories for manufactured goods increased 0.7 percent in
March, but analysts still saw signs in the report that the economy
was cooling off.
   Orders for durable and non-durable goods rose to a seasonally
adjusted $232.9 billion in March after dropping 2 percent in
February and 1.2 percent in January, the Commerce Department
reported.
   The gain last month was propelled by a big jump in
transportation orders, which surged 10.1 percent on the strength of
a 48.3 percent increase in orders for aircraft, missiles and parts.
   Excluding transportation, a category that is subject to wide
swings depending on when big contracts are signed, all other orders
were down 0.9 percent in March after declining 1 percent in
February.
   Analysts said the report added to signs that economic growth is
slackening, but also demonstrated the economy still has some
strength left.
   ``I don't think the economy is as weak as some of the recent
signs have been showing,'' said economist John Hagens of the Wefa
Group in Bala Cynwyd, Pa. ``Calling it a full-fledged slowdown
right now is a little bit premature.''
   Hagens said that with aircraft manufacturers already holding big
backlogs of unfilled orders, the latest surge in orders in that
category was unlikely to have much immediate effect on economic
activity.
   He said the report showed some strength in orders for computers
and other equipment, while demand in construction-related
industries remained weak.
   Orders in the volatile defense category, which overlaps
transportation, also showed strength in March, rising 28.8 percent
after an increase of 19.7 percent in February.
   Excluding defense, all other orders in March were down 0.3
percent after falling 2.7 percent in February.
   Economist Robert DeFina of Security Pacific National Bank in Los
Angeles said the report was consistent with other recent signs that
the economy may be slowing down, noting that orders for non-defense
capital goods have fluctuated in recent months and that factory
shipments were down in March as backlogs of unfilled orders
increased.
   ``They all seem to fit in with this picture of a slowing
economy,'' he said.
   However, economist Robert Brusca of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. in New York said that while orders last quarter
were slower than during the strong fourth quarter of 1988,
manufacturing still shows enough strength that inflationary
pressures could mount.
   ``There's a little bit of a slowdown that's not worth a lot,''
Brusca said. ``I would still be concerned about the risks of
inflation here much more than the risk of recession.''
   The Commerce Department gave these details on factory orders in
March:
   _Orders for non-defense capital goods, considered a barometer of
business investment plans, were up 2.4 percent in March after
falling 7.8 percent in February and rising 2.3 percent in January.
   _Boosted by the strong demand for aircraft, orders for ``big
ticket'' durable goods were up 0.9 percent in March to a seasonally
adjusted $125.2 billion after falling in the previous two months.
Excluding aircraft, durable goods orders declined 3.6 percent.
   _Orders for non-durable goods were up 0.5 percent in March to a
seasonally adjusted $107.7 billion after dropping 0.4 percent in
February.
   _Shipments of manufactured goods declined 0.1 percent in March
to a seasonally adjusted $228.1 billion, after falling 1.4 percent
in February.
</TEXT>
