<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Disney     05-02 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Disney,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit up 24 Pct. in 2nd Qtr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co.'s profit rose 24 percent
in the second quarter of its fiscal year, thanks to free-spending
visitors at the company's amusement parks.
   Disney reported Tuesday it earned $149 million, or $1.08 a
share, up from $120.1 million, or 87 cents a share, in the second
quarter of its 1989 fiscal year. Sales in the quarter ended March
31 were $1.04 billion, up 14 percent from $774.5 million a year
earlier.
   Operating income from theme parks, which account for the lion's
share of Disney business, rose 43 percent in the latest quarter
because of higher per-capita guest spending, strong attendance and
improved resort operations, the company said. A new studio tour
opened at Walt Disney World in Florida this week.
   Operating income in the filmed entertainment division was 21
percent lower than in the comparable quarter last year, when money
was rolling in from the hit movies ``Three Men and a Baby'' and
``Good Morning, Vietnam.'' Revenue from filmed entertainment was 28
percent higher than a year ago.
   The consumer products division, which includes a growing chain
of shops selling Disney toys and clothes, recorded a 32 percent
rise in operating income.
   In the first half of Disney's 1989 fiscal year, profit was
$297.3 million, or $2.16 a share, up 35 percent from $220.6
million, or $1.61 a share, in the first half of last year. Sales
for the half were $2.08 billion, up from $1.51 billion a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
