   Prices were little changed in dull trading on
Wall Street today with many investors retreating to the sidelines
in anticipation of the government's April employment report, due
out later this week.
   ``It hasn't done much of anything today,'' said Jack Barbanel, a
market analyst with Gruntal &amp; Co. ``There was some support from
program traders, but the market by itself doesn't have enough
momentum.''
   The government reported today that sales of new homes fell 5.5
percent in March and that orders to U.S. factories rose 0.7 percent
last month. But Barbanel said the statistics also had little effect
on trading.
   Alfred E. Goldman, an analyst with A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc. in
St. Louis, said many investors were waiting for Friday's Labor
Department report, although it was not expected to radically alter
the market's perception of the economy.
 
