<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-02 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Slip; Gasoline, Heating Oil Down Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices retreated in active trading
Tuesday, reflecting market concerns about overproduction among OPEC
members.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, lost 86
cents to settle at $19.80 a barrel, after rising 24 cents on Monday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
June contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline settled 1.36 cents
lower to 71.25 cents a gallon. The contract had risen 1.39 cents in
the previous session.
   June home heating oil, which declined 0.31 cent Monday, fell
another 1.85 cents Tuesday to 47.61 cents a gallon.
   John H. O'Connell, an energy analyst at Refco Inc., said
profit-taking from the recent jump in crude and gasoline prices and
concerns about OPEC overproduction largely were responsible for
Tuesday's selloff.
   ``There's a growing belief that OPEC is producing 22 million
barrels'' daily, he said.
   The 13-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
agreed last year to a daily production level of 18.5 million
barrels for the first half of 1989.
   Quotas for the second half of the year are expected to be
discussed at a June OPEC meeting and analysts predict cartel
members will seek to expand production in light of the recent price
runup.
   Adding to the market slump Tuesday was speculation that the
transportation and production system in the North Sea would resume
operations next week following an April 18 explosion at a gasoline
platform that disrupted operations, analysts said.
   The North Sea accident and the Exxon oil spill off the Alaskan
coast in March have helped to significantly boost oil prices,
particularly gasoline and crude.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
