<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Kodak     05-02 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Kodak,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Up, Profits Down at Eastman Kodak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite record sales, Eastman Kodak Co.'s
fiscal first-quarter profit fell 23 percent due to costs associated
with last year's purchase of Sterling Drug Co.
   The announcement caught many stock analysts by surprise and sent
the photo giant's stock tumbling on the New York Stock Exchange,
where it closed down $3.12{ a share to $43.75.
   ``I was looking for an unimpressive quarter, but these numbers
are definitely lower than I and most everyone else anticipated,''
said Mark Obenzinger, an analyst for Wood, Gundy &amp; Co.
   For the quarter, which ended March 19, the company reported a
profit of $200 million, or 62 cents a share, compared with $260
million, or 80 cents a share, for the same period a year ago.
   Sales for the quarter totaled a record $3.9 billion, up 17
percent from last year when they were $3.3 billion.
   The earnings decline was largely a result of adding in three
months, instead of one month, of costs and interest expense for
Sterling Drug, which Kodak bought last February for $5.1 billion.
   ``That's a major difference,'' said Kodak spokesman Ron Roberts.
   For example, interest expenses in last year's first quarter
totaled $92 million. This year they were $192 million. Marketing
and administrative costs were $869 million. In this year's initial
quarter, they climbed $206 million, to $1.07 billion.
   Roberts also said less favorable currency-exchange rates and the
general cost of inflation contributed to higher costs for Kodak.
   However, Roberts noted that last year's first quarter was the
best in company history and this year's first-quarter earnings are
the third-highest.
   ``The first quarter rarely provides good insight into
performance expectations due to the seasonality of our business,''
said Colby Chandler, Kodak's chairman and chief executive officer.
   The first three months of the year are generally Kodak's slowest
time because people do not take as many pictures as they do in the
spring, summer and fall.
   Chandler said he still predicts the company will achieve record
earnings this year, but it's not going to be easy.
</TEXT>
