<FIRST>r f AM-IBM-Phones     05-02 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-Phones,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Enters Market For Intelligent Phone Systems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Tuesday it will offer a system that can identify incoming phone
calls and get information about the callers out of the computer.
   Other companies such as American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
already offer such caller-identification systems, but IBM has an
advantage in the market because of its close ties to potential
customers, a consultant said.
   Typical customers for such systems are stock brokerages and
companies that handle ordering and billing over the phone. With the
system, someone who takes a call simultaneously gets a screen full
of information about the customer's account.
   Similarly, a company could list one number in the phone book and
then route calls automatically to the closest office.
   In addition to CallPath, IBM also announced at a Dallas trade
show new controllers that serve as go-betweens for mainframe
computers and desktop terminals.
   IBM is so familiar with its customers that it can custom-tailor
CallPath to their needs better than other companies can, said
Francis McInerney, senior analyst at Northern Business
Information-Datapro in New York.
   IBM's long-range goal is to get a large portion of its revenue
from helping customers assemble customized information systems,
McInerney said. CallPath will help by creating a standard platform
to build on, he said.
</TEXT>
