<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices dipped lower in dull and directionless
trading on Wall Street Tuesday as many investors stayed on the
sidelines, playing it safe in advance of Friday's unemployment
report.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 12.10 to 2,402.86,
but most of the plunge was attributed to a 3\-point drop in the
stock of Eastman Kodak, one of the average's components. Kodak
closed at 43~ after announcing a disappointing drop in its
first-quarter earnings.
   Declining issues barely outnumbered advancing ones in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 720 issues
rising, 729 falling and 530 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 172.56 million
shares, up from 138.05 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 205.4 million shares.
   Prices moved in a narrow range for much of the day. Alfred E.
Goldman, a market analyst with A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc. in St.
Louis, described Tuesday's session as ``basically a dull day
correcting a market that had a big run-up'' and that helped relieve
the market's overbought condition.
   Goldman said the market's upward trend essentially remained
intact.
   The government reported that sales of new homes fell 5.5 percent
in March and that orders to U.S. factories rose 0.7 percent last
month. But analysts said the statistics had little effect on
trading.
   Goldman said many traders stayed out of the market, preferring
to see what Friday's Labor Department report on April employment
would hold. If the report indicates a surging economy, fears of
continued interest rate hikes could send stock prices lower.
   However, Goldman predicted, ``That figure will not really change
anybody's mind. The economy's not coming unglued and it's not
picking up steam.''
   Union Carbide was the most active issue on the NYSE Tuesday,
falling [ to 31\.
   Pepsico, which announced a favorable earnings report, rose 1[ to
49]. Boeing, which said it had more than $400 million in new
contracts, picked up 1\ to close at 78].
   Ogilvy Group, which soared more than $17 Monday after WPP Group
PLC proposed a $730 million buyout of the advertising concern, was
up a more modest | to 49} in over-the-counter trading.
   Another over-the-counter issue, R.P. Scherer, fell 3[ to 30\
after a Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc. unit agreed to acquire
the gelatin capsule manufacturer.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $5.990 billion, or 0.20
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped 0.45 to 172.37.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 1.16 to 354.61, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index declined 1.00 to 308.12.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
0.56 to 428.03. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 344.66, down 0.62.
