<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-02 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Mixed; Gold Weakens Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher against several key
currencies Tuesday, defying central bank attempts to dilute its
value through coordinated selling on foreign-exchange markets.
   Gold weakened slightly. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted bullion at $376.35 a troy ounce, down from $377.45 Monday.
   Currency strategists said the dollar's behavior reflected a big
underlying demand for the currency, a consequence of what they
called the resiliently strong U.S. economy and relatively high
American interest rates that make dollar-denominated investments
more attractive.
   They also attributed some of the dollar's strength to pent-up
orders for the currency overseas, where many markets were closed
Monday for the May Day labor holiday.
   The dollar fell early in the day when the Federal Reserve and
central banks in other key U.S. trading partners sold dollars to
blunt the currency's appreciation.
   But when traders realized why the dollar was falling, they
started buying it aggressively and the dollar rose again, finishing
higher against the yen, mark and French franc and nearly unchanged
vs. the British pound and a few other important currencies.
   ``The sentiment is definitely continuing to be bullish,'' said
Scott Greene, a senior dealer at the New York branch of
Switzerland's Bank Julius Baer &amp; Co. ``Unless the intervention gets
more serious, traders will just see it as an excuse to buy cheap
dollars.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 133.85 Japanese yen, up from
132.49 yen the previous session. In London, the dollar traded at
133.82 yen. Later in New York the dollar fetched 134.27 yen, up
from 134.13 yen the previous session.
   The pound cost $1.6845 in London late Tuesday, unchanged from
the previous session. In New York sterling rose slightly, fetching
$1.6806 vs. $1.6798.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. late Monday: 1.8919
marks, up from 1.8907; 1.6842 Swiss francs, down from 1.6870;
1.1812 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1872; 6.3950 French francs, up
from 6.3900; 1,383.25 Italian lire, unchanged.
   Other late rates for the dollar in London vs. rates Friday, the
previous trading session: 1.8875 marks, up from 1.8805; 1.6805
Swiss francs, up from 1.6742; 6.3735 French francs, up from 6.3650;
2.1270 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1220; 1,379.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,377.50; and 1.1830 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1835.
   Gold weakened slightly in U.S. and European markets after a
bigger decline in Asia. On the New York Commodity Exchange gold for
current delivery fell 40 cents a troy ounce to $377.80. In London
it fell 75 cents to $377.50 and in Zurich it fell 45 cents to
$377.30. In Hong Kong it fell $6.10 to $375.75.
   Silver bullion in London resisted the trend, trading at $5.65,
up from $5.63. On the New York Comex, silver for current delivery
fell 2.9 cents a troy ounce to $5.617.
</TEXT>
