<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-02 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharp Drop in Energy Futures Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices dropped sharply Tuesday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange as traders reacted to reports that OPEC nations
are exceeding their production limits.
   In other markets, grain and soybean prices dropped; precious
metals closed lower on light trading, and livestock and pork prices
rallied.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 35 cents to 89 cents
lower with the contract for delivery in June at $19.80 a barrel;
heating oil was 1.19 cents to 1.85 cents lower with June at 47.61
cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .42 cent to 1.36 cents lower
with June at 7.25 cents a gallon.
   ``It was a bloodbath,'' said Jerry Samuels, an analyst with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Prices dropped in active trading as traders who bought on the
assumption prices would go up liquidated their holdings as the
market broke the $20.50 barrier.
   ``There was no fresh news that would warrant such a move down,''
said Samuels. ``There is continued concern from OPEC
overproduction.''
   Word was that in April, Saudi Arabia surpassed its production
limit of 4.5 million barrels a day, with daily production reaching
4.9 million barrels to 5 million barrels.
   ``That is not so much, but there are reports the Kuwaitis _ who
have a million barrels per day limit _ produced 1.7 million barrels
daily,'' Samuels said.
   Gasoline futures were forced down by the selling of crude oil
futures, but overall, prices remain steady, said Samuels, adding
the fall in gasoline prices is likely to be more temporary than the
drop in crude oil and heating oil.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade as traders reacted to short-term weather
forecasts calling for above-average rainfall.
   Wheat prices rose in anticipation of an announcement by the Bush
administration on additional subsidized grain sales to the Soviet
Union.
   After the close of trading, the White House announced the sale
of 1.5 million metric tons of wheat to the Soviets under the export
bonus program. The wheat is for delivery in May and June.
   Wheat prices also were helped by word that the condition of the
red winter wheat crop in Kansas and Oklahoma has deteriorated
further.
   ``There was light volume,'' said Steve Freed an analyst with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``The market is nervous about
the weather.''
   Lower soybean and corn prices followed the release of the
National Weather Service's 6- to 10-day forecast for
wetter-than-normal conditions next week in the Midwest and the
Central Plains.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{ cents
lower with May at $2.73{ a bushel; oats were a \ cent to 3 cents
lower with May at $1.84\ a bushel; soybeans were 1\ cent to 5 cents
lower with May at $7.34 a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange with prices buoyed by better than expected cash prices.
   ``Traders hadn't expected it to be so strong,'' said Tom Morgan
of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Pork prices were helped by a Commerce Department ruling that
Canada was subsidizing pork exports and that may prompt the United
States to impose duties on Canadian pork products.
   Live cattle settled .18 cent to .60 cent higher with June at
72.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle was .30 cent to .65 cent higher
with May at 76.72 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .62 cent
higher with June at 47.42 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.10 cent to .88 cent higher with May at 31.75 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures prices dropped in sluggish trading on
New York's Commodities Exchange.
   ``There is a lot of gold and a lot of silver around, and there's
not a lot of reasons to buy,'' said David Syphen, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York.
   Gold settled 40 cents to $1.70 lower, with May at $377.80 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.9 cents to 3.2 cents lower with May at $5.617 a
troy ounce.
</TEXT>
