<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 1845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-TexasAir     05-02 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Texas Air,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Air Reports Quarterly Loss Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp., the nation's largest airline
company, said Tuesday it lost $255.5 million for the first quarter
of 1989, most of which was attributed to strikebound Eastern
Airlines.
   The holding company's loss for the three-month period came on
revenue of $1.9 billion and contrasted with a loss of $124.3
million on revenue of $2.2 billion during the same three months in
1988.
   Texas Air owns Miami-based Eastern and Houston-based Continental
Airlines as well as System One Holdings, an airline reservation
system.
   Eastern has been in bankruptcy protection from creditors since
March 9, five days after the start of a bruising strike by its
Machinists union that was supported by pilots and flight attendants.
   Miami-based Eastern by itself recorded a loss of $255.2 million
on revenues of $620.6 million before a $10.4 million charge for
dividends payable to its preferred stockholders. During the first
quarter of 1988, Eastern had a loss of $31 million on revenues of
$1.1 billion before a $14.1 million charge for dividends payable to
its preferred stockholders.
   Eastern virtually shut down operations March 4 when its
machinists went on strike and its pilots and flight attendants
honored the picket lines.
   Phil Bakes, Eastern's president and chief executive, said in a
statement that ``while further substantial operating losses should
be expected for the second quarter, the company's business plan
which was recently submitted to our creditors and 5,000 working
employees shows dramatic future improvements.
   ``Additionally, cash resources will increase dramatically as a
result of the planned disposition of certain assets that will allow
us to pay down substantial amount of debt, satisfy all bankruptcy
liabilities and finish the year with substantial cash resources.''
   Bakes said the airline's cash resources will increase
``dramatically'' from Eastern's new plan to rebuild as a smaller
carrier and sell $1.8 billion in assets separately.
   All such sales must be approved by a federal bankruptcy court in
New York. U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland has called a
hearing for Wednesday on the issue of auctioning Eastern in its
entirety, including its Northeast shuttle service slated to be sold
to developer Donald Trump for $365 million.
   Continental posted a first-quarter loss of $16.5 million on
revenues of $1.2 billion compared with a net loss of $80.6 million
on revenue of $1.1 billion for the first quarter of 1988.
   The losses at Eastern and Continental were partly offset by
profits of other units that do not individually report their
results, including System One Holdings, Texas Air said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
