<FIRST>u f AM-SunE&amp;P     05-02 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sun E&amp;P,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sun E&amp;P Becomes Oryx Energy; Plans International Expansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDISON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Exploration and Production Co. said
Tuesday it was changing its name to Oryx Energy Co. to reflect its
independence from Sun Co. Inc., from which it was spun off in
November.
   Oryx is named after a large antelope that has long, straight
horns that sweep backward. The name change was approved by
shareholders Tuesday and takes effect Wednesday.
   Oryx could spend as much as $2 billion to expand its holdings
internationally, Chairman Robert Hauptfuhrer told reporters.
   He indicated the company is looking mainly at possible joint
ventures in the North Sea, Southeast Asia, Africa and South
America. He said political policy and government turmoil in other
areas, especially the Middle East, make acquisitions there unlikely.
   Oryx has $4 billion in assets. It was created when Radnor,
Pa.-based Sun decided to spin off its exploration and production
business, and concentrate on refining and retailing. Sun remains a
large, mainly regional, refinery, distributing its products mainly
under the Sunoco brand name.
   Also Tuesday, Oryx announced the creation of a leveraged
employee stock ownership plan with initial funding form a $110
million, 20-year private placement of debt.
</TEXT>
