<FIRST>u f AM-ColemanFired 1stLd-Writethru   05-02 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coleman Fired, 1st Ld-Writethru,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Owners Fire Grandson Of Coleman Co. Founder As Chief Exec And
President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, James T. ..., with 1 graf to UPDATE with company
reax; picks up 10th graf, Coleman's severance ..., ^By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheldon Coleman announced Tuesday he has
been fired as president and chief executive of Coleman Co., the
maker of Coleman lanterns and other outdoor products that was
founded by his grandfather.
   Coleman said Wall Street takeover strategist Ron Perelman, who
bought the company six weeks ago, terminated him during a meeting
Monday night in Houston. Coleman said the decision was reaffirmed
Tuesday.
   Perelman and his staff had said they wanted Coleman to stay on
as chief executive officer. Perelman probably is best known for his
1985 purchase for $1.8 billion of the Revlon Group Inc. and his
acquisition of five failing savings and loans in Texas, a move that
gave him significant tax advantages.
   At a news conference, Coleman, 36, said he was told Monday he
and Perelman's acquisition corporation should part company because
he ``didn't respond enthusiastically enough or quickly enough to
some of their suggestions'' about his possible role on the new
management team.
   Coleman said each time Perelman's executives, whom he described
as ``extremely intelligent, fast-moving, hard-charging people,''
proposed duties for him, he asked to have some time to consider the
proposal. By the time he was ready to respond in each instance, the
suggested duties had changed, he said.
   ``The roles changed with each meeting we had,'' he said.
   ``I think they have tried to treat me well,'' Coleman said. ``It
is not a happy time for me. I'm extremely sad to be leaving a
company that has been part of our family for 89 years.''
   Coleman said Perelman's newly formed acquistion company, Lantern
Acquisition Corp., hadn't appointed anyone to succeed him.
   Charles McIlwaine, vice president of Coleman Co. corporate
communications, issued a statement saying the corporation's new
owners had decided it was time for a change in top management. The
statement said the company's ``current operating management'' would
be retained and a new chief executive officer would be appointed
soon.
   Coleman's severance package provides him a cash payment of
approximately $250,000.
   His firing leaves only one Coleman relative involved in the
company. Bradford Denning, the grandson of Sheldon Coleman's uncle
Clarence, is controller for O'Brien International in Redmond, Wash.
The Coleman Co. subsidiary makes water skis and sailboards.
   Perelman obtained resignations last week from the Coleman Co.
board of directors, except Sheldon Coleman. Three other Coleman
family members resigned board posts.
   The members of the new transition board all are officers or
directors in MacAndrews &amp; Forbes Holdings Inc., which is wholly
owned by Perelman.
   Sheldon Coleman said Tuesday his future as a board member still
is unresolved.
   Coleman Co. is the world's top manufacturer of outdoor
recreation products. It also makes home heating and air
conditioning equipment. Record sales of $657.9 million and record
earnings of $24.5 million were recorded in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
