<FIRST>u f AM-ContactLenses 1stLd-Writethru   05-02 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contact Lenses, 1st Ld-Writethru,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Contact Lens Said To Set Higher Standards Of Health, Vision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT that 3M will manufacture, sted market,
the lenses.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allergan Optical and Minnesota Mining &amp;
Manufacturing Co. Tuesday introduced contact lenses that the
companies said pose less health risk to eyes than any extended-wear
soft lenses currently available.
   The Allergan Advent lenses are designed to meet the eye's
critical need for oxygen, the companies said at a New York news
conference.
   The flexible material of the new lens allows virtually the same
amount of oxygen to reach the eye as when no lens is being worn,
the companies said.
   Reduced oxygen has been identified as one of key dangers of
overnight and long-term lens wearing. It can cause abnormal
swelling of the eye's outer coating, the cornea, and lead to
permanent vision-distoring eye damage.
   The Advent lenses, which will be available nationally later this
month, establish a new, fourth category of contact lens, which 3M
and Allergan Optical call Flexible Fluoropolymer. Existing lenses
on the market come under one of three categories: hard, soft or
rigid gas permeable.
   The new lenses also are designed to be more resistant to the
buildup of deposits, making them easier to care for. Deposits can
impair the vision-enhancing properties of lenses, cause discomfort
and possibly eye infections.
   The safety of extended-wear lenses has been the subject of study
and debate in the eye care industry for years.
   Last month Bausch &amp; Lomb Inc., the world's leading maker of
contact lenses, started to advise against keeping in its
extended-wear soft contact lenses for more than a week without
removing and cleaning them.
   Extended-wear lenses, which debuted commercially in 1984,
currently have government approval to be worn continuously for up
to 30 days.
   But the Food and Drug Administraion has said it is reviewing its
policy and the agency is expected to urge contact lens makers to
voluntarily shorten the maximum period for wearing their lenses to
a week.
   Allergan Optical, a maker of lenses and lens-care products and a
division of Allergan Inc., based in Irvine, Calif., has set seven
days as the maximum suggested wearing time for the Advent lenses.
   They are recommended for people who regularly wear lenses for
extended periods or occasionally overnight. The Allergan Advents
are expected to compete directly with disposable lenses, such as
the AcuVue lens made by a division of Johnson &amp; Johnson.
   The Allergan Advents, listed for $70 per lens, will be
manufactured by a unit of 3M.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890502-0302 </DOCNO>
