<FIRST>r f AM-Federal-Tigers     05-02 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Federal-Tigers,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOT Approves Federal Express-Flying Tigers Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department gave final
approval Tuesday to Federal Express Corp.'s takeover of the Flying
Tigers air cargo service on the condition that Federal give up its
U.S.-Japan small package service.
   Approval came after the White House indicated it would not
object to the acquisition, according to documents filed by the
department. The Justice Department earlier said it would not oppose
the $880 million deal announced in December 1988 by both companies.
   The acquisition gives Memphis, Tenn.-based Federal Express a
foothold in the international air cargo business.
   The department order considered several objections from other
air freight companies.
   It transfers the foreign certificate authorities of The Flying
Tiger Line Inc., also known as Flying Tigers, to Federal Express,
provided that Federal surrenders its certificate for small package
service between the United States and Japan, effective with the
start of service by a replacement carrier.
   The new certificates are issued both in the names of Flying
Tigers and Federal Express, giving the company the option of
operating under either name.
   Federal Express, which serves the United States with 104 cargo
jets and 137 smaller planes, established routes to Brussels and
Tokyo before acquiring Flying Tigers. It has 63,000 employees
worldwide.
   Flying Tigers, with 6,500 employees, operates 37 cargo jets and
two passengers planes, with scheduled cargo service to North and
South America, Asia, Europe, the South Pacific and the Middle East.
   The Flying Tiger Line was founded in 1945 by pilots who fought
with Maj. Gen. Claire Chennault's fighter group, the Flying Tigers,
which flew missions over China in 1941.
   Tiger International, Tigers' parent company, almost was forced
into liquidation in 1986 after a run of losses analysts blamed on
unsuccessful diversification efforts, high salaries and high fuel
prices. But employees agreed to take a pay cut. The company showed
a profit last year and paid employees $16.5 million in
profit-sharing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
