<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-LTV     05-02 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-LTV,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>LTV First Quarter Net Income Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp., buffeted by cost increases in aircraft
programs and a 25 percent decline in steel operating income,
reported a first-quarter profit Tuesday of $76.6 million, down
sharply from a year earlier excluding a one-time charge.
   In the first quarter of 1988, the Dallas-based conglomerate
suffered a net loss of $2.12 billion, but that period included a
one-time charge of $2.26 billion resulting from a change in
accounting for post-employment medical and life insurance benefits.
   Without the charge, LTV's income for the first quarter of 1988
was $131.2 million.
   First quarter sales declined, to $1.6 billion from $1.9 billion
in the first quarter in 1988. Sales results for the company's steel
bar division were being held for disposition.
   Sales declines in aircraft and energy products were offset by
higher sales in missiles and electronics.
   In releasing its first quarter earnings, the company said cost
increases are expected in its YA-7F aircraft development program
and higher unit costs are projected on production of Boeing 747
commercial aircraft components.
   ``The decline in first quarter sales and operating income
reflects LTV's continuing rationalization of steel operations and
the cost increases in the two aircraft programs,'' said Raymond A.
Hay, chairman and chief executive officer.
   LTV attributed the decline in steel operating income to the sale
last year of its Warren, Ohio, steel plant.
   ``Demand for flat rolled steel remained firm, most of our
facilities are operating at a high percentage of capacity and
orders are strong through the second quarter,'' Hay said.
</TEXT>
