<FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CNW-Japonica     05-02 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CNW-Japonica,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japonica Partners, CNW Trade Charges Over Takeover Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japonica Partners and CNW Corp., the hunter and
the prey, reported little progress Tuesday at a meeting between
representatives of the New York investment group and the rail
holding company.
   Japonica has made a hostile bid for CNW, and each said the other
was to blame for the outcome of a meeting Monday that was called to
evaluate the takeover offer.
   CNW officials said Japonica barred any progress in the talks by
refusing to supply more information about equity and debt
commitments that might affect its $44-per-share offer for CNW's
outstanding common stock.
   Japonica shot back, calling the three-hour session a ``phantom
meeting.''
   ``We have been informed that CNW's directors have not authorized
their advisers to commence merger negotiations with Japonica
Partners,'' Japonica said in a statement.
   Japonica holds 8.8 percent of CNW's 16.4 million outstanding
shares.
   Fredric Spar, a Japonica spokesman, said the meeting occurred in
New York, with attorneys and bankers from Salomon Brothers Inc. and
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. representing a special committee formed by CNW
to examine the takeover offer.
   ``Japonica Partners offered to enter into a merger agreement at
$44 within 72 hours, while permitting CNW to actively seek higher
offers both before the agreement is entered into and for a
reasonable period thereafter,'' Japonica said.
   ``It is incomprehensible to us that the board that one year ago
wanted stockholders to sell their shares at $31 now refuses to
negotiate in good faith our fully financed offer at a nearly 50
percent premium,'' Japonica said.
   CNW countered by saying representatives of its special committee
had attempted to work out a confidentiality agreement that would
give Japonica prompt access to CNW's management and private
information. The Chicago company said Japonica had been unwilling
to conclude such an agreement.
   CNW's principal subsidiary is the Chicago and North Western
Transportation Co., which operates a nine-state, 6,000-mile freight
system with 8,500 employees. CNW also has real estate holdings and
runs Chicago-area commuter rail lines.
   It earned $81 million on revenues of $995.4 million in 1988.
   Japonica said it would pare CNW to its core railroad freight
business and consider selling off its real estate, excess equipment
and commuter rail lines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
