<FIRST>r f BC-McDonnellDouglasCutback     05-02 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-McDonnell Douglas Cutback,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter Division Announces 450 Layoffs, More to Come</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Helicopter Co. on Tuesday
announced the planned layoff of 450 workers this month, with about
the same number to follow next year.
   President Bill Brown blamed the firings on a slowdown in attack
helicopter production.
   He said temporary and regular employees would be laid off,
including workers at plants in Mesa and Culver City, Calif., and in
all divisions.
   The helicopter division of McDonnell Douglas Corp. has 5,000
employees at its Mesa plant and 3,000 in Culver City.
   The company has been building about 10 AH-64 Apache attack
helicopters a month, but the Pentagon has ordered that rate cut
back to six a month beginning June 1990.
   McDonnell Douglas has delivered about 460 Apaches on a contract
that called for 975. But President Bush said two weeks ago in
unveiling his defense cuts that the Army now wants only 807, a drop
of 168.
   The division also builds the MD-500 series of light helicopters
and a variety of automatic cannons.
   The Apache suffered a major setback earlier this year when the
commander of the Army's 82nd Aviation Brigade at Fort Bragg, N.C.,
complained that it was unreliable. He said all 12 of the Apaches in
his unit were incapacitated at points during a war exercise, and
only five were in operating condition at the end.
</TEXT>
